  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When bilirubin's high but ALT's shy, Gilbert's is the guy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Gilbert's syndrome is the correct diagnosis because the patient presents with mild, intermittent jaundice, a family history, and liver function tests showing isolated unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia (elevated bilirubin, normal ALT/ALP). This classic presentation strongly points to a benign, inherited condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGilbert's syndrome is characterized by a benign, inherited defect in bilirubin UDP-glucuronyl transferase activity, leading to reduced conjugation of bilirubin. This results in unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia, which typically fluctuates and becomes noticeable during periods of stress, infection, or fasting, as seen in this patient's history of jaundice after a cold. The normal ALT and ALP levels confirm the absence of significant hepatocellular injury or cholestasis, distinguishing it from other causes of jaundice. The family history further supports an inherited condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Autoimmune hepatitis) (Incorrect): This condition typically presents with elevated transaminases (ALT/AST) and often conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, along with specific autoantibodies, which are not suggested by the normal ALT in this case.\nOption C (Hepatitis A) (Incorrect): Acute viral hepatitis, like Hepatitis A, would cause significant elevation of transaminases (ALT/AST) and often conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, along with acute symptoms, which are absent here.\nOption D (Hepatitis B) (Incorrect): Similar to Hepatitis A, acute or chronic Hepatitis B would typically show elevated transaminases and often conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, not the isolated unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia seen.\nOption E (Hepatitis C) (Incorrect): Chronic Hepatitis C usually presents with elevated transaminases and can lead to cirrhosis, which is inconsistent with the normal ALT and intermittent, benign course described.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Gilbert's Syndrome | Acute Viral Hepatitis | Autoimmune Hepatitis | Obstructive Jaundice |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Bilirubin Type | Unconjugated | Mixed (often conjugated predominant) | Mixed (often conjugated predominant) | Conjugated |\n| ALT/AST | Normal | Markedly elevated | Elevated | Normal to mildly elevated |\n| ALP | Normal | Normal to mildly elevated | Normal to mildly elevated | Markedly elevated |\n| Clinical Course | Intermittent, benign | Acute, self-limiting or chronic | Chronic, progressive | Acute/Chronic, often with pruritus |\n| Triggers | Fasting, stress, infection | Viral exposure | Autoimmune factors | Biliary obstruction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intermittent jaundice + normal LFTs (except bilirubin) + family history = Gilbert's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., ultrasound) would typically show normal liver parenchyma and biliary tree, ruling out structural causes of jaundice.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD Practice Guidance on the Evaluation of Abnormal Liver Chemistries (2017) recommends a stepwise approach to hyperbilirubinemia, distinguishing conjugated from unconjugated forms.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Autoimmune hepatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Gilbert’s syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Hepatitis A | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatitis B | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hepatitis C | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) The diagnosis is Gilbert’s syndrome, which affects some 2–3 per cent of the population. The clinical** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
