  "answer": "C) 3. C: Median nerve Median nerve injury at the wrist causes sensory loss over the thumb, index finger, middle finger, and radial aspect of the ring finger. The muscles of the hand supplied by the median nerve can be remembered by using the mnemonic ‘LOAF’, Lumbricals 1 and 2, Opponens pollicis, Abductor pollicis, and Flexor pollicis brevis.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the radius breaks, the median nerve often takes the hit.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is the Median nerve. A distal radius fracture is a common cause of median nerve compression or injury at the wrist, leading to the classic sensory loss described over the thumb, index, and middle fingers.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe median nerve is particularly vulnerable to injury in distal radius fractures due to its anatomical course through the carpal tunnel, which can be compressed by fracture fragments or post-traumatic swelling. Its sensory distribution includes the palmar aspect of the thumb, index, middle, and radial half of the ring finger, as well as the dorsal tips of these digits. Motor innervation includes the thenar muscles (Opponens pollicis, Abductor pollicis brevis, Flexor pollicis brevis) and the first two lumbricals, often remembered by the 'LOAF' mnemonic.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Axillary nerve damage typically results in deltoid weakness and sensory loss over the lateral shoulder (regimental badge area), not the hand.\nOption B (Incorrect): Lateral pectoral nerve innervates the pectoralis major muscle and has no sensory distribution to the hand.\nOption D (Incorrect): Musculocutaneous nerve injury causes weakness in elbow flexion and sensory loss over the lateral forearm, not the thumb, index, and middle fingers.\nOption E (Incorrect): Radial nerve injury at the wrist would primarily affect sensation over the dorsal aspect of the thumb, index, and middle fingers, and motor function of wrist/finger extensors, not the palmar sensation described.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Common Injury Site | Sensory Deficit | Motor Deficit |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Median | Carpal tunnel, distal radius fracture | Palmar thumb, index, middle, radial ring finger | LOAF muscles (thenar eminence, lumbricals 1&2) |\n| Radial | Humeral shaft fracture, Saturday night palsy | Dorsal thumb, index, middle finger web space | Wrist drop (extensors of wrist/fingers) |\n| Ulnar | Elbow (cubital tunnel), Guyon's canal | Palmar/dorsal little finger, ulnar half of ring finger | Claw hand (interossei, medial lumbricals, hypothenar) |\n| Axillary | Shoulder dislocation, humeral neck fracture | Lateral shoulder (regimental badge area) | Deltoid (shoulder abduction), Teres minor |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Distal radius fracture + thumb/index/middle finger numbness = Median nerve.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nX-ray confirms the distal radius fracture. Intraoperatively, one would assess for direct nerve impingement by fracture fragments, hematoma, or swelling within the carpal tunnel, and ensure adequate decompression if carpal tunnel syndrome is acute.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Distal Radius Fractures (2017). It recommends assessing for nerve injuries, particularly median nerve, in all patients with distal radius fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Axillary nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lateral pectoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Median nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Musculocutaneous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Radial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 3. C: Median nerve Median nerve injury at the wrist causes sensory loss over the thumb, index finger** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
