  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let your liver go on an African safari without its Hep A vaccine!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hepatitis A. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the patient's recent travel to Africa, acute onset of jaundice and hepatomegaly, and liver function tests showing predominantly elevated ALT (transaminitis) with specific IgM antibodies, all characteristic of acute viral hepatitis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAcute viral hepatitis, particularly Hepatitis A, is characterized by hepatocellular inflammation and damage, leading to the release of intracellular enzymes like ALT into the bloodstream, hence the elevated ALT. The elevated bilirubin reflects impaired hepatic uptake, conjugation, and excretion. The presence of specific IgM antibodies indicates a recent or acute infection, as IgM is the first antibody produced in response to an acute viral exposure. Hepatitis A is typically transmitted via the fecal-oral route, making it common in travelers to endemic areas, and it is a self-limiting infection that does not lead to chronic liver disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Hepatitis B, while causing acute hepatitis, often has different transmission routes (blood, sexual, vertical) and can progress to chronic infection. The IgM antibodies for Hepatitis A specifically rule this out.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatitis C is primarily transmitted via blood and rarely presents as an acute symptomatic illness; it is more commonly associated with chronic infection.\nOption D (Incorrect): Malaria, though possible with African travel, typically presents with fever, chills, and hemolytic anemia, not primarily with this pattern of LFTs and specific IgM antibodies for hepatitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Primary sclerosing cholangitis is a chronic, progressive cholestatic liver disease, not an acute infection, and would typically show a much higher ALP relative to ALT, without specific IgM antibodies for acute viral infection.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatitis A | Hepatitis B | Hepatitis C |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Transmission | Fecal-oral | Blood, sexual, vertical | Blood, sexual (less common) |\n| Chronicity | Never chronic | Can be chronic (5-10% adults) | Often chronic (75-85%) |\n| Serology (Acute) | Anti-HAV IgM | HBsAg, Anti-HBc IgM | HCV RNA, Anti-HCV (late) |\n| Vaccine | Yes | Yes | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute hepatitis in a traveler with elevated ALT and IgM antibodies points to Hepatitis A.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, acute hepatitis typically shows a normal or slightly enlarged liver with decreased echogenicity, often with a thickened gallbladder wall due to inflammation. No specific intraoperative findings unless biopsy is performed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) 2020 Practice Guidance: Hepatitis A. It recommends vaccination for travelers to endemic areas and post-exposure prophylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hepatitis A | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hepatitis B | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hepatitis C | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Malaria | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Primary sclerosing cholangitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) The history and liver function tests are characteristic of acute hepatitis, with a predominantly rai** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
