  "question": "For the equation described below, select the single best answer. [(2 × diastolic) + systolic]/3",
  "options": {
    "A": "Cardiac index",
    "B": "Cerebral blood flow",
    "C": "Cerebral perfusion pressure",
    "D": "Mean arterial pressure",
    "E": "Pulmonary vascular resistance"
  },
  "answer": "D) 9. D: Mean arterial pressure Mean arterial pressure (MAP) = [(2 × diastolic blood pressure) + systolic blood pressure]/3. Diastole counts twice as much as systole because 2/3 of the cardiac cycle is spent in diastole. A MAP of 60 is required to perfuse the coronary arteries, brain, and kidneys. The reference range is 70–100 mmHg.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 MAP: Your organs' average pressure, weighted for rest.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. The formula [(2 × diastolic) + systolic]/3 is the standard calculation for Mean Arterial Pressure (MAP). This formula accounts for the fact that the heart spends approximately two-thirds of the cardiac cycle in diastole.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMean Arterial Pressure (MAP) represents the average pressure in a patient's arteries during one cardiac cycle. It is a crucial indicator of organ perfusion, as it reflects the pressure driving blood flow to vital organs like the brain, kidneys, and coronary arteries. The weighting of diastolic pressure twice as much as systolic pressure in the formula is physiologically accurate because the heart spends a longer duration in the relaxed, filling phase (diastole) than in the contracting, ejecting phase (systole). Maintaining an adequate MAP, typically above 60-65 mmHg, is essential to prevent ischemia and ensure proper cellular function in critical care settings.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Cardiac index) (Incorrect): Cardiac index is cardiac output divided by body surface area, a measure of cardiac performance relative to body size, not calculated by this formula.\nOption B (Cerebral blood flow) (Incorrect): Cerebral blood flow is the blood supply to the brain, regulated by multiple factors including MAP, but not directly calculated by this formula. It's a flow, not a pressure.\nOption C (Cerebral perfusion pressure) (Incorrect): Cerebral perfusion pressure (CPP) is calculated as MAP minus intracranial pressure (ICP), indicating the pressure gradient driving blood to the brain, not solely by this formula.\nOption E (Pulmonary vascular resistance) (Incorrect): Pulmonary vascular resistance (PVR) is a measure of the resistance to blood flow in the pulmonary circulation, calculated using pulmonary artery pressures and cardiac output, not by this formula.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Parameter | Formula | Significance |\n|---|---|---|\n| Mean Arterial Pressure (MAP) | [(2 × Diastolic) + Systolic] / 3 | Average pressure driving organ perfusion |\n| Cardiac Output (CO) | Heart Rate × Stroke Volume | Total blood pumped per minute |\n| Cerebral Perfusion Pressure (CPP) | MAP - ICP | Pressure gradient for brain perfusion |\n| Systemic Vascular Resistance (SVR) | (MAP - CVP) / CO × 80 | Resistance to blood flow in systemic circulation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: MAP is the average pressure, weighted for diastole's longer duration.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, MAP is continuously monitored via an arterial line, displaying a waveform and a numerical value. A 'square wave test' or 'flush test' is used to assess the accuracy of the arterial line's damping, ensuring reliable MAP readings.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nSurviving Sepsis Campaign Guidelines 2021: Recommends targeting a MAP of 65 mmHg in patients with septic shock requiring vasopressors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cardiac index | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cerebral blood flow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cerebral perfusion pressure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mean arterial pressure | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Pulmonary vascular resistance | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 9. D: Mean arterial pressure Mean arterial pressure (MAP) = [(2 × diastolic blood pressure) + systol** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
