  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Size matters: Cardiac Index puts your heart's work into perspective!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question correctly identifies the definition of Cardiac Index. Cardiac Index is a crucial hemodynamic parameter that normalizes cardiac output to an individual's body size, providing a more accurate assessment of cardiac function.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCardiac Index (CI) is derived by dividing Cardiac Output (CO) by Body Surface Area (BSA). This normalization is vital because cardiac output requirements vary significantly with body size. A CI between 2.5 and 4 L/min/m² is generally considered normal, reflecting adequate tissue perfusion relative to metabolic demand. It's a more sensitive indicator of cardiac performance than CO alone, especially in patients with extreme body sizes or those in shock.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Cerebral blood flow is the blood supply to the brain, measured in mL/100g/min, and is not defined by cardiac output/body surface area.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cerebral perfusion pressure is the net pressure gradient causing blood flow to the brain (MAP - ICP or CVP, whichever is higher), not a ratio of cardiac output to body surface area.\nOption D (Incorrect): Mean arterial pressure is the average arterial pressure during a single cardiac cycle, calculated as (Systolic BP + 2*Diastolic BP)/3, and is unrelated to cardiac output/body surface area.\nOption E (Incorrect): Pulmonary vascular resistance is the resistance to blood flow through the pulmonary circulation, calculated as (Mean Pulmonary Artery Pressure - Pulmonary Artery Wedge Pressure) / Cardiac Output, and is not cardiac output/body surface area.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Parameter | Definition | Normal Range | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cardiac Output (CO) | Volume of blood pumped by the heart per minute | 4-8 L/min | Overall heart pumping efficiency |\n| Cardiac Index (CI) | CO normalized to body surface area | 2.5-4 L/min/m² | Heart pumping efficiency relative to body size |\n| Stroke Volume (SV) | Volume of blood pumped per beat | 60-100 mL/beat | Ventricular contractility and preload |\n| Ejection Fraction (EF) | Percentage of blood ejected from ventricle with each beat | 55-70% | Ventricular systolic function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Cardiac Index normalizes CO for body size, crucial for accurate hemodynamic assessment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nCardiac index is typically measured invasively using a pulmonary artery catheter (Swan-Ganz catheter) which provides cardiac output, and then calculated using a patient's BSA. Non-invasive methods like echocardiography or bioreactance can also estimate cardiac output, from which CI can be derived.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 ACC/AHA/HFSA Focused Update of the 2013 ACCF/AHA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure. It recommends hemodynamic monitoring (including CI) in select patients with advanced heart failure for guiding therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cardiac index | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Cerebral blood flow | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cerebral perfusion pressure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Mean arterial pressure | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Pulmonary vascular resistance | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 13. A: Cardiac index Cardiac index = cardiac output/body surface area. The reference range is 2.5–4 ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
