  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't delay, investigate that delayed haemolysis today!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Delayed haemolytic reaction. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic triad of anaemia, jaundice, and fever occurring approximately one week after a blood transfusion, which points to an anamnestic antibody response leading to extravascular haemolysis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDelayed haemolytic transfusion reactions (DHTRs) occur when a patient, previously sensitized to a red blood cell antigen (often from a prior transfusion or pregnancy), produces an anamnestic antibody response to transfused red cells carrying that antigen. The initial antibody levels are too low to cause an immediate reaction, but within 3-10 days, IgG antibodies (e.g., anti-Kidd, anti-Rh, anti-Duffy) increase significantly, leading to extravascular destruction of the transfused red cells by macrophages in the spleen and liver. This destruction manifests as falling hemoglobin, rising bilirubin (jaundice), and fever.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Febrile non-hemolytic transfusion reactions typically occur within hours of transfusion and are characterized by fever and chills without significant haemolysis or jaundice.\nOption B (Incorrect): Allergic reactions are usually immediate, presenting with urticaria, pruritus, or bronchospasm, and do not typically cause delayed anaemia or jaundice.\nOption C (Incorrect): Viral hepatitis has a much longer incubation period (weeks to months) and would not typically present acutely one week post-transfusion directly attributable to the transfusion event in this manner.\nOption D (Incorrect): Septicaemia (bacterial contamination) usually presents acutely within hours of transfusion with high fever, chills, and shock, and while it can cause haemolysis, the delayed onset and specific symptom triad point more strongly to DHTR.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Transfusion Reaction Type | Timing | Key Symptoms | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Acute Hemolytic | Immediate (within 24h) | Fever, chills, back pain, haemoglobinuria, shock | Pre-formed ABO antibodies (IgM) |\n| Delayed Hemolytic | 3-10 days post-transfusion | Fever, anaemia, jaundice, positive DAT | Anamnestic IgG antibody response |\n| Febrile Non-Hemolytic | Within 1-6 hours | Fever, chills, headache | Cytokine release from donor leukocytes |\n| Allergic (Mild) | Immediate | Urticaria, pruritus | Recipient IgE antibodies to donor plasma proteins |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anaemia, jaundice, fever one week post-transfusion = Delayed Hemolytic Reaction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nLaboratory findings would show a falling hemoglobin/hematocrit, elevated indirect bilirubin, elevated LDH, decreased haptoglobin, and a positive direct antiglobulin test (DAT) due to IgG antibodies coating the transfused red cells.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAABB Technical Manual (19th Edition, 2017) recommends prompt investigation of any suspected transfusion reaction, including serologic testing for delayed hemolytic reactions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Febrile reaction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Allergic reaction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Viral hepatitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Septicaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Delayed haemolytic reaction | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The patient is usually immunized to the antigen at previous transfusion, but\nthe concentration of th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
