  "question": "A diabetic patient with chronic, stable schizophrenia presents with a gangrenous toe which requires an amputation. He understands the implications but refuses surgery. Who is the single most likely per-son from the options listed from whom to take consent.",
  "options": {
    "A": "Patient",
    "B": "Partner",
    "C": "Surgeon",
    "D": "Psychiatrist",
    "E": "Judge"
  },
  "answer": "A) Even those ‘under section’ to receive psychiatric treatment cannot be forced to have a surgical procedure for a physical condition if they are deemed to be competent.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A sound mind, even if schizophrenic, still owns its body.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Despite having chronic, stable schizophrenia, the patient is presumed competent to make decisions regarding their physical health. Therefore, consent for the amputation must be obtained directly from the patient, upholding their fundamental right to autonomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPatient autonomy is a cornerstone of medical ethics, asserting an individual's right to make decisions about their own medical care. Even in the presence of a mental health diagnosis like schizophrenia, a patient is presumed competent unless proven otherwise. Capacity to consent involves understanding the information, appreciating the situation and its consequences, reasoning through the options, and communicating a choice. If a patient meets these criteria for a specific decision, their refusal of treatment, even life-saving, must be respected.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Partner) (Incorrect): A partner cannot provide consent for a competent adult patient. Their role is supportive, but legal decision-making authority rests with the patient unless the patient has designated them as a proxy or the patient is deemed incompetent.\nOption C (Surgeon) (Incorrect): The surgeon's role is to explain the procedure and obtain consent, not to provide it themselves. Obtaining consent from the surgeon would be a conflict of interest and violate patient autonomy.\nOption D (Psychiatrist) (Incorrect): While the psychiatrist manages the patient's mental health, they do not have the authority to consent for a physical procedure if the patient is deemed competent. Their role might be to help assess capacity, but not to make the decision.\nOption E (Judge) (Incorrect): A judge's involvement is typically reserved for cases where there is a dispute over capacity, or when treatment is mandated against a patient's wishes under specific legal frameworks (e.g., mental health acts for psychiatric treatment, not usually for physical conditions if competent). It's not the primary route for obtaining consent.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | Who gives consent | Key Principle |\n| :------- | :---------------- | :------------ |\n| Competent Adult | Patient | Autonomy, Capacity |\n| Incompetent Adult | Legally appointed proxy/Next of kin (best interest) | Best Interest, Substituted Judgment |\n| Minor (under 16) | Parent/Legal Guardian (or Gillick competent minor) | Parental Responsibility, Gillick Competence |\n| Emergency (life-threatening, no capacity) | Implied consent/Clinical team (best interest) | Best Interest, Necessity |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Competence trumps diagnosis; always seek consent from the patient first.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nClinically, gangrene appears as blackened, necrotic tissue, often with a clear line of demarcation from viable tissue. Intraoperatively, the affected digit would be visibly non-viable, potentially emitting a foul odor, and lacking blood flow, requiring amputation at a level with good vascularity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGeneral Medical Council (GMC) - Consent: Patients and doctors making decisions together (2020). This guideline emphasizes that doctors must ensure patients have the information they want or need to make a decision, understand the information, and are not pressured. It also details how to assess and act when a patient lacks capacity.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Patient | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Partner | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Surgeon | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Psychiatrist | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Judge | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Even those ‘under section’ to receive psychiatric treatment cannot be forced to have a surgical proc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
