  "answer": "C) Acral paraesthesia is a common manifestation of hypocalcaemia secondary to damage to the parathyroid glands.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tingling fingers after neck surgery? Don't forget the tiny calcium controllers!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Parathyroid glands. Injury to the parathyroid glands leads to hypocalcemia, which commonly manifests as acral paresthesia, presenting as tingling in the fingertips.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe parathyroid glands are crucial for calcium homeostasis, secreting parathyroid hormone (PTH) to regulate serum calcium levels. During neck surgeries, particularly thyroidectomy, these small glands are vulnerable to inadvertent removal or devascularization due to their close proximity to the thyroid. Damage results in hypoparathyroidism and subsequent hypocalcemia. Low serum calcium increases neuronal membrane excitability, leading to symptoms like paresthesias, muscle cramps, and in severe cases, tetany.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Phrenic nerve) (Incorrect): The phrenic nerve innervates the diaphragm; injury causes diaphragmatic paralysis and respiratory compromise, not finger tingling.\nOption B (Stellate ganglion) (Incorrect): The stellate ganglion is part of the sympathetic nervous system; injury typically results in Horner's syndrome (ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis), not finger tingling.\nOption D (Recurrent laryngeal nerve) (Incorrect): The recurrent laryngeal nerve controls most intrinsic laryngeal muscles; injury causes vocal cord paralysis, leading to hoarseness or aphonia, not finger tingling.\nOption E (External laryngeal nerve) (Incorrect): The external laryngeal nerve innervates the cricothyroid muscle, affecting vocal cord tension and pitch; injury causes subtle voice changes like difficulty with high notes, not finger tingling.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Structure | Function | Common Injury Symptom | Clinical Test |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Parathyroid Glands | Calcium regulation | Acral paresthesia, tetany | Serum Calcium/PTH |\n| Recurrent Laryngeal Nerve | Vocal cord movement | Hoarseness, dysphonia | Laryngoscopy |\n| External Laryngeal Nerve | Vocal cord tension (pitch) | Voice fatigue, loss of high pitch | Laryngoscopy with stroboscopy |\n| Phrenic Nerve | Diaphragmatic innervation | Diaphragmatic paralysis, dyspnea | Chest X-ray, fluoroscopy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Finger tingling after neck surgery? Think hypocalcemia, check parathyroids.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, parathyroid glands appear yellowish-tan and are often identified by their distinct vascular supply. Techniques like indocyanine green (ICG) fluorescence or rapid PTH assay can be used to assess parathyroid viability and function, especially during thyroidectomy or parathyroidectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Parathyroid Disease (e.g., 2016). These guidelines emphasize careful identification and preservation of parathyroid glands during neck surgery to prevent postoperative hypoparathyroidism.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Phrenic nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Stellate ganglion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Parathyroid glands | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Recurrent laryngeal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | External laryngeal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Acral paraesthesia is a common manifestation of hypocalcaemia secondary to damage to the parathyroid** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
