  "answer": "E) The deep peroneal nerve is also known as the anterior tibial nerve. It supplies the muscles of the anterior compartment of the leg, extensor hallucis longus, extensor digitorum longus, extensor digitorum brevis, peroneus tertius and, most importantly, tibialis anterior.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let your patient get foot drop; protect that deep peroneal nerve!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. The deep peroneal nerve, also known as the anterior tibial nerve, is the sole motor supply to the tibialis anterior muscle, which is a key muscle of the anterior compartment of the leg.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe deep peroneal nerve is a terminal branch of the common peroneal nerve, which itself arises from the sciatic nerve. It pierces the anterior intermuscular septum to enter the anterior compartment, where it innervates the tibialis anterior, extensor hallucis longus, and extensor digitorum longus. Damage to this nerve, often seen in compartment syndrome or fibular head fractures, results in \"foot drop\" due to paralysis of these dorsiflexors.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The saphenous nerve is a purely sensory branch of the femoral nerve, supplying sensation to the medial aspect of the leg and foot. It has no motor function.\nOption B (Incorrect): The femoral nerve innervates the muscles of the anterior thigh, primarily the quadriceps femoris, and provides sensory innervation to the anterior thigh and medial leg via the saphenous nerve. It does not supply the tibialis anterior.\nOption C (Incorrect): The tibial nerve innervates the muscles of the posterior compartment of the leg (e.g., gastrocnemius, soleus, tibialis posterior) and the intrinsic muscles of the foot. It is responsible for plantarflexion and inversion.\nOption D (Incorrect): The superficial peroneal nerve innervates the muscles of the lateral compartment of the leg (peroneus longus and brevis), responsible for eversion of the foot. It also provides sensory innervation to the dorsum of the foot, excluding the first web space.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Compartment | Key Motor Function | Key Sensory Area |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Deep Peroneal | Anterior Leg | Dorsiflexion of foot, toe extension | First web space of foot |\n| Superficial Peroneal | Lateral Leg | Eversion of foot | Dorsum of foot (except first web space) |\n| Tibial | Posterior Leg | Plantarflexion, toe flexion, inversion | Sole of foot |\n| Saphenous | N/A (Sensory) | None | Medial leg and foot |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Deep peroneal nerve = anterior compartment = foot dorsiflexion.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring surgical decompression for anterior compartment syndrome, the deep peroneal nerve must be carefully identified and protected as it runs close to the interosseous membrane. On MRI, denervation changes (edema, atrophy) in the tibialis anterior muscle can indicate deep peroneal nerve injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Acute Compartment Syndrome (2019) recommends prompt fasciotomy to prevent irreversible nerve and muscle damage, including to the deep peroneal nerve.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Femoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tibial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Superficial peroneal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Deep peroneal nerve | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The deep peroneal nerve is also known as the anterior tibial nerve. It supplies the muscles of the a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
