  "id": 140047,
  "question": "For each of the conditions described below, select the single best arterial blood gas result from the options listed below. Chronic renal failure",
  "options": {
    "A": "Metabolic acidosis",
    "B": "Metabolic alkalosis",
    "C": "Respiratory acidosis",
    "D": "Respiratory alkalosis",
    "E": "None of the above"
  },
  "answer": "A) 24. A: Metabolic acidosis Metabolic acidosis occurs when the body produces excessive quantities of acid or when the kidneys fail to remove enough acid from the body. If unchecked, metabolic acidosis leads to acidaemia, (pH less than 7.35) due to increased production of hydrogen ions by the body or the inability of the body to form bicarbonate (HCO3−) in the kidney. MUDPILES is a useful mnemonic to remember the causes of metabolic acidosis: • M – Methanol • U – Uraemia (chronic kidney failure) • D – Diabetic ketoacidosis • P – Paraldehyde • I – Infection, Iron, Isoniazid, Inborn errors of metabolism • L – Lactic acidosis • E – Ethylene glycol and Ethanol • S – Salicylates (aspirin)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When kidneys fail, acid prevails!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Metabolic acidosis. Chronic renal failure significantly impairs the kidneys' ability to excrete acid and regenerate bicarbonate, leading to a net accumulation of acid in the body.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe kidneys are central to maintaining acid-base balance through several mechanisms, including the reabsorption of filtered bicarbonate, the excretion of titratable acids (like phosphate), and the production and excretion of ammonium. In chronic renal failure, progressive nephron loss compromises these functions. Specifically, the impaired ability to excrete hydrogen ions and synthesize new bicarbonate results in a systemic acid load. This often presents as a high anion gap metabolic acidosis in advanced stages, due to the retention of unmeasured anions like phosphates and sulfates, or a normal anion gap acidosis in earlier stages due to impaired ammonium excretion.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Metabolic alkalosis is characterized by an excess of bicarbonate, which is the opposite of the acid-base disturbance seen in chronic renal failure.\nOption C (Incorrect): Respiratory acidosis is caused by hypoventilation and retention of carbon dioxide, a primary respiratory problem, not a direct consequence of kidney failure.\nOption D (Incorrect): Respiratory alkalosis results from hyperventilation and excessive excretion of carbon dioxide, which is also not the primary acid-base derangement in chronic renal failure.\nOption E (Incorrect): Metabolic acidosis is a well-established and common complication of chronic renal failure, making 'None of the above' incorrect.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary ABG Disturbance | Compensatory Mechanism | Key Cause in CRF |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Metabolic Acidosis | Low pH, Low HCO3- | Hyperventilation (low pCO2) | Impaired acid excretion, reduced HCO3- reabsorption |\n| Metabolic Alkalosis | High pH, High HCO3- | Hypoventilation (high pCO2) | Vomiting, diuretics, hyperaldosteronism |\n| Respiratory Acidosis | Low pH, High pCO2 | Renal HCO3- retention | Hypoventilation (e.g., COPD, opioids) |\n| Respiratory Alkalosis | High pH, Low pCO2 | Renal HCO3- excretion | Hyperventilation (e.g., anxiety, hypoxia) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Uremia equals metabolic acidosis; think MUDPILES for causes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, chronic renal failure often presents with small, echogenic kidneys. Intraoperatively, patients with severe metabolic acidosis may exhibit Kussmaul respirations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKidney Disease: Improving Global Outcomes (KDIGO) 2012 Clinical Practice Guideline for the Evaluation and Management of Chronic Kidney Disease. It recommends monitoring and managing metabolic acidosis in CKD patients, often with alkali therapy to maintain serum bicarbonate levels.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Metabolic acidosis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Metabolic alkalosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Respiratory acidosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Respiratory alkalosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | None of the above | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 24. A: Metabolic acidosis Metabolic acidosis occurs when the body produces excessive quantities of a** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
