  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Femoral nerve: Quads' best friend, knee extension's key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, the Femoral nerve. The quadriceps femoris muscle group, which includes the rectus femoris and the three vasti muscles, is exclusively innervated by the femoral nerve, making it essential for knee extension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe femoral nerve originates from the lumbar plexus (L2-L4) and descends through the psoas major, entering the thigh beneath the inguinal ligament. It then branches to supply the quadriceps femoris, sartorius, pectineus, and iliacus muscles, making it the primary motor nerve for the anterior compartment of the thigh. Its integrity is vital for ambulation, knee stability, and activities requiring leg extension.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Obturator nerve) (Incorrect): This nerve primarily innervates the adductor compartment of the thigh, responsible for hip adduction.\nOption B (Saphenous nerve) (Incorrect): This is a cutaneous branch of the femoral nerve, providing sensory innervation to the medial thigh, leg, and foot, not motor innervation to muscles.\nOption D (Tibial nerve) (Incorrect): A branch of the sciatic nerve, it innervates muscles of the posterior compartment of the thigh (hamstrings, except short head of biceps femoris), and all muscles of the posterior leg and sole of the foot.\nOption E (Sural nerve) (Incorrect): This is a sensory nerve formed by branches of the tibial and common fibular nerves, supplying sensation to the posterolateral leg and lateral foot.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Primary Muscle Group | Function |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Femoral | L2-L4 | Anterior thigh (Quadriceps femoris, Sartorius, Pectineus, Iliacus) | Knee extension, hip flexion |\n| Obturator | L2-L4 | Medial thigh (Adductors, Gracilis, Obturator externus) | Hip adduction |\n| Sciatic (Tibial portion) | L4-S3 | Posterior thigh (Hamstrings), Posterior leg, Foot | Knee flexion, ankle plantarflexion, toe flexion |\n| Sciatic (Common Fibular portion) | L4-S2 | Anterior/Lateral leg | Ankle dorsiflexion, foot eversion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Femoral nerve: anterior thigh, knee extension.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the femoral nerve can be identified lateral to the femoral artery and vein (NAVEL mnemonic) in the femoral triangle. On MRI, it appears as a distinct hypointense structure within the anterior compartment, often seen near the iliopsoas muscle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Regional Anesthesia and Pain Medicine (ASRA) Guidelines (2023): Recommends ultrasound guidance for femoral nerve blocks to ensure accurate placement and minimize complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Obturator nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Saphenous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Femoral nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Tibial nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Sural nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Quadratus femoris is composed of three vastus muscles and the rectus femoris. The femoral nerve also** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
