  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Below and lateral to the tubercle? Think femoral, it's crucial!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Femoral hernia. This question tests precise anatomical knowledge of hernia locations relative to the pubic tubercle, a critical landmark for differentiating groin hernias. A femoral hernia is uniquely characterized by its protrusion below and lateral to the pubic tubercle.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFemoral hernias occur when abdominal contents protrude through the femoral canal, an anatomical space located inferior to the inguinal ligament. This canal is bounded anteriorly by the inguinal ligament, posteriorly by the pectineal ligament, medially by the lacunar ligament, and laterally by the femoral vein. Its opening, the femoral ring, is indeed situated below and lateral to the pubic tubercle. The femoral canal typically contains fat, lymphatics (including Cloquet's node), and loose connective tissue, making it a potential space for herniation, especially in women due to a wider pelvis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Direct inguinal hernias protrude through Hesselbach's triangle, medial to the inferior epigastric vessels, and superior to the pubic tubercle.\nOption B (Incorrect): Indirect inguinal hernias pass through the deep inguinal ring, lateral to the inferior epigastric vessels, and superior to the pubic tubercle, following the spermatic cord.\nOption C (Incorrect): Obturator hernias protrude through the obturator foramen, deep within the pelvis, and typically present with medial thigh pain (Howship-Romberg sign), not as a palpable mass below and lateral to the pubic tubercle.\nOption E (Incorrect): Epigastric hernias occur through the linea alba, superior to the umbilicus, far from the pubic tubercle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hernia Type | Location Relative to Pubic Tubercle | Passage | Key Feature |\n| :---------- | :---------------------------------- | :------ | :---------- |\n| Femoral     | Below and lateral                   | Femoral canal | High risk of strangulation, more common in women |\n| Indirect Inguinal | Superior and lateral (deep ring) | Deep inguinal ring, inguinal canal | Most common type, often into scrotum |\n| Direct Inguinal | Superior and medial (Hesselbach's) | Posterior wall of inguinal canal | Rarely into scrotum, bulge with straining |\n| Obturator   | Deep pelvis, through obturator foramen | Obturator canal | Howship-Romberg sign (medial thigh pain) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Femoral hernias are below and lateral to the pubic tubercle; remember the high strangulation risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound or CT, a femoral hernia appears as a sac (often containing fat or bowel) protruding through the femoral canal, medial to the femoral vein and inferior to the inguinal ligament. Intraoperatively, it is identified by its distinct anatomical relationship to the femoral vessels and the pubic bone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEuropean Hernia Society (EHS) Guidelines for treatment of inguinal hernia in adult patients (2009): These guidelines provide recommendations for the diagnosis and management of groin hernias, emphasizing anatomical considerations for differentiation and repair strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Direct inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Indirect inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Obturator hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Femoral hernia | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Epigastric hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Femoral hernias pass through the femoral canal, which is below and lateral to the pubic tubercle. Th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
