  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Celiac trunk: where splanchnic nerves get their start!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Coeliac trunk. The greater splanchnic nerves carry preganglionic sympathetic fibers that synapse in the celiac ganglion, which is intimately associated with the origin of the coeliac trunk. This anatomical proximity makes them closely related.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe greater splanchnic nerves originate from T5-T9/T10 spinal segments, traverse the diaphragm, and primarily synapse in the celiac ganglia. These ganglia are strategically positioned at the root of the coeliac trunk, forming the extensive celiac plexus. This arrangement allows for sympathetic innervation to foregut derivatives supplied by the coeliac trunk, including the stomach, liver, spleen, and pancreas. Understanding this neurovascular relationship is crucial for procedures like celiac plexus blocks for pain management.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Abdominal aorta) (Incorrect): The abdominal aorta is the main vessel from which the coeliac trunk originates, but it is too broad and not the specific, close relationship.\nOption B (Aortic arch) (Incorrect): The aortic arch is located in the thorax, anatomically distant from the abdominal greater splanchnic nerves and their target ganglia.\nOption D (Superior mesenteric artery) (Incorrect): While also a major abdominal artery, the superior mesenteric artery is associated with the superior mesenteric ganglion, which receives input from the lesser splanchnic nerves, not primarily the greater splanchnic nerves.\nOption E (Inferior mesenteric artery) (Incorrect): The inferior mesenteric artery is associated with the inferior mesenteric ganglion, which receives input from lumbar splanchnic nerves, not the greater splanchnic nerves.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Artery/Region | Associated Ganglion/Plexus | Primary Splanchnic Nerves | Innervated Organs (General) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Coeliac Trunk | Coeliac Ganglion/Plexus | Greater Splanchnic (T5-T9/10) | Foregut derivatives (stomach, liver, spleen, pancreas, duodenum proximal to major papilla) |\n| Superior Mesenteric Artery | Superior Mesenteric Ganglion/Plexus | Lesser Splanchnic (T10-T11) | Midgut derivatives (small intestine, large intestine to distal 1/3 transverse colon) |\n| Inferior Mesenteric Artery | Inferior Mesenteric Ganglion/Plexus | Lumbar Splanchnic (L1-L2) | Hindgut derivatives (distal 1/3 transverse colon to rectum) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Greater splanchnic nerves target the celiac ganglion at the coeliac trunk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), the celiac plexus can be visualized anterior to the aorta at the level of the celiac trunk origin, often targeted for neurolytic blocks. Intraoperatively, the celiac ganglia are found bilaterally, often fused, surrounding the origin of the celiac artery from the aorta.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Surgeons (ACS) Surgical Education and Training Guidelines (e.g., ABSITE content outlines). These guidelines emphasize foundational anatomical knowledge, including neurovascular relationships, as critical for surgical competence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Abdominal aorta | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Aortic arch | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Coeliac trunk | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Superior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Inferior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 32. C: Coeliac trunk The coeliac trunk is closely related to the fibres of the greater splanchnic ne** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
