  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When liver cancer strikes, think AFP!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) because it is the most widely recognized and utilized tumor marker for hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC). Elevated AFP levels are frequently observed in patients with HCC and correlate with tumor burden and prognosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAlpha-fetoprotein is a glycoprotein produced primarily by the fetal liver and yolk sac during gestation. In adults, its production is typically suppressed, but it can be re-expressed by malignant hepatocytes in HCC. Elevated AFP levels are crucial for screening high-risk individuals, aiding in diagnosis alongside imaging, monitoring treatment response, and detecting recurrence. It also serves as an independent prognostic indicator, with higher levels often correlating with more advanced disease and poorer outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): CA-125 is primarily associated with ovarian cancer, not hepatocellular carcinoma.\nOption B (Incorrect): CA19-9 is a marker predominantly used for pancreatic cancer and sometimes cholangiocarcinoma, not HCC.\nOption C (Incorrect): CEA (Carcinoembryonic Antigen) is a general marker for various adenocarcinomas, particularly colorectal cancer, and is not specific for HCC.\nOption D (Incorrect): LDH (Lactate Dehydrogenase) is a non-specific marker of tissue damage or high metabolic activity, seen in many cancers but not specific for HCC.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Marker | Associated Cancer(s) | Clinical Utility |\n| :----------- | :------------------- | :--------------- |\n| Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) | Hepatocellular Carcinoma (HCC), Germ Cell Tumors | Screening, diagnosis, prognosis, monitoring recurrence |\n| CA-125 | Ovarian Cancer | Monitoring treatment response, detecting recurrence |\n| CA19-9 | Pancreatic Cancer, Cholangiocarcinoma | Diagnosis, monitoring treatment response |\n| CEA | Colorectal Cancer, Gastric, Lung, Breast | Monitoring recurrence, prognosis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: AFP is the classic marker for HCC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, HCC typically appears as an arterial-phase enhancing lesion with subsequent washout in the portal venous or delayed phases. Intraoperatively, HCC often presents as a firm, nodular mass, sometimes with a capsule, and can vary in color from tan to green depending on bile production.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Study of Liver Diseases (AASLD) 2018 Practice Guidance for the Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma recommends AFP as an optional component of surveillance for HCC in high-risk patients, alongside ultrasound.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CA-125 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CA19-9 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CEA | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | LDH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Alpha-fetoprotein | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Alpha-fetoprotein is often raised in hepatocellular carcinoma. It is the most widely used tumour mar** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
