  "answer": "C) Carcino-embryonic antigen (CEA) is the tumour marker of choice for patients with colorectal cancer. It is used for monitoring colorectal cancer, especially when the disease has metastasized.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CEA: Your colon's early warning for a comeback tour.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Carcino-embryonic antigen (CEA). CEA is the most widely used and established tumor marker for monitoring colorectal cancer, particularly in the setting of recurrence or metastatic disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCarcino-embryonic antigen (CEA) is a glycoprotein involved in cell adhesion, normally produced during fetal development. In adults, elevated levels are often associated with various cancers, most notably colorectal cancer. While not sensitive or specific enough for screening, its primary utility lies in post-treatment surveillance to detect recurrence, monitor response to therapy, and assess prognosis, especially in patients with metastatic disease. A rising CEA level after curative resection is a strong indicator of disease recurrence.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): CA-125 is primarily associated with ovarian cancer.\nOption B (Incorrect): CA19-9 is mainly used for pancreatic and biliary tract cancers.\nOption D (Incorrect): LDH (Lactate Dehydrogenase) is a non-specific marker elevated in various conditions, including melanoma, lymphoma, and germ cell tumors, but not specific for colorectal cancer.\nOption E (Incorrect): Alpha-fetoprotein (AFP) is a marker for hepatocellular carcinoma and germ cell tumors.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Marker | Associated Cancer(s) | Primary Clinical Use |\n|--------------|----------------------|----------------------|\n| CEA          | Colorectal, Gastric, Pancreatic, Lung, Breast | Monitoring recurrence, treatment response |\n| CA-125       | Ovarian              | Monitoring treatment, recurrence |\n| CA19-9       | Pancreatic, Biliary  | Monitoring treatment, recurrence |\n| AFP          | Hepatocellular Carcinoma, Germ Cell Tumors | Diagnosis, monitoring treatment, recurrence |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CEA for CRC surveillance, not screening.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT imaging, a rising CEA in a patient with colorectal cancer history would prompt a search for new or growing lesions, particularly in the liver or lungs, which are common sites for metastatic disease. Intraoperatively, elevated CEA might guide a more aggressive search for occult metastases or indicate the need for more extensive lymphadenectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Colon Cancer (Version 1.2024) recommend CEA levels be obtained every 3-6 months for at least 2 years post-resection for Stage II and III disease, and then annually for up to 5 years, as part of surveillance for recurrence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CA-125 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CA19-9 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | CEA | ✅ Correct |\n| D | LDH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Alpha-fetoprotein | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Carcino-embryonic antigen (CEA) is the tumour marker of choice for patients with colorectal cancer. ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
