  "question": "A 52-year-old woman presents with a rapidly worsening cough, haemoptysis, and shortness of breath at rest. Her chest radio-graph demonstrates mediastinal gland enlargement. Her blood tests reveal hypercalcaemia. Please select the best diagnosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Mesothelioma",
    "B": "Pancoast tumour",
    "C": "Small cell carcinoma",
    "D": "Secondary lung tumour",
    "E": "Squamous cell carcinoma"
  },
  "answer": "C) 34. C: Small cell carcinoma Small-cell carcinoma (also known as ‘small-cell lung cancer’, or ‘oat-cell carcinoma’) is a type of highly malignant cancer that most commonly arises within the lung. Compared to non-small cell carcinoma, small cell carcinoma has a more aggressive course: a shorter doubling time, higher growth fraction, and earlier development of metastases. These tumours are often associated with ectopic hormone production and paraneoplastic syndromes.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small cell: rapid, rampant, and paraneoplastic.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct diagnosis is Small Cell Carcinoma. This aggressive lung cancer is characterized by rapid progression, early mediastinal involvement, and a strong association with paraneoplastic syndromes, which explains the patient's hypercalcaemia and rapidly worsening symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSmall cell carcinoma (SCLC) is a highly malignant neuroendocrine tumor of the lung, known for its extremely rapid doubling time and early, widespread metastasis, particularly to regional lymph nodes and distant sites. Its aggressive nature aligns with the 'rapidly worsening' symptoms and 'mediastinal gland enlargement' described. SCLC is notorious for its association with various paraneoplastic syndromes due to ectopic hormone production, including SIADH, Cushing's syndrome, and less commonly, hypercalcaemia (though more classically associated with squamous cell carcinoma, SCLC can also cause it via PTHrP or bone metastases). The combination of rapid progression, extensive mediastinal disease, and a paraneoplastic syndrome strongly points to SCLC.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Mesothelioma) (Incorrect): Mesothelioma is a tumor of the pleura, not typically presenting with mediastinal gland enlargement as a primary feature, and hypercalcaemia is not a classic paraneoplastic syndrome associated with it.\nOption B (Pancoast tumour) (Incorrect): A Pancoast tumor is a specific type of apical lung tumor causing shoulder pain and Horner's syndrome due to invasion of the brachial plexus and sympathetic chain. While it is a lung cancer, it does not typically present with prominent mediastinal gland enlargement or hypercalcaemia as its defining features.\nOption D (Secondary lung tumour) (Incorrect): While possible, 'secondary lung tumour' is a descriptive term for metastasis and not a primary diagnosis. It doesn't explain the specific constellation of symptoms and paraneoplastic syndrome as well as a primary lung cancer type.\nOption E (Squamous cell carcinoma) (Incorrect): Squamous cell carcinoma is indeed strongly associated with hypercalcaemia due to PTHrP production. However, the 'rapidly worsening' nature and extensive 'mediastinal gland enlargement' are often more characteristic of the highly aggressive and rapidly metastasizing small cell carcinoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Small Cell Carcinoma | Squamous Cell Carcinoma | Adenocarcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Growth Rate | Very rapid | Moderate | Moderate |\n| Metastasis | Early, widespread (mediastinal, distant) | Regional, later distant | Early, distant |\n| Paraneoplastic Syndromes | SIADH, Cushing's, Lambert-Eaton, *can cause hypercalcemia* | Hypercalcemia (PTHrP) | Hypertrophic osteoarthropathy |\n| Location | Central | Central | Peripheral |\n| Association | Strongest with smoking | Strong with smoking | Less with smoking, common in non-smokers |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rapidly progressive lung symptoms + mediastinal nodes + paraneoplastic syndrome = think SCLC.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, expect a large central mass with extensive mediastinal and hilar lymphadenopathy. Intraoperatively, the tumor would appear friable and often unresectable due to widespread involvement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Small Cell Lung Cancer (latest version). These guidelines recommend systemic therapy (chemotherapy with or without radiation) as the primary treatment due to its aggressive nature and early metastasis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mesothelioma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Pancoast tumour | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Small cell carcinoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Secondary lung tumour | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Squamous cell carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 34. C: Small cell carcinoma Small-cell carcinoma (also known as ‘small-cell lung cancer’, or ‘oat-ce** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
