  "question": "Select the appropriate hormone that the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex secretes?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Adrenaline",
    "B": "Aldosterone",
    "C": "Cortisol",
    "D": "Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA)",
    "E": "Renin"
  },
  "answer": "C) 35. C: Cortisol Zona fasciculata is responsible for producing glucocorticoids, including 11-deoxycorticosterone, corticosterone, and cortisol. Cortisol is the main glucocorticoid under normal conditions and its actions include mobilization of fats, proteins, and carbohydrates. Moreover, cortisol enhances the activity of other hormones including glucagon and catecholamines. The zona fasciculata secretes a basal level of cortisol but can also produce bursts of the hormone in response to adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) release from the anterior pituitary gland.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fasciculata makes the \"sugar\" hormone, Cortisol – sweet!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cortisol because the zona fasciculata is the primary site within the adrenal cortex responsible for producing glucocorticoids. Cortisol is the main glucocorticoid under normal physiological conditions, playing a critical role in metabolic regulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe zona fasciculata is uniquely adapted for glucocorticoid synthesis, primarily cortisol, which plays a crucial role in metabolism by mobilizing fats, proteins, and carbohydrates. Its actions are vital for maintaining glucose homeostasis and enhancing the effects of other hormones like glucagon and catecholamines. Cortisol secretion from this zone is tightly regulated by the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis, with adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) from the anterior pituitary stimulating both basal and stress-induced bursts of hormone release.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Adrenaline is secreted by the adrenal medulla, not the adrenal cortex.\nOption B (Incorrect): Aldosterone is a mineralocorticoid primarily secreted by the zona glomerulosa, the outermost layer of the adrenal cortex.\nOption D (Incorrect): Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) is an androgen primarily secreted by the zona reticularis, the innermost layer of the adrenal cortex.\nOption E (Incorrect): Renin is an enzyme secreted by the juxtaglomerular cells of the kidney, not by the adrenal gland.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Layer | Primary Hormone Class | Key Hormone(s) | Function |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Zona Glomerulosa | Mineralocorticoids | Aldosterone | Electrolyte balance, blood pressure regulation |\n| Zona Fasciculata | Glucocorticoids | Cortisol | Glucose metabolism, stress response, anti-inflammatory |\n| Zona Reticularis | Androgens | DHEA, Androstenedione | Sex hormone precursors |\n| Adrenal Medulla | Catecholamines | Adrenaline, Noradrenaline | \"Fight or flight\" response |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adrenal cortex layers: GFR - Salt, Sugar, Sex.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, an adrenal mass (adenoma, carcinoma) originating from the zona fasciculata might appear as a well-circumscribed or irregular lesion within the adrenal gland, potentially causing Cushing's syndrome symptoms. Intraoperatively, the adrenal gland is typically identified superior to the kidney, and the overall gland size and presence of masses are assessed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Clinical Endocrinologists (AACE) and American Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Medical and Surgical Guidelines for Patients with Adrenal Incidentalomas (2023). These guidelines recommend evaluation for hormonal overproduction, including cortisol, in patients with incidentally discovered adrenal masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adrenaline | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Aldosterone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cortisol | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Renin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 35. C: Cortisol Zona fasciculata is responsible for producing glucocorticoids, including 11-deoxycor** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
