  "answer": "C) The diaphragm’s motor innervation is obtained from the phrenic nerve (C3, 4, 5). This nerve also conveys sensation to the central portion of the diaphragm, but the lower six intercostals nerves supply sensation to the periphery. The following relate to structures passing through the diaphragm at specific vertebral levels:\n• T8: Right phrenic nerve, inferior vena cava\n• T10: Vagus nerve, left gastric vein/artery, oesophagus\n• T12: Azygous vein, aorta, thoracic duct\nThe left phrenic nerve pieces the central tendon.",
