  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 IgG: The complex culprit in Type III's inflammatory assault!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Immunoglobulin G (IgG). Type III hypersensitivity reactions are characterized by the formation and deposition of immune complexes, primarily involving IgG antibodies, which then trigger an inflammatory response.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nType III hypersensitivity, also known as immune complex-mediated hypersensitivity, occurs when IgG antibodies bind to soluble antigens, forming circulating immune complexes. These complexes can deposit in various tissues, such as blood vessel walls, glomeruli, or joints. Once deposited, they activate the complement system and attract inflammatory cells like neutrophils, leading to tissue damage through the release of lysosomal enzymes and reactive oxygen species. Classic examples include systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE), rheumatoid arthritis (RA), and serum sickness, all driven by persistent immune complex formation and deposition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Helper T cells 4 (CD4+ T cells) are crucial in orchestrating immune responses, but they are the primary mediators of Type IV (delayed-type) hypersensitivity, not Type III.\nOption B (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin A (IgA) is predominantly found in mucosal secretions and plays a key role in mucosal immunity, but it is not the primary antibody mediator of Type III hypersensitivity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin D (IgD) is found on the surface of B cells and is involved in B cell activation, but its role in hypersensitivity reactions is not well-defined, and it is not a mediator of Type III.\nOption D (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin E (IgE) is the primary antibody responsible for Type I (immediate) hypersensitivity reactions, such as allergies and anaphylaxis, by binding to mast cells and basophils.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hypersensitivity Type | Mediator | Mechanism | Examples |\n|----------------------|----------|-----------|----------|\n| Type I (Immediate)   | IgE      | Mast cell degranulation, histamine release | Anaphylaxis, allergic asthma, hay fever |\n| Type II (Cytotoxic)  | IgG, IgM | Antibody-mediated cell destruction (complement, ADCC) | Hemolytic anemia, Goodpasture's syndrome |\n| Type III (Immune Complex) | IgG, IgM | Immune complex deposition, complement activation | SLE, RA, serum sickness |\n| Type IV (Delayed)    | T cells  | T-cell mediated inflammation, macrophage activation | Contact dermatitis, TB skin test, transplant rejection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Type III hypersensitivity = IgG + soluble antigen = immune complexes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn Type III conditions like SLE or RA, imaging (X-ray, MRI) might reveal joint erosions, synovitis, or effusions. In vasculitis (a manifestation of immune complex deposition), angiography might show vessel narrowing or aneurysms.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) Guidelines for the Management of Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (2019) recommend targeted immunosuppressive therapies to reduce immune complex formation and inflammation.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Helper T cells 4 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Immunoglobulin A | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Immunoglobulin D | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Immunoglobulin E | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Immunoglobulin G | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 38. E: Immunoglobulin G Type III hypersensitivity reaction occurs when there is accumulation of immu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
