  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 T-cells take their sweet time for Type IV.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Helper T cells because Type IV hypersensitivity is a cell-mediated immune response, distinct from the antibody-mediated reactions of other hypersensitivity types. Helper T cells, specifically CD4+ Th1 cells, are the primary orchestrators of this delayed-type hypersensitivity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nType IV hypersensitivity, also known as delayed-type hypersensitivity (DTH), is unique among the hypersensitivity reactions as it does not involve antibodies. Instead, it is driven by T lymphocytes. CD4+ Th1 helper T cells are activated upon recognizing specific antigens presented by antigen-presenting cells (APCs) via MHC class II molecules. These activated T cells then release cytokines that recruit and activate macrophages and other inflammatory cells, leading to tissue damage and inflammation that typically manifests 24-72 hours after antigen exposure. Examples include contact dermatitis, the tuberculin skin test (Mantoux test), and chronic transplant rejection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin A (IgA) is an antibody primarily found in mucosal secretions and is not involved in Type IV hypersensitivity.\nOption C (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin D (IgD) is an antibody found on the surface of B cells and its exact role in hypersensitivity is not well-defined, but it is not a mediator of Type IV reactions.\nOption D (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin E (IgE) is an antibody central to Type I (immediate) hypersensitivity reactions, mediating allergic responses like anaphylaxis. It is not involved in Type IV.\nOption E (Incorrect): Immunoglobulin G (IgG) is the most abundant antibody and is involved in Type II (cytotoxic) and Type III (immune complex) hypersensitivity reactions, but not Type IV.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hypersensitivity Type | Mediator | Mechanism | Examples |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Type I (Anaphylactic) | IgE | Mast cell degranulation | Allergic rhinitis, Anaphylaxis |\n| Type II (Cytotoxic) | IgG, IgM | Antibody-mediated cell destruction | Hemolytic transfusion reactions, Autoimmune hemolytic anemia |\n| Type III (Immune Complex) | IgG, IgM | Immune complex deposition | Serum sickness, Lupus nephritis |\n| Type IV (Delayed-Type) | T cells (Th1) | Cell-mediated, cytokine release | Contact dermatitis, Mantoux test, Chronic transplant rejection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Type IV is T-cell mediated, not antibody-mediated.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor a positive Mantoux test, you would observe an indurated (hardened) and erythematous (reddened) area of skin, typically measured in millimeters, at the site of intradermal injection 48-72 hours later. In chronic transplant rejection, imaging (e.g., ultrasound, CT) might show progressive organ dysfunction, fibrosis, and structural changes in the transplanted organ.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Allergy, Asthma & Immunology (AAAAI) Guidelines (various years) provide comprehensive information on hypersensitivity reactions, though specific guidelines for Type IV alone are less common than for Type I. General immunology textbooks and consensus statements from organizations like the World Allergy Organization (WAO) also cover these principles.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Helper T cells | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Immunoglobulin A | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Immunoglobulin D | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Immunoglobulin E | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Immunoglobulin G | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 39. A: Helper T cells 4 Type IV hypersensitivity (or delayed type hypersensitivity) is a reaction th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
