  "answer": "E) 42. E: A woman with blood group B RhD-negative and thyroid disease is found to have a haemoglobin level of 11.0 having just given birth to a baby with blood group B RhD-positive. Treatment: Anti-D immunoglobulin. • Patient A: Group A RhD-negative A patient with group B blood has anti-A antibodies and therefore cannot receive group A blood. This patient is also RhD-negative and so cannot receive RhD-positive blood. The patient could take iron sulphate tablets but, with a haemoglobin level of 6.0, a blood transfusion is a better option. • Patient B: Group A RhD-negative A patient with group A blood has anti-B antibodies and therefore cannot receive group B blood. This patient is also RhD-positive and so can receive RhD-positive or negative blood. The patient could take iron sulphate tablets but, with a haemoglobin level of 6.0, a blood transfusion is a better option. • Patient C: Iron sulphate tablets The haemoglobin level is not very low and so a gradual normalization with iron sulphate tablets is a better option compared with the risks associated with blood transfusion. Blood transfusion is usually considered when the haemoglobin level drops below 8 g/dL. • Patient D: Group O RhD-negative A patient with group O blood has anti-A and anti-B antibodies and can only therefore receive group O blood. This patient is also RhD-negative and so cannot receive RhD-positive blood. • Patient E: Anti-D immunoglobulin A woman who is RhD-negative but exposed to the RhD-antigen via childbirth or transfusion will go on to develop antibodies that would attack a subsequent RhD-positive baby in utero. Anti-D immunoglobulin will reduce her immune response and therefore reduce the risk of developing antibodies.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anti-D: The shield for future Rh-positive babies.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is the single best treatment because it correctly identifies the critical need for Anti-D immunoglobulin in an RhD-negative mother who has just given birth to an RhD-positive baby. This intervention is crucial to prevent RhD alloimmunization, which could lead to severe hemolytic disease in future RhD-positive pregnancies.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRhD alloimmunization occurs when an RhD-negative individual is exposed to RhD-positive red blood cells, typically during pregnancy or childbirth. The mother's immune system recognizes the fetal RhD antigen as foreign and produces anti-D antibodies. Anti-D immunoglobulin works by binding to and clearing any fetal RhD-positive red blood cells that have entered the maternal circulation before the mother's immune system can mount a primary immune response. This passive immunization prevents the mother from developing her own active anti-D antibodies, thereby protecting subsequent RhD-positive fetuses from hemolytic disease of the fetus and newborn (HDFN).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A patient with blood group B cannot receive group A blood due to anti-A antibodies. Furthermore, an RhD-negative patient cannot receive RhD-positive blood due to the risk of alloimmunization.\nOption B (Incorrect): A patient with blood group A cannot receive group B blood due to anti-B antibodies.\nOption C (Incorrect): A haemoglobin level of 9.4 g/dL is not typically an indication for blood transfusion, especially in a stable patient. Iron supplementation is usually the preferred initial treatment for mild anemia.\nOption D (Incorrect): A patient with blood group O can only receive group O blood. Additionally, an RhD-negative patient cannot receive RhD-positive blood.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Scenario | Indication/Condition | Treatment Principle | Key Consideration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| RhD-negative mother, RhD-positive baby | Prevention of alloimmunization | Anti-D Immunoglobulin | Prevents HDFN in future pregnancies |\n| Symptomatic anemia or Hb < 7 g/dL | Acute blood loss or severe anemia | Red Blood Cell Transfusion | ABO/RhD compatibility is paramount |\n| Asymptomatic mild anemia (Hb 8-10 g/dL) | Iron deficiency | Oral Iron Supplementation | Avoids transfusion risks, gradual correction |\n| Blood Transfusion | Need for RBCs | ABO/RhD Matching | Universal donor O-negative, universal recipient AB-positive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rh-negative mothers exposed to Rh-positive blood need Anti-D to prevent future fetal harm.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly imaging or intraoperative, the consequence of failing to administer Anti-D can be seen as fetal hydrops on ultrasound in subsequent pregnancies due to severe hemolytic disease of the fetus and newborn.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACOG Practice Bulletin No. 181: Prevention of Rh D Alloimmunization (2017). It recommends routine antenatal and postpartum administration of RhD immune globulin for RhD-negative women.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A 35-year-old woman with blood group B RhD-negative follow-ing a left-sided | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A 66-year-old man with pros-tate carcinoma and blood group A RhD-positive i | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A patient with blood group B RhD-positive following a right-sided hemicolec | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A 75-year-old man with meta-static colorectal carcinoma and blood group O R | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | A woman with blood group B RhD-negative and thyroid disease is found to hav | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 42. E: A woman with blood group B RhD-negative and thyroid disease is found to have a haemoglobin le** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
