  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When in doubt, cut it out (the testicle, for cancer).**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Testicular cancer. A painless, firm mass within the testicle, even with transillumination, is highly suspicious for malignancy, as testicular tumors can be associated with reactive hydroceles.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTesticular cancer typically presents as a painless, firm, non-tender mass arising from the testicle itself. The key diagnostic feature here is the firm mass that does not separate from the testicle, indicating an intratesticular lesion. While hydroceles (which transilluminate) are usually benign, a reactive hydrocele can form secondary to an underlying testicular tumor, leading to the transillumination observed. Therefore, any firm, intratesticular mass must be considered cancer until proven otherwise, necessitating prompt evaluation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Testicular torsion presents with acute, severe pain, often with a high-riding testicle and absent cremasteric reflex. It does not transilluminate.\nOption C (Incorrect): A direct inguinal hernia is a protrusion through Hesselbach's triangle, typically presenting as a bulge in the groin that may descend into the scrotum but is separate from the testicle and does not transilluminate.\nOption D (Incorrect): An indirect inguinal hernia protrudes through the deep inguinal ring, often descending into the scrotum, but it is separate from the testicle and does not transilluminate.\nOption E (Incorrect): A varicocele is a \"bag of worms\" sensation, typically on the left, that does not transilluminate and is separate from the testicle. It often resolves when supine.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Pain | Transillumination | Consistency/Feel | Relation to Testicle |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Testicular Cancer | Usually painless | May transilluminate (if hydrocele present) | Firm, hard | Intratesticular (not separate) |\n| Hydrocele | Usually painless | Brightly transilluminates | Smooth, fluid-filled | Surrounds testicle |\n| Testicular Torsion | Acute, severe pain | No | Firm, tender | Testicle high-riding, rotated |\n| Varicocele | Dull ache, heaviness | No | \"Bag of worms\" | Separate from testicle, superior |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A firm, painless intratesticular mass is cancer until proven otherwise, even if it transilluminates.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn scrotal ultrasound, testicular cancer typically appears as a hypoechoic, heterogeneous, intratesticular mass with increased vascularity on color Doppler. A coexisting hydrocele would be seen as an anechoic fluid collection surrounding the testicle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Testicular Cancer (2023). These guidelines recommend radical orchiectomy for suspected testicular cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Testicular cancer | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Testicular torsion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Direct inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Indirect inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Varicocele | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 44. A: Testicular cancer Any firm scrotal mass is cancer until proven otherwise. Testicular cancer m** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
