  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Punctum in the neck? Think epidermal cyst, not a lymph node's secret admirer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Epidermal cyst. The key clinical features pointing to this diagnosis are the firm lump in the neck, the skin appearing attached to the lump, and especially the presence of a small punctum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEpidermal cysts, also known as epidermoid cysts or sebaceous cysts (though technically distinct), are benign lesions originating from the follicular infundibulum. They are characterized by a sac filled with keratinous material and often have a central punctum, which is a small opening to the skin surface. The attachment of the skin to the lump and the visible punctum are pathognomonic signs, indicating the cyst's dermal origin and connection to the epidermis. They are common in the head and neck region and can vary in size and consistency.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymph nodes are typically mobile, firm but not usually attached to the overlying skin, and do not have a punctum. They are often associated with infection or malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Branchial cysts are congenital anomalies typically found in the lateral neck, anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. They are usually smooth, fluctuant, and do not have a punctum or skin attachment.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thyroglossal cysts are midline neck masses, often infrahyoid, that characteristically move superiorly with tongue protrusion. They do not have a punctum or skin attachment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cystic hygromas (lymphatic malformations) are soft, compressible, transilluminating masses, usually found in the posterior triangle of the neck, often presenting in infancy or early childhood. They do not have a punctum or skin attachment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Epidermal Cyst | Lymph Node | Branchial Cyst | Thyroglossal Cyst |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Anywhere, common head/neck | Anywhere, common neck | Lateral neck, ant. SCM | Midline neck, moves with tongue |\n| **Punctum** | **Often present** | Absent | Absent | Absent |\n| **Skin Attachment** | **Common** | Rare | Rare | Rare |\n| **Consistency** | Firm | Firm/Rubbery | Fluctuant | Fluctuant |\n| **Mobility** | Variable, often fixed to skin | Mobile | Mobile | Moves with tongue |\n| **Origin** | Epidermal inclusion | Lymphatic tissue | Branchial arch remnant | Thyroglossal duct remnant |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A neck lump with a punctum and skin attachment is an epidermal cyst until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, an epidermal cyst typically appears as a well-circumscribed, hypoechoic mass with internal echoes, often showing a 'target' or 'onion skin' appearance. Intraoperatively, the cyst is encapsulated, filled with cheesy, malodorous keratinous material, and its connection to the skin via the punctum is usually visible.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for the management of benign skin lesions (2019) recommend complete surgical excision for symptomatic or cosmetically bothersome epidermal cysts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Branchial cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Epidermal cyst | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 46. E: Epidermal cyst Epidermal cysts originate in the skin and have a characteristic punctum. They ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
