  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it glows, it's a hygroma, so let the lymph flow!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Cystic hygroma. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the patient's age, the soft, fluctuant, and transilluminating nature of the neck mass, and its cystic appearance on ultrasound, all classic features of a cystic hygroma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCystic hygromas are congenital lymphatic malformations (lymphangiomas) that typically present in the head and neck region during infancy or early childhood, though they can manifest later. Their characteristic soft, fluctuant feel, coupled with transillumination, is due to their thin-walled, fluid-filled nature. Ultrasound confirms the multi-loculated cystic structure, often without a solid component, distinguishing them from other neck masses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Lymph node) (Incorrect): Lymph nodes are typically firm, non-transilluminating, and solid or hypoechoic on ultrasound, not purely cystic.\nOption B (Branchial cyst) (Incorrect): While branchial cleft cysts can be cystic and located near the angle of the mandible, transillumination is not a consistent or primary diagnostic feature, and they often have a more defined epithelial lining.\nOption C (Thyroglossal cyst) (Incorrect): Thyroglossal duct cysts are characteristically located in the midline of the neck, often moving with tongue protrusion, which is inconsistent with a lateral mass adjacent to the angle of the mandible.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cystic Hygroma | Branchial Cleft Cyst | Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Lymph Node (Inflamed) |\n| :---------------- | :-------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Lateral neck, posterior triangle, often diffuse | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM, near angle of mandible | Midline neck, moves with tongue protrusion | Anywhere in neck, often anterior/posterior triangles |\n| **Consistency** | Soft, fluctuant | Soft, fluctuant | Soft, fluctuant | Firm, rubbery |\n| **Transillumination** | **Positive** | Usually negative | Usually negative | Negative |\n| **Imaging (US)** | Multi-loculated cystic mass | Unilocular or bilocular cystic mass | Unilocular cystic mass, often with internal debris | Solid, hypoechoic, oval, often with fatty hilum |\n| **Age** | Infancy/childhood | Childhood/adolescence | Childhood/adolescence | Any age |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lateral neck mass + transillumination = Cystic Hygroma until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a cystic hygroma appears as a multi-loculated, anechoic (fluid-filled) mass with thin septations. Intraoperatively, it presents as a soft, spongy, often ill-defined mass composed of multiple thin-walled lymphatic sacs, sometimes extending into surrounding tissues.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation and Management of Neck Masses in Children (2018). Recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for most pediatric neck masses and highlights characteristic features for differential diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Branchial cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystic hygroma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 47. D: Cystic hygroma A cystic hygroma is a lymphangioma which usually presents in childhood. Cystic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
