  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gut's blocked by a stone, an AXR shows where it's flown!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is the correct answer because the clinical presentation strongly suggests bowel obstruction, potentially gallstone ileus, for which a plain abdominal X-ray (AXR) is the appropriate initial investigation. The patient's symptoms of colicky pain, vomiting, distension, and increased bowel sounds are classic for obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGallstone ileus is a rare form of mechanical bowel obstruction caused by the impaction of a gallstone in the intestinal lumen, typically after eroding through the gallbladder wall into the duodenum. The classic radiographic triad (Rigler's triad) seen on AXR includes pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), small bowel obstruction, and an ectopic gallstone. The AXR can reveal dilated loops of bowel proximal to the obstruction, air in the biliary tree, and sometimes the calcified gallstone itself, making it an excellent initial diagnostic tool for this specific presentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): For a pancreatic head tumor with failed ERCP, the next step to relieve jaundice is percutaneous transhepatic cholangiopancreatogram (PTC) for anterograde stenting, not MRCP, which is diagnostic.\nOption B (Incorrect): Acute cholecystitis is best diagnosed with an ultrasound scan, which can detect gallstones, gallbladder wall thickening, and pericholecystic fluid. Contrast-enhanced CT is not the first-line investigation.\nOption D (Incorrect): For acute pancreatitis with an obstructive picture, an ultrasound scan is indicated to detect gallstones as a common cause. A pelvic X-ray is irrelevant for epigastric pain and pancreatitis.\nOption E (Incorrect): A common bile duct (CBD) stone is best managed and removed by Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP), not Percutaneous Transhepatic Cholangiopancreatogram (PTC), which is typically reserved for cases where ERCP fails or is contraindicated.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Scenario | Initial Investigation | Rationale |\n| :---------------- | :-------------------- | :-------- |\n| Pancreatic head tumor, failed ERCP | PTC | Anterograde stenting for jaundice relief |\n| Acute cholecystitis | Ultrasound scan | Detects gallstones, inflammation |\n| Bowel obstruction (gallstone ileus) | Plain abdominal X-ray (AXR) | Reveals dilated bowel, pneumobilia, ectopic stone |\n| Acute pancreatitis with obstructive picture | Ultrasound scan | Identifies gallstones as cause |\n| CBD stone | ERCP | Diagnostic and therapeutic (stone removal) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For suspected bowel obstruction, AXR is your first line, especially for gallstone ileus.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn AXR for gallstone ileus, look for dilated small bowel loops, air in the biliary tree (pneumobilia), and a calcified gallstone in an ectopic location, usually the ileum.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) 2018 Guideline for the Management of Acute Pancreatitis recommends ultrasound for etiology. American Society for Gastrointestinal Endoscopy (ASGE) 2019 guidelines address ERCP indications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A 65-year-old woman is referred with a 4-month history of weight loss and p | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A 43-year-old woman who is rather overweight presents with a 3-day history  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A 60-year-old woman with a previous history of gallstones presents with col | ✅ Correct |\n| D | A 35-year-old man with a history of alcohol abuse presents to A&E with a 2- | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | A 45-year-old woman presents with right upper quadrant pain and vomiting. H | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 48. C: A 60-year-old woman with a previous history of gallstones presents with colicky abdominal pai** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
