  "answer": "E) 49. E: Total hip replacement In elderly patients, hemiarthroplasty is indicated for intracapsular fractures unless there is a diseased acetabulum, when a total hip replacement is preferred.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the acetabulum is sick, don't just fix the stick!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Total Hip Replacement. This choice is optimal because the patient's pre-existing rheumatoid arthritis affecting both hips indicates significant acetabular disease, which contraindicates hemiarthroplasty for an intracapsular femoral neck fracture.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTotal hip replacement (THR) is the preferred treatment for displaced femoral neck fractures in elderly patients with pre-existing symptomatic hip arthritis, such as rheumatoid arthritis. THR addresses both the acute fracture and the underlying chronic arthropathy, providing superior long-term functional outcomes and pain relief compared to hemiarthroplasty. By replacing both the femoral head and the acetabulum, THR prevents ongoing pain from the diseased acetabular cartilage and offers a more durable solution for an active individual with pre-existing joint pathology.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Dynamic hip screw) (Incorrect): DHS is typically used for stable intertrochanteric fractures, not intracapsular femoral neck fractures.\nOption B (Cannulated screws) (Incorrect): Cannulated screws are generally reserved for younger patients with non-displaced or minimally displaced femoral neck fractures, or in elderly patients with good bone quality and minimal displacement. This patient's age, RA, and implied displacement from a fall make this less suitable.\nOption C (Uncemented hemiarthroplasty) (Incorrect): Hemiarthroplasty (uncemented or cemented) replaces only the femoral head. It is contraindicated when there is pre-existing acetabular disease, as the prosthetic femoral head would articulate with diseased cartilage, leading to continued pain and poor outcomes.\nOption D (Cemented hemiarthroplasty) (Incorrect): Similar to uncemented hemiarthroplasty, this option replaces only the femoral head. The presence of rheumatoid arthritis affecting the hips indicates a diseased acetabulum, making hemiarthroplasty an inappropriate choice.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Treatment for Femoral Neck Fracture |\n|---|---|\n| Young patient (<60), non-displaced | ORIF (Cannulated screws) |\n| Elderly, displaced, no pre-existing OA | Hemiarthroplasty (cemented often preferred) |\n| Elderly, displaced, pre-existing OA/RA | Total Hip Arthroplasty (THR) |\n| Elderly, non-displaced, good bone | ORIF (Cannulated screws) or Hemiarthroplasty |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Rheumatoid arthritis + femoral neck fracture = Total Hip Replacement.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain X-ray, an intracapsular femoral neck fracture will be visible. Intraoperatively, the surgeon would observe significant cartilage erosion, synovitis, and potentially osteophytes within the acetabulum, consistent with advanced rheumatoid arthritis, confirming the need for acetabular resurfacing.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for Management of Hip Fractures in Older Adults (2020) recommends considering total hip arthroplasty for displaced femoral neck fractures in active older adults with pre-existing symptomatic arthritis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Dynamic hip screw | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Cannulated screws | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Uncemented hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cemented hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Total hip replacement | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 49. E: Total hip replacement In elderly patients, hemiarthroplasty is indicated for intracapsular fr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
