  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Save the young hip, screw it right!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Cannulated screws. For a young patient with an intracapsular femoral neck fracture, the primary goal is to preserve the femoral head, and cannulated screws offer stable fixation while minimizing disruption to the blood supply.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntracapsular femoral neck fractures in young patients are critical due to the high risk of avascular necrosis (AVN) and non-union, largely because the blood supply to the femoral head (medial circumflex femoral artery) is often compromised. Cannulated screws provide stable internal fixation, allowing for early mobilization while preserving the femoral head's vascularity. This approach aims to prevent the need for early arthroplasty, which has a limited lifespan in a young, active individual, thereby delaying or avoiding more complex reconstructive surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Traction is a temporary measure and not a definitive treatment for a femoral neck fracture, especially in a young patient requiring stable fixation.\nOption B (Incorrect): Dynamic hip screws (DHS) are primarily used for intertrochanteric fractures, not intracapsular femoral neck fractures, as their biomechanics are less suitable for the latter.\nOption D (Incorrect): Intramedullary hip screws (IMHS) or nails are typically indicated for unstable intertrochanteric or subtrochanteric fractures, not for intracapsular femoral neck fractures.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hemiarthroplasty is generally reserved for older patients with displaced femoral neck fractures, or younger patients where femoral head salvage is not possible due to severe displacement or pre-existing conditions, as it replaces the femoral head rather than preserving it.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Age/Condition | Fracture Type | Recommended Treatment |\n| :-------------------- | :------------ | :---------------------- |\n| Young (<60), Undisplaced | Intracapsular Femoral Neck | Cannulated Screws |\n| Young (<60), Displaced | Intracapsular Femoral Neck | ORIF with Cannulated Screws (if viable), or Hemiarthroplasty/THA (if not viable) |\n| Elderly (>60), Undisplaced | Intracapsular Femoral Neck | Cannulated Screws |\n| Elderly (>60), Displaced | Intracapsular Femoral Neck | Hemiarthroplasty or Total Hip Arthroplasty (THA) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Young patient + intracapsular femoral neck = preserve the head with screws.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn intraoperative fluoroscopy, cannulated screws are placed in a triangular configuration, ensuring adequate purchase in the femoral head and neck, avoiding joint penetration, and confirming reduction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for Management of Hip Fractures in Adults (2020) recommends internal fixation for non-displaced femoral neck fractures in physiologically younger patients.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Traction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Dynamic hip screw | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cannulated screws | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Intramedullary hip screw | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 50. C: Cannulated screws Cannulated screws are preferred in younger patients with intracapsular frac** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
