  "answer": "B) 55. B: Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein The liver has a rich blood supply derived from two sources: two-thirds from the portal vein, the remaining one-third from the hepatic artery. Portal vein blood is rich in nutrients absorbed from the intestine but has a relatively low oxygen tension. Hepatic arterial blood contains few nutrients but is rich in oxygen. The hepatic artery supplies roughly 50 per cent of the oxygen delivered to the liver and the portal vein the other 50 per cent of hepatic oxygen supply. The liver is divided into segments by planes defined by the main hepatic veins (Couinaud classification). Purposeful embolization of hepatic arterial branches may be used to treat hepatic metastases.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The hepatic artery: small flow, big oxygen punch!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, B, accurately reflects that while the hepatic artery contributes only about one-third of the liver's total blood flow, it provides approximately half of the liver's oxygen supply, making its oxygen contribution equal to that of the portal vein. This dual supply ensures adequate oxygenation despite the portal vein's lower oxygen tension.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe liver possesses a unique dual blood supply crucial for its metabolic demands. The portal vein delivers approximately two-thirds of the total blood flow, rich in absorbed nutrients from the gastrointestinal tract but relatively low in oxygen. Conversely, the hepatic artery, a branch of the celiac axis, supplies the remaining one-third of the blood flow. Although its volume contribution is smaller, hepatic arterial blood is highly oxygenated and provides roughly 50% of the liver's total oxygen requirements, balancing the lower oxygen content of portal venous blood. This intricate balance is vital for maintaining hepatocyte function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The hepatic artery supplies only about one-third of the liver's total blood flow, while the portal vein supplies two-thirds.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatic arterial blood is highly oxygenated, whereas portal venous blood has a relatively low oxygen tension due to prior passage through the intestinal capillary beds.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hepatic metastases are often hypervascularized by the hepatic artery, making hepatic arterial embolization a common treatment strategy.\nOption E (Incorrect): The liver is divided into anatomical segments (Couinaud classification) by planes defined by the main hepatic veins, not the hepatic artery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hepatic Artery | Portal Vein |\n|---|---|---|\n| Blood Flow Contribution | ~1/3 of total | ~2/3 of total |\n| Oxygen Supply Contribution | ~50% of total | ~50% of total |\n| Oxygenation Level | High | Relatively Low |\n| Nutrient Content | Low | High (from GI tract) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hepatic artery: 1/3 flow, 1/2 oxygen. Portal vein: 2/3 flow, 1/2 oxygen.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography, the hepatic artery and its branches can be clearly visualized, especially when planning transarterial chemoembolization (TACE) for hepatocellular carcinoma or metastases. Intraoperatively, the hepatic artery is typically found anterior to the portal vein and medial to the common bile duct in the porta hepatis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) Practice Guidance for the Treatment of Hepatocellular Carcinoma (2018) recommends transarterial chemoembolization (TACE) as a standard treatment for intermediate-stage HCC, leveraging the hepatic artery's primary supply to tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Supplies the same amount of blood to the liver as the portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Contains blood with the same oxygenation as the portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Does not supply blood to hepatic metastases | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Divides the liver into anatomical segments | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 55. B: Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein The liver has a rich blood** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
