  "answer": "C) 56. C: Protracted vomiting Metabolic alkalosis is commonly seen in patients with protracted vomiting where there is a loss of hydrochloric acid. Aspirin (salicylic acid) poisoning will lead to a metabolic acidosis with a raised anion gap. A pancreatic fistula will lead to loss of bicarbonate-rich (alkaline-rich) digestive juices, resulting in a metabolic acidosis (normal anion gap). Hyperventilation will cause a respiratory, rather than a metabolic, alkalosis. Hypoglycaemia will lead to a metabolic acidosis secondary to lactic acidosis and the production of ketone bodies.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Vomit acid, gain base: Alkalosis is your fate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is protracted vomiting, which leads to metabolic alkalosis due to the significant loss of hydrochloric acid from the stomach. This loss of gastric acid directly increases the body's bicarbonate concentration, resulting in an elevated pH.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProtracted vomiting causes a direct loss of hydrogen ions (as HCl) from the stomach. This leads to a compensatory increase in plasma bicarbonate as the kidneys attempt to excrete bicarbonate but are often limited by volume depletion and hypokalemia, which promote bicarbonate reabsorption. The net effect is an increase in extracellular fluid pH, defining metabolic alkalosis, often accompanied by hypochloremia and hypokalemia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Pancreatic fistula leads to the loss of bicarbonate-rich pancreatic fluid, resulting in a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis, not alkalosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Aspirin (salicylate) poisoning typically causes a mixed acid-base disorder, initially respiratory alkalosis followed by a high anion gap metabolic acidosis due to uncoupling of oxidative phosphorylation and lactic acid production.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hypoglycemia itself does not directly cause metabolic alkalosis; severe hypoglycemia can lead to lactic acidosis, a form of metabolic acidosis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Hyperventilation causes a respiratory alkalosis by blowing off CO2, thereby reducing carbonic acid, not a metabolic alkalosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Primary Disturbance | Common Cause |\n|---|---|---|\n| Metabolic Alkalosis | Increased HCO3- | Protracted vomiting, Diuretics |\n| High Anion Gap Metabolic Acidosis | Decreased HCO3- | Lactic acidosis, Ketoacidosis, Salicylate poisoning |\n| Normal Anion Gap Metabolic Acidosis | Decreased HCO3- | Pancreatic fistula, Diarrhea, Renal tubular acidosis |\n| Respiratory Alkalosis | Decreased pCO2 | Hyperventilation, Anxiety, Hypoxia |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Vomiting means losing acid, leading to metabolic alkalosis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (e.g., CT abdomen) in severe protracted vomiting might show gastric distension, signs of dehydration, or electrolyte imbalances on labs (hypochloremia, hypokalemia). Intraoperatively, one might observe a distended stomach or signs of volume depletion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Nephrology (ASN) Clinical Practice Guideline on Acid-Base Disorders (2019) recommends a systematic approach to diagnosis and management of metabolic alkalosis, emphasizing correction of underlying cause and electrolyte imbalances.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pancreatic fistula | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Aspirin poisoning | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Protracted vomiting | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Hypoglycaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hyperventilation | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 56. C: Protracted vomiting Metabolic alkalosis is commonly seen in patients with protracted vomiting** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
