  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When bone aches, think S. aureus first.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Staphylococcus aureus. This is a fundamental concept in surgical infections, as S. aureus is the predominant pathogen responsible for osteomyelitis across all age groups, including adults. Its prevalence is due to its ubiquitous nature and potent virulence factors.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStaphylococcus aureus is a highly virulent bacterium, frequently colonizing skin and nasal passages, making it readily available to cause infection. Its ability to produce adhesins allows it to bind effectively to bone and prosthetic materials. Furthermore, S. aureus can form protective biofilms, making eradication challenging, and it secretes various toxins and enzymes that contribute to tissue destruction and evasion of host immune responses, leading to persistent and chronic bone infections.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Escherichia coli is a common cause of urinary tract and intra-abdominal infections, and can cause osteomyelitis secondary to decubitus ulcers or sacral infections, but it is not the most common overall cause.\nOption C (Incorrect): Staphylococcus epidermidis is a common cause of prosthetic joint infections due to its biofilm-forming capabilities, but it is less frequently implicated in native bone osteomyelitis compared to S. aureus.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pseudomonas aeruginosa is often associated with osteomyelitis following puncture wounds (especially through footwear), in IV drug users, or in diabetic foot infections, but it is not the most common cause in the general adult population.\nOption E (Incorrect): Streptococcus viridans group bacteria are typically associated with endocarditis or dental infections and are a rare cause of primary osteomyelitis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Patient Group/Risk Factor | Most Common Pathogen | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| General (Adults/Children) | *Staphylococcus aureus* | Most common overall |\n| Prosthetic Joint Infection | *Staphylococcus epidermidis* | Biofilm formation, low virulence |\n| Puncture Wound (foot) | *Pseudomonas aeruginosa* | Especially through sneakers |\n| Sickle Cell Disease | *Salmonella spp.* | Impaired splenic function |\n| Diabetic Foot Ulcer | Polymicrobial (incl. *S. aureus*, Enterobacteriaceae, anaerobes) | Often *S. aureus* also present |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: S. aureus is the king of osteomyelitis, regardless of age.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, early osteomyelitis may show soft tissue swelling, followed by periosteal reaction, cortical destruction, and lucency. MRI is highly sensitive, showing T1 hypointense and T2 hyperintense signals in bone marrow, with enhancement after gadolinium. Intraoperatively, one would typically find purulent exudate, necrotic bone (sequestrum), and reactive new bone formation (involucrum).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nIDSA Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Osteomyelitis (2012) recommend S. aureus as the most common pathogen and emphasize the importance of bone biopsy for definitive diagnosis and culture-directed therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Staphylococcus aureus | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Escherichia coli | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Staphylococcus epidermidis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pseudomonas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Streptococcus viridans | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 57. A: Staphylococcus aureus Osteomyelitis is most commonly caused by S. aureus in all age groups.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
