  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keloids: They grow beyond the lines, so pressure them back in!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nStatus: ACCEPT. Pressure dressings are a recognized and effective feature in the management of keloid scars. They help to modulate the abnormal collagen synthesis and organization characteristic of keloids.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKeloid scars are a pathological form of wound healing characterized by excessive collagen deposition and fibroblast proliferation, extending beyond the original wound boundaries. Pressure dressings exert continuous mechanical force on the scar tissue, leading to local hypoxia, reduced blood flow, and altered fibroblast activity. This mechanical stress is thought to decrease collagen synthesis, increase collagenase activity, and promote collagen fiber alignment, ultimately leading to scar flattening and softening. This non-invasive approach is a cornerstone in keloid management, often used in conjunction with other therapies like intralesional steroid injections.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Keloid scars are characterized by their growth *beyond* the original wound margins, distinguishing them from hypertrophic scars which remain confined to the wound boundaries.\nOption C (Incorrect): Keloid scars are most commonly found on areas of high skin tension or trauma, such as the sternum, deltoid region, earlobes, and upper back, rather than primarily flexure surfaces of the limbs.\nOption D (Incorrect): Subcuticular sutures are used for wound closure to minimize tension and improve cosmetic outcome, but they do not prevent the formation of keloid scars in predisposed individuals.\nOption E (Incorrect): Simple re-excision of keloid scars typically results in a high rate of recurrence, often with a larger and more aggressive keloid. Multimodal treatment is usually required to prevent recurrence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Keloid Scar | Hypertrophic Scar |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Extent** | Extends beyond original wound margins | Confined to original wound margins |\n| **Growth** | Progressive, often years after injury | Regresses over time |\n| **Symptoms** | Pruritic, painful, cosmetically disfiguring | Pruritic, cosmetically disfiguring |\n| **Common Sites** | Sternum, deltoid, earlobes, upper back | Any site of injury |\n| **Recurrence after Excision** | High | Low |\n| **Treatment** | Pressure, steroids, silicone, radiation, cryotherapy | Pressure, steroids, silicone |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pressure dressings and steroid injections are key non-surgical keloid treatments.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, a keloid appears as a firm, raised, often irregularly shaped, shiny, and sometimes erythematous lesion that clearly extends into the surrounding normal skin beyond the original incision or injury site. It lacks the organized appearance of normal scar tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines of Care for the Management of Keloids and Hypertrophic Scars (2014) recommends intralesional corticosteroids, silicone gel sheeting, and pressure therapy as first-line treatments.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | May respond to pressure dressing | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Occurs within the limits of the surgical wound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Is most common on flexure sur-faces of the limbs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Can be prevented by subcuticular sutures | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | May be re-excised with good results | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 58. A: May respond to pressure dressing Keloid scars extend beyond the margins of the wound (unlike ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
