  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Factor IX deficiency means no Christmas for your clotting cascade!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Deficiency of factor IX. Hemophilia B, also known as Christmas disease, is an X-linked recessive bleeding disorder characterized by a deficiency in coagulation factor IX, leading to impaired clot formation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFactor IX is a crucial component of the intrinsic pathway of the coagulation cascade. It is a vitamin K-dependent serine protease that, when activated by factor XIa, forms a complex with factor VIIIa, calcium, and phospholipids to activate factor X. This activation is essential for the subsequent conversion of prothrombin to thrombin and ultimately fibrin clot formation. A deficiency in factor IX disrupts this critical step, resulting in prolonged bleeding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Deficiency of platelets, or thrombocytopenia, is a quantitative or qualitative platelet disorder, distinct from hemophilia which is a coagulation factor deficiency.\nOption B (Incorrect): Deficiency of factor VIII is the cause of Hemophilia A, which is the most common type of hemophilia.\nOption D (Incorrect): Deficiency of factor X is a rare autosomal recessive bleeding disorder affecting both intrinsic and extrinsic pathways, not specifically Hemophilia B.\nOption E (Incorrect): Deficiency of factor XI causes Hemophilia C (Rosenthal syndrome), which typically presents with milder bleeding symptoms and is also known as plasma thromboplastin antecedent (PTA) deficiency.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition      | Deficient Factor | Common Name         | Inheritance |\n|----------------|------------------|---------------------|-------------|\n| Hemophilia A   | Factor VIII      | Classic Hemophilia  | X-linked    |\n| Hemophilia B   | Factor IX        | Christmas Disease   | X-linked    |\n| Hemophilia C   | Factor XI        | Rosenthal Syndrome  | Autosomal   |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hemophilia A is Factor VIII, Hemophilia B is Factor IX. Remember the order.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging (MRI/ultrasound) may show hemarthrosis (bleeding into joints) or intramuscular hematomas. Intraoperatively, expect prolonged and excessive bleeding from surgical sites if not adequately pre-treated with factor replacement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Federation of Hemophilia (WFH) Guidelines for the Management of Hemophilia (2021). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, treatment, and management of hemophilia A and B.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Deficiency of platelets | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Deficiency of factor VIII | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Deficiency of factor IX | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Deficiency of factor X | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Deficiency of factor XI | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 60. C: Deficiency of factor IX Haemophilia B (also known as Christmas disease) is less common than h** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
