  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anterior pituitary: The master *producer* of hormonal symphony!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Prolactin, as it is one of the six key hormones synthesized and secreted by the anterior pituitary gland. This question tests fundamental knowledge of endocrine anatomy and physiology, specifically differentiating the functions of the anterior and posterior pituitary.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anterior pituitary, also known as the adenohypophysis, is a true endocrine gland that synthesizes and secretes its own hormones. These include Follicle-Stimulating Hormone (FSH), Luteinizing Hormone (LH), Adrenocorticotropic Hormone (ACTH), Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone (TSH), Growth Hormone (GH), and Prolactin. In contrast, the posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis) does not synthesize hormones; instead, it stores and releases Antidiuretic Hormone (ADH, or vasopressin) and Oxytocin, which are produced by the hypothalamus.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Oxytocin is synthesized in the hypothalamus and stored/secreted by the posterior pituitary, not the anterior pituitary.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thyroxin (T4) is produced and secreted by the thyroid gland, under the influence of TSH from the anterior pituitary, but not by the pituitary itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): ADH (Antidiuretic Hormone) is synthesized in the hypothalamus and stored/secreted by the posterior pituitary, not the anterior pituitary.\nOption E (Incorrect): Vasopressin is another name for ADH, and like ADH, it is secreted by the posterior pituitary, not the anterior pituitary.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Gland | Hormones Synthesized/Secreted |\n|---|---|\n| Anterior Pituitary (Adenohypophysis) | FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Growth Hormone, Prolactin |\n| Posterior Pituitary (Neurohypophysis) | ADH (Vasopressin), Oxytocin (Synthesized in hypothalamus, stored/secreted here) |\n| Thyroid Gland | Thyroxin (T4), Triiodothyronine (T3), Calcitonin |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Anterior pituitary *makes* hormones; posterior pituitary *stores* them.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPituitary adenomas, often visualized on MRI, can cause endocrine dysfunction (e.g., hyperprolactinemia from a prolactinoma) or mass effect symptoms like bitemporal hemianopsia due to optic chiasm compression. Transsphenoidal surgery is the common approach for resection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Management of Prolactinomas (2011, updated 2023) recommends dopamine agonists as first-line therapy for most prolactinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Prolactin | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Oxytocin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroxin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | ADH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Vasopressin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 64. A: Prolactin The anterior pituitary gland (adenohypophysis or pars distalis) synthesizes and sec** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
