  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 125 mL/min: Your kidneys' daily filtration superpower!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, 125 mL/min, which represents the average normal glomerular filtration rate (GFR) in healthy adults. GFR is the best overall index of kidney function, reflecting the volume of fluid filtered from the renal glomerular capillaries into Bowman's capsule per unit time.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe glomerular filtration rate is a crucial physiological parameter, indicating the kidneys' ability to clear waste products from the blood. It is determined by the net filtration pressure across the glomerular capillaries and the filtration coefficient. A normal GFR of 125 mL/min ensures efficient removal of toxins and maintenance of fluid and electrolyte balance, vital for overall homeostasis. This rate is maintained by autoregulatory mechanisms within the kidney, such as the tubuloglomerular feedback and myogenic response, which stabilize renal blood flow and GFR despite fluctuations in systemic blood pressure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 50 mL/min indicates significant renal impairment, typically corresponding to CKD Stage 3B or 4.\nOption B (Incorrect): 75 mL/min suggests mild to moderate renal impairment, often seen in CKD Stage 3A.\nOption C (Incorrect): 100 mL/min is below the average normal GFR and might indicate early, mild kidney function decline, though still considered within a relatively healthy range for some individuals.\nOption E (Incorrect): 150 mL/min is higher than the average normal GFR and is not typically considered the standard normal value.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| GFR (mL/min/1.73m²) | CKD Stage | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| ≥ 90 | G1 | Normal or high |\n| 60-89 | G2 | Mildly decreased |\n| 45-59 | G3a | Mildly to moderately decreased |\n| 30-44 | G3b | Moderately to severely decreased |\n| 15-29 | G4 | Severely decreased |\n| < 15 | G5 | Kidney failure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: GFR of 125 mL/min is the gold standard for healthy kidney function.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn renal ultrasound, normal kidney size (typically 9-12 cm in adults) and absence of hydronephrosis or significant cortical thinning would be consistent with a normal GFR. In advanced CKD, kidneys often appear small and echogenic.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nKDIGO 2012 Clinical Practice Guideline for the Evaluation and Management of Chronic Kidney Disease. It recommends using GFR and albuminuria for CKD classification and risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 50 mL/min | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 75 mL/min | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 100 mL/min | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 125 mL/min | ✅ Correct |\n| E | 150 mL/min | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 66. D: 125 mL/min The normal glomerular filtration rate (GFR) in humans is 125 mL/min. After the age** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
