  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't smoke, or your lungs will be the UK's most common cancer statistic!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Lung cancer. While breast cancer is most common in females and prostate in males, lung cancer consistently ranks as the most common cancer overall in the UK when considering both genders, primarily due to its high incidence and prevalence.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLung cancer's high incidence is largely driven by its strong association with smoking, which remains a significant public health challenge. Its prevalence across both male and female populations, often presenting with advanced disease, contributes to its top ranking in overall cancer statistics in the UK. Understanding these epidemiological trends is crucial for public health initiatives and clinical practice.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Colorectal cancer) (Incorrect): While a very common cancer in both sexes, it is not the most common overall in the UK, ranking behind lung cancer.\nOption C (Breast cancer) (Incorrect): This is the most common cancer specifically in females in the UK, but when considering the entire population (males and females combined), lung cancer surpasses it.\nOption D (Melanoma) (Incorrect): Melanoma is a significant skin cancer, but its overall incidence is considerably lower than lung, breast, or colorectal cancers in the UK.\nOption E (Leukaemia) (Incorrect): Leukaemia refers to a group of blood cancers. While serious, its incidence is much lower than the major solid organ cancers listed.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Category | Most Common Overall (UK) | Most Common in Females (UK) | Most Common in Males (UK) |\n| :------- | :----------------------- | :-------------------------- | :------------------------ |\n| Cancer   | Lung cancer              | Breast cancer               | Prostate cancer           |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Lung cancer is the overall UK cancer king, regardless of gender.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, lung cancer often appears as a solitary pulmonary nodule, mass, or hilar/mediastinal lymphadenopathy. Intraoperatively, it may present as a firm, irregular mass within the lung parenchyma or enlarged, hard lymph nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNICE Guideline [NG122] Lung cancer: diagnosis and management (2019, last updated 2023). Recommends prompt investigation for suspected lung cancer, including imaging and biopsy, and multidisciplinary team discussion for treatment planning.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Colorectal cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lung cancer | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Breast cancer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Melanoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Leukaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 67. B: Lung cancer The three most common cancers in the female population in the UK in descending or** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
