  "answer": "E) 69. E: Is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament The liver weighs 1500 g and is the largest organ in the body. It receives 30 per cent of the body’s total cardiac output (1500 mL blood flow/min). The liver is drained by the hepatic veins into the inferior vena cava. The nerve supply of the liver is by the right vagus nerve via the celiac ganglia and left vagus, which is supplied directly into the porta hepatis. Sympathetic innervation is carried on vessels. The liver is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament.",
