  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Falciform ligament: the liver's anchor, not just a peritoneal fold.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is the correct answer. The falciform ligament is a characteristic anatomical feature of the liver, serving as its primary attachment to the diaphragm and anterior abdominal wall, which is a fundamental aspect of its anatomical position.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe falciform ligament is a peritoneal fold, a remnant of the ventral mesentery, that extends from the anterior abdominal wall and diaphragm to the anterior and superior surfaces of the liver. It contains the ligamentum teres hepatis (obliterated umbilical vein) in its free edge. This ligament effectively divides the liver into anatomical right and left lobes anteriorly and superiorly, playing a crucial role in maintaining the liver's position within the abdominal cavity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The liver typically weighs around 1500 g in an adult, not 750 g.\nOption B (Incorrect): The liver receives approximately 25-30% of the body’s total cardiac output, not 60%.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatic veins drain into the inferior vena cava, not the superior vena cava.\nOption D (Incorrect): The liver receives its nerve supply from the right vagus via the celiac ganglia (not superior mesenteric) and the left vagus directly, with sympathetic innervation carried on vessels.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Correct Characteristic | Incorrect Option Details |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Weight** | ~1500 g | Option A states 750 g |\n| **Cardiac Output** | 25-30% | Option B states 60% |\n| **Venous Drainage** | Inferior Vena Cava | Option C states Superior Vena Cava |\n| **Nerve Supply** | Right vagus (celiac ganglia), Left vagus (direct) | Option D states Right vagus (superior mesenteric ganglia) |\n| **Attachment** | Falciform ligament to diaphragm/anterior wall | Option E is correct |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The falciform ligament is the liver's key anchor to the diaphragm and anterior abdominal wall.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/US), the falciform ligament appears as a linear structure extending from the anterior abdominal wall to the liver, often containing the ligamentum teres. Intraoperatively, it is a visible peritoneal fold that can be divided during liver mobilization.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nFoundational Surgical Anatomy Textbooks (e.g., Gray's Anatomy, Sabiston Textbook of Surgery) consistently describe the falciform ligament as a primary liver attachment.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It weighs 750 g | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It receives 60 per cent of the body’s total cardiac output | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It drains through hepatic veins into the superior vena cava | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It receives its nerve supply from the right vagus via the superior mesenter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 69. E: Is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament The liver weighs 1500 g and is the lar** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
