  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Zap the prostate, save the man, if it's localized and you've got a plan!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Radiotherapy. For localized prostate carcinoma, radiotherapy, along with radical prostatectomy and proton therapy, stands as a primary curative treatment option aimed at eradicating the disease.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadiotherapy utilizes high-energy radiation to damage the DNA of cancer cells, leading to their destruction and preventing further proliferation. This can be delivered externally (External Beam Radiation Therapy - EBRT) or internally (brachytherapy), precisely targeting the prostate gland while minimizing damage to surrounding healthy tissues. Its curative intent is based on achieving local tumor control and eradication, particularly in patients with localized disease who are not surgical candidates or prefer a non-invasive approach.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Lithotripsy) (Incorrect): Lithotripsy is a procedure used to break up kidney stones or gallstones, not a treatment for prostate cancer.\nOption C (Hormonal treatment) (Incorrect): Hormonal therapy (androgen deprivation therapy) is primarily palliative, used to slow disease progression or as an adjuvant, but not curative for localized disease on its own.\nOption D (Cytotoxic therapy) (Incorrect): Cytotoxic chemotherapy is typically reserved for advanced, metastatic prostate cancer that has become hormone-refractory, not for curative treatment of localized disease.\nOption E (Tamsulosin) (Incorrect): Tamsulosin is an alpha-blocker used to relieve symptoms of benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) by relaxing smooth muscle in the prostate and bladder neck; it has no role in treating prostate cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Type | Modality | Primary Indication | Curative Intent for Localized Disease |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Curative | Radical Prostatectomy | Localized Prostate Cancer | Yes |\n| Curative | Radiotherapy (EBRT, Brachytherapy) | Localized Prostate Cancer | Yes |\n| Palliative/Adjuvant | Hormonal Therapy (ADT) | Advanced/Metastatic PCa, Adjuvant | No |\n| Symptomatic | Alpha-blockers (Tamsulosin) | Benign Prostatic Hyperplasia (BPH) | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Localized prostate cancer has curative options: surgery, radiation, proton therapy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPre-treatment imaging, typically MRI, is crucial for accurate staging and treatment planning, defining the prostate gland and surrounding structures for precise radiation delivery. During radiotherapy, daily imaging (e.g., cone-beam CT) ensures accurate targeting.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (2023): Recommend radical prostatectomy, external beam radiation therapy, or brachytherapy as primary curative options for localized prostate cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radiotherapy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Lithotripsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hormonal treatment | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cytotoxic therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tamsulosin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 73. A: Radiotherapy Recognized curative treatment for localized carcinoma of the prostate includes p** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
