  "id": 140116,
  "question": "Splenectomy increases suscepti-bility to which of the following organisms? A Streptococcus pyogenes B Schistosoma haematobium C Bacteroides fragilis D Neisseria meningitidis E Staphylococcus aureus",
  "options": {
    "A": "Streptococcus pyogenes",
    "B": "Schistosoma haematobium",
    "C": "Bacteroides fragilis",
    "D": "Neisseria meningitidis",
    "E": "Staphylococcus aureus"
  },
  "answer": "D) 77. D: Neisseria meningitidis The spleen plays an important role in the removal of dead and dying erythrocytes and in the defence against microbes. Removal of the spleen (splenectomy) leaves the host susceptible to a wide array of pathogens, but especially to encapsulated organisms. Certain bacteria have evolved ways of evading the human immune system. One way is through the production of a ‘slimy’ capsule on the outside of the bacterial cell wall. Such a capsule resists phagocytosis and ingestion by macrophages and neutrophils. This allows them not only to escape direct destruction by phagocytes, but also to avoid stimulating T-cell responses through the presentation of bacterial peptides by macrophages. The only way that such organisms can be defeated is by making them more ‘palatable’ by coating their capsular polysaccharide surfaces in opsonizing antibody. The production of antibody against capsular polysaccharide primar-ily occurs through mechanisms that are independent of T-cells. The spleen plays a central role in both the initiation of the antibody response and the phagocytosis of opsonized encapsulated bacteria from the bloodstream. This helps to explain why the asplenic individuals are most susceptible to infection from encapsulated organisms, notably Streptococcus pneumoniae (pneumococcus), Neisseria meningitidis (meningococcus), and Haemophilus influenzae. The risk of acquiring these infections is reduced by immunizing individuals against such organisms and by placing patients on prophylactic penicillin, in most cases for the rest of their life. In addition, asplenic individuals should be advised to wear a MedicAlert bracelet to warn other healthcare professionals of their condition.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No spleen? Beware the encapsulated unseen!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D: Neisseria meningitidis. Splenectomy significantly increases susceptibility to infections by encapsulated bacteria, as the spleen plays a critical role in their clearance and in initiating antibody responses against them.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen is a vital organ for immune surveillance, particularly against encapsulated bacteria. Its functions include filtering the blood, removing old red blood cells, and initiating immune responses. Crucially, the spleen is the primary site for generating T-cell independent antibody responses against polysaccharide capsules of bacteria and for phagocytosing opsonized encapsulated bacteria from the bloodstream. Encapsulated organisms, such as Neisseria meningitidis, possess a polysaccharide capsule that helps them evade phagocytosis by macrophages and neutrophils. Without a functional spleen, the body's ability to produce specific antibodies against these capsules and to efficiently clear these opsonized bacteria is severely compromised, leading to a high risk of overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Streptococcus pyogenes (Group A Strep) is not typically encapsulated in the same manner as the classic OPSI organisms, and while it can cause severe infections, it is not the primary organism for which splenectomy specifically increases susceptibility due to loss of splenic function against capsules.\nOption B (Incorrect): Schistosoma haematobium is a parasitic trematode, not a bacterium. Splenectomy does not specifically increase susceptibility to parasitic infections in the same way it does for encapsulated bacteria.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bacteroides fragilis is an anaerobic bacterium commonly found in the gut flora. While it can cause infections, it is not an encapsulated organism primarily targeted by splenic immune function in the context of OPSI.\nOption E (Incorrect): Staphylococcus aureus is a common bacterial pathogen, but it is not typically considered an encapsulated organism in the same category as S. pneumoniae, N. meningitidis, or H. influenzae regarding the specific risk of OPSI due to loss of splenic function against capsules.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organism | Encapsulated? | OPSI Risk Post-Splenectomy | Prevention Strategy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Neisseria meningitidis | Yes | High | Vaccination, lifelong prophylactic antibiotics |\n| Streptococcus pneumoniae | Yes | High | Vaccination, lifelong prophylactic antibiotics |\n| Haemophilus influenzae type b | Yes | High | Vaccination, lifelong prophylactic antibiotics |\n| Staphylococcus aureus | No (mostly) | General infection risk | General hygiene, appropriate antibiotics for specific infections |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Splenectomy = high risk for encapsulated organism sepsis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPost-splenectomy, imaging for OPSI might show signs of severe sepsis like diffuse infiltrates on chest X-ray for pneumonia, or signs of meningitis on head CT. Intraoperatively, a surgeon would confirm complete removal of splenic tissue to prevent accessory spleen function.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guidelines for Immunization of Persons with Asplenia (e.g., 2020). Recommends vaccination against S. pneumoniae, N. meningitidis, and H. influenzae type b, along with influenza and tetanus/diphtheria/pertussis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Streptococcus pyogenes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Schistosoma haematobium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bacteroides fragilis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neisseria meningitidis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Staphylococcus aureus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 77. D: Neisseria meningitidis The spleen plays an important role in the removal of dead and dying er** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
