  "question": "Which of the following hormones is secreted by the anterior pitu-itary gland?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Testosterone",
    "B": "Oxytocin",
    "C": "Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH)",
    "D": "Corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH)",
    "E": "ADH"
  },
  "answer": "C) The pituitary gland (hypophysis) is the conductor of the endocrine orchestra. It is divided into an anterior part and a posterior part. The anterior pituitary (adenohypophysis or pars distalis) secretes 6 hormones, namely:\n\n• FSH/LH: Reproduction • ACTH: Stress response\n• TSH: Basal metabolic rate • GH: Growth\n• Prolactin: Lactation\n\nThe posterior pituitary (neurohypophysis or pars nervosa) secretes only 2 hormones:\n\n• ADH (vasopressin): Osmotic regulation • Oxytocin: Milk ejection and labour\nTestosterone is produced from Leydig cells in the testes and from the adrenal glands. CRH is produced by the median eminence of the hypothalamus.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Anterior pituitary: The conductor of the endocrine orchestra.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). This question assesses fundamental knowledge of endocrine physiology, specifically identifying hormones secreted by the anterior pituitary gland, which is crucial for understanding systemic regulation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe anterior pituitary, also known as the adenohypophysis, is a critical component of the endocrine system, often referred to as the 'master gland' due to its role in regulating other endocrine glands. It secretes six key hormones: Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), Luteinizing hormone (LH), Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH), Growth hormone (GH), Prolactin, and Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH). TSH specifically targets the thyroid gland, stimulating the production and release of thyroid hormones (T3 and T4), which are essential for regulating basal metabolic rate, growth, and development.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Testosterone is primarily produced by the Leydig cells in the testes in males and in smaller amounts by the adrenal glands in both sexes, not the anterior pituitary.\nOption B (Incorrect): Oxytocin is secreted by the posterior pituitary gland, not the anterior pituitary. It plays roles in uterine contractions during labor and milk ejection.\nOption D (Incorrect): Corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) is produced by the hypothalamus, specifically the median eminence, and acts on the anterior pituitary to stimulate ACTH release.\nOption E (Incorrect): ADH (Antidiuretic hormone), also known as vasopressin, is secreted by the posterior pituitary gland. It regulates water reabsorption in the kidneys.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pituitary Lobe | Hormones Secreted | Primary Functions |\n|---|---|---|\n| Anterior Pituitary (Adenohypophysis) | TSH, ACTH, GH, Prolactin, FSH, LH | Regulates thyroid, adrenal cortex, growth, lactation, reproduction |\n| Posterior Pituitary (Neurohypophysis) | ADH (Vasopressin), Oxytocin | Regulates water balance, uterine contraction, milk ejection |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the anterior pituitary's 'FLAT PiG' mnemonic for its hormones: FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, GH.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, pituitary adenomas, which can cause hyper- or hyposecretion of anterior pituitary hormones, appear as enhancing lesions within the sella turcica. During transsphenoidal surgery, the anterior pituitary is accessed via the sphenoid sinus, and its distinct glandular tissue is identifiable.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society's Clinical Practice Guidelines for the Diagnosis and Management of Pituitary Adenomas (2016) provide comprehensive recommendations for evaluating and treating disorders of the anterior pituitary.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Testosterone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Oxytocin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | ADH | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The pituitary gland (hypophysis) is the conductor of the endocrine orchestra. It is divided into an ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
