  "id": 140122,
  "question": "The oxygen–haemoglobin disso-ciation curve is shifted to the left by what?",
  "options": {
    "A": "An increase in pCO2",
    "B": "A fall in pH",
    "C": "A rise in temperature",
    "D": "An increase in 2,3-DPG",
    "E": "Foetal haemoglobin"
  },
  "answer": "E) The haemoglobin oxygen dissociation curve is sigmoidal in shape, which reflects the underlying biochemical properties of haemoglobin. The significance of the sigmoidal curve is that haemoglobin becomes highly saturated at high oxygen partial pressures (and is therefore highly efficient at collecting oxygen) and releases a significant amount of oxygen at pressures that are fairly low, but not extremely so (with the result that haemoglobin is highly effective at supplying oxygen where it is needed).\nThe effect of things that shift the curve to the right (raised CO2, lowered pH, increased temperature, increase in 2,3-DPG) is to increase oxygen availability in the tissues. The effect of CO2/H+ on O2 carriage is known as the Bohr shift or effect. This is exactly what is needed in metabolizing tissues; release of acids or CO2 thus liberates O2 to fulfil the metabolic needs of the tissue. Do not confuse this with the effect of changes in O2 on CO2 carriage, which is called the Haldane effect.\nA shift of the oxygen dissociation curve to the left is characteristic of foetal haemoglobin. When compared with adult haemoglobin, it is composed of two alpha and two gamma chains, instead of the usual two alpha and two beta chains of adult haemoglobin. This arrangement assists in the transfer of oxygen across the placenta from the maternal to the foetal circulation. The corollary of this is that foetal tissue oxygen levels have to be low to permit the release of oxygen from the haemoglobin (Figure 3).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Foetal Hb: The ultimate oxygen hoarder for tiny humans!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies foetal haemoglobin as the factor that shifts the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve to the left. This leftward shift signifies an increased affinity of haemoglobin for oxygen, which is physiologically crucial for efficient oxygen transfer from the maternal circulation across the placenta to the foetus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFoetal haemoglobin (HbF) is structurally different from adult haemoglobin (HbA), consisting of two alpha and two gamma chains (α2γ2) instead of two alpha and two beta chains (α2β2). This unique structure gives HbF a higher affinity for oxygen compared to HbA, primarily because 2,3-bisphosphoglycerate (2,3-BPG) binds less avidly to HbF. The reduced binding of 2,3-BPG stabilizes the R-state (relaxed, high-affinity) conformation of HbF, facilitating oxygen uptake from the maternal blood at the placenta, where pO2 is relatively lower than in the lungs.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (An increase in pCO2) (Incorrect): An increase in pCO2 leads to a fall in pH and a rightward shift of the curve (Bohr effect), indicating decreased oxygen affinity and enhanced oxygen release to tissues.\nOption B (A fall in pH) (Incorrect): A fall in pH (acidosis) causes a rightward shift of the curve (Bohr effect), promoting oxygen unloading in metabolically active tissues.\nOption C (A rise in temperature) (Incorrect): An increase in temperature shifts the curve to the right, decreasing haemoglobin's affinity for oxygen and facilitating its release to warmer, more active tissues.\nOption D (An increase in 2,3-DPG) (Incorrect): An increase in 2,3-DPG (also known as 2,3-BPG) binds to haemoglobin, stabilizing its T-state (tense, low-affinity) conformation, thus shifting the curve to the right and promoting oxygen release.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Effect on Curve | Physiological Consequence |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Left Shift** | Increased O2 affinity | Enhanced O2 uptake (e.g., placenta, lungs) |\n| Foetal Hb | Left | Facilitates O2 transfer to foetus |\n| Decreased pCO2 | Left | Increased O2 affinity |\n| Increased pH (Alkalosis) | Left | Increased O2 affinity |\n| Decreased Temperature | Left | Increased O2 affinity |\n| Decreased 2,3-DPG | Left | Increased O2 affinity |\n| **Right Shift** | Decreased O2 affinity | Enhanced O2 release (e.g., metabolizing tissues) |\n| Increased pCO2 | Right | Bohr effect, O2 release |\n| Decreased pH (Acidosis) | Right | Bohr effect, O2 release |\n| Increased Temperature | Right | O2 release to active tissues |\n| Increased 2,3-DPG | Right | O2 release to tissues |\n| Exercise | Right | Combination of factors |\n| Anemia | Right | Compensatory O2 release |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Left shift = Lungs, Low temp, Low 2,3-DPG, Low H+ (high pH), Little CO2, and Little baby (Foetal Hb).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly visualized, understanding the oxygen-haemoglobin dissociation curve is critical when interpreting arterial blood gases (ABGs) in patients with conditions like hypothermia, acidosis/alkalosis, or in neonates. For instance, a left shift in a neonate's ABG indicates their HbF is efficiently scavenging oxygen, which is normal, but also means tissue pO2 must be lower to offload oxygen.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is a foundational concept in respiratory physiology and biochemistry, not typically governed by a single clinical guideline. It is extensively covered in standard physiology and medical textbooks.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | An increase in pCO2 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A fall in pH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A rise in temperature | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | An increase in 2,3-DPG | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Foetal haemoglobin | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The haemoglobin oxygen dissociation curve is sigmoidal in shape, which reflects the underlying bioch** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
