  "question": "Which of the following cells are cytotoxic?",
  "options": {
    "A": "CD4 T-cells",
    "B": "CD8 T-cells",
    "C": "B-cells",
    "D": "TH1 cells",
    "E": "TH2 cells"
  },
  "answer": "B) Lymphocytes can be divided into 2 main subtypes: T-cells and B-cells. B-cells (or plasma cells) secrete antibodies. T-cells can be divided into two further subtypes: CD4 T-cells and CD8 T-cells. CD4 (helper) T-cells can recognize antigen only in the context of MHC Class II, whereas CD8 (cytotoxic) T-cells recognize cell-bound antigens only in association with Class I MHC. This is known as MHC restriction.\nCD4 and CD8 T-cells perform distinct but somewhat overlapping functions. The CD4 helper T-cell can be viewed as a master regulator. By secreting cytokines (soluble factors that mediate communication between cells), CD4 helper T-cells influence the function of virtually all other cells of the immune system including other T-cells,\nB-cells, macrophages, and natural killer (NK) cells. The central role of CD4 cells is tragically illustrated by the HIV virus, which cripples the immune system by\nselective destruction of this T-cell subset. In recent years two functionally different populations of CD4 helper T-cells have been recognized – TH1 cells and TH2\ncells –each characterized by the cytokines that they produce. In general, TH1 cells facilitate cell-mediated immunity, whereas TH2 cells promote humoral-mediated immunity.\nCD8 cytotoxic T-cells mediate their functions primarily by acting as cytotoxic cells (i.e., they are T-cells that kill other cells). They are important in the host defence against cytosolic pathogens. Two principal mechanisms of cytotoxicity have been dis-covered: perforin–granzyme-dependent killing and Fas–Fas ligand-dependent killing.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CD8 T-cells: The immune system's precision killers.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption B, CD8 T-cells, is the correct answer. CD8 T-cells are specifically known as cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs) because their primary function is to directly kill other cells, such as virally infected cells or tumor cells.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCD8 cytotoxic T-cells mediate their functions primarily by acting as cytotoxic cells, meaning they are T-cells that kill other cells. They are crucial in host defense against cytosolic pathogens and play a significant role in tumor surveillance. Their cytotoxic action involves two principal mechanisms: perforin–granzyme-dependent killing, where perforin creates pores in the target cell membrane allowing granzymes to enter and induce apoptosis, and Fas–Fas ligand-dependent killing, which triggers programmed cell death in the target cell upon binding.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (CD4 T-cells) (Incorrect): CD4 T-cells are helper T-cells that regulate immune responses by secreting cytokines, but they do not directly kill target cells.\nOption C (B-cells) (Incorrect): B-cells are responsible for humoral immunity, primarily by differentiating into plasma cells and secreting antibodies, not by direct cytotoxicity.\nOption D (TH1 cells) (Incorrect): TH1 cells are a subset of CD4 helper T-cells that facilitate cell-mediated immunity, but they are not directly cytotoxic themselves.\nOption E (TH2 cells) (Incorrect): TH2 cells are another subset of CD4 helper T-cells that promote humoral-mediated immunity, and like TH1 cells, they are not directly cytotoxic.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Primary Function |\n|---|---|\n| CD4 T-cells | Helper/Regulatory, cytokine secretion |\n| CD8 T-cells | Cytotoxic (kill infected/tumor cells) |\n| B-cells | Antibody production (humoral immunity) |\n| TH1 cells | Facilitate cell-mediated immunity |\n| TH2 cells | Promote humoral immunity |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CD8 T-cells are the direct cellular assassins of the immune system.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly visualized, the presence of CD8 T-cells infiltrating a tumor (Tumor-Infiltrating Lymphocytes or TILs) on pathology slides is often a favorable prognostic indicator, suggesting an active anti-tumor immune response.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific surgical guideline applies directly to this basic immunology concept. However, foundational immunology textbooks like 'Janeway's Immunobiology' (9th Ed., 2017) extensively cover these cell functions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | CD4 T-cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | CD8 T-cells | ✅ Correct |\n| C | B-cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | TH1 cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | TH2 cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Lymphocytes can be divided into 2 main subtypes: T-cells and B-cells. B-cells (or plasma cells) secr** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
