  "id": 140124,
  "question": "A 3-week-old baby exhibits projectile vomiting shortly after feeding, and failure to thrive.\nOn examination, an olive-shaped mass is palpable in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen. A clinical diagnosis of pyloric stenosis is made. What biochemi-cal laboratory features would support the diagnosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Hypokalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, low urinary pH",
    "B": "Hyperkalaemia, metabolic acidosis, high urinary pH",
    "C": "Hypokalaemia, metabolic acidosis, high urinary pH",
    "D": "Hyperkalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, low urinary pH",
    "E": "Hypokalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, high urinary pH"
  },
  "answer": "A) Following a diagnosis of pyloric stenosis, the first concern is to correct the metabolic abnormalities that invariably coexist with the condition. The serum electrolytes and capillary gases should be measured and corrected prior to surgery.\nWith prolonged vomiting, the infant becomes dehydrated, with a hypochloraemic metabolic alkalosis. The alkalosis is a result of loss of unbuffered hydrogen ions in gastric juice with concomitant retention of bicarbonate.\nFluid loss stimulates renal sodium reabsorption, but sodium can be reabsorbed only either with chloride, or in exchange for hydrogen and potassium ions\n(to maintain electroneutrality). Gastric juice has a high concentration of chloride and patients losing gastric secretions become hypochloraemic. This means that less sodium than normal can be reabsorbed with chloride.\nHowever, it appears that the defence of extracellular fluid volume takes precedence over acid–base homeostasis and further sodium reabsorption occurs in exchange for hydrogen ions (perpetuating the alkalosis) and potassium ions (leading to potassium depletion). This explains the apparently paradoxical finding of acidic urine in patients\nwith pyloric stenosis. Potassium is also lost in the gastric juice and thus patients frequently become potassium-depleted and yet are losing potassium in their urine.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pyloric stenosis: Vomit acid, get alkalotic, pee acid, lose K+.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A because pyloric stenosis leads to persistent vomiting of gastric contents, resulting in significant loss of hydrogen and chloride ions. This causes a hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis and volume depletion, which triggers renal compensatory mechanisms leading to hypokalemia and paradoxically acidic urine.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProlonged vomiting in pyloric stenosis causes direct loss of gastric HCl, leading to hypochloremia and metabolic alkalosis. The resulting volume depletion activates the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system, promoting renal sodium reabsorption. To maintain electroneutrality, sodium is reabsorbed in exchange for hydrogen and potassium ions, exacerbating the alkalosis and causing hypokalemia. Despite systemic alkalosis, the kidneys prioritize volume repletion, leading to increased H+ excretion and thus a low urinary pH (paradoxical aciduria).\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Hyperkalaemia is incorrect as potassium is lost in gastric juice and exchanged for sodium in the kidney, leading to hypokalaemia. Metabolic acidosis is incorrect; loss of gastric acid causes alkalosis. High urinary pH is incorrect due to paradoxical aciduria.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hyperkalaemia is incorrect. Metabolic acidosis is incorrect. High urinary pH is incorrect.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hyperkalaemia is incorrect; hypokalaemia is expected. Metabolic alkalosis and low urinary pH are correct, but the hyperkalaemia makes this option wrong.\nOption E (Incorrect): High urinary pH is incorrect; the kidney excretes H+ to conserve volume, leading to low urinary pH. Hypokalaemia and metabolic alkalosis are correct, but the urinary pH makes this option wrong.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pyloric Stenosis | Severe Diarrhea | Diabetic Ketoacidosis (DKA) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Primary Acid-Base Disturbance | Metabolic Alkalosis | Metabolic Acidosis | Metabolic Acidosis |\n| Potassium Level | Hypokalemia | Hypokalemia (often) | Hyperkalemia (initially), then Hypokalemia |\n| Urinary pH | Low (Paradoxical Aciduria) | Variable, often low | Low |\n| Cause | Loss of gastric HCl | Loss of bicarbonate from gut | Accumulation of ketoacids |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pyloric stenosis = Vomiting H+, losing Cl-, kidney saves volume, excretes K+ and H+.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUltrasound reveals a thickened pyloric muscle (>3-4 mm) and elongated pyloric channel (>14-17 mm). Intraoperatively, a hypertrophied, avascular pyloric muscle is incised longitudinally down to the mucosa (Ramstedt pyloromyotomy).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Pyloric Stenosis (2017) recommends correcting fluid and electrolyte abnormalities, especially hypochloremic metabolic alkalosis, prior to surgical intervention.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Hypokalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, low urinary pH | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Hyperkalaemia, metabolic acidosis, high urinary pH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypokalaemia, metabolic acidosis, high urinary pH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hyperkalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, low urinary pH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hypokalaemia, metabolic alkalosis, high urinary pH | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Following a diagnosis of pyloric stenosis, the first concern is to correct the metabolic abnormaliti** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
