  "question": "Which antiarrhythmic drug acts by inhibiting potassium channels?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Lignocaine",
    "B": "Atenolol",
    "C": "Amiodarone",
    "D": "Verapamil",
    "E": "Diltiazem"
  },
  "answer": "C) This question requires knowledge of the Vaughan Williams classification of antiarrhythmic drugs. Lignocaine is a class 1B drug and blocks sodium channels.\nAll class I drugs have membrane stabilizing properties. Procainamide, a class 1A drug, and flecainide, a class 1C drug, also block sodium channels.\nAll class I drugs have membrane stabilizing properties.\nClass II drugs comprise the beta-blockers. They are believed to work by blocking the pro-arrhythmic effects of catecholamines and the sympathetic nervous system.\nClass III drugs (e.g., amiodarone, sotalol) act through the blockade of potassium channels. They work by prolonging the action potential, thereby increasing the refractory period and hence suppressing ectopic and re-entrant activity. Note that sotalol has both class II and class III actions.\nClass IV includes drugs such as verapamil and diltiazem which act by blocking calcium channels.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Amiodarone: The 'K' to a longer refractory period.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Amiodarone. This question tests your knowledge of the Vaughan Williams classification of antiarrhythmic drugs, specifically identifying drugs that act by inhibiting potassium channels.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAmiodarone is a Class III antiarrhythmic drug. These drugs primarily act by blocking potassium channels, which prolongs the repolarization phase of the cardiac action potential. This prolongation increases the effective refractory period, thereby preventing re-entrant arrhythmias and suppressing ectopic activity. While amiodarone has broad effects (Class I, II, and IV activity), its predominant and defining mechanism as a Class III agent is potassium channel blockade.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Lignocaine) (Incorrect): Lignocaine (Lidocaine) is a Class IB antiarrhythmic drug that acts by blocking fast sodium channels, primarily affecting ventricular arrhythmias.\nOption B (Atenolol) (Incorrect): Atenolol is a Class II antiarrhythmic drug, which is a beta-blocker. It works by blocking beta-adrenergic receptors, reducing sympathetic stimulation to the heart.\nOption D (Verapamil) (Incorrect): Verapamil is a Class IV antiarrhythmic drug, a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker. It acts by blocking L-type calcium channels, primarily affecting the AV node.\nOption E (Diltiazem) (Incorrect): Diltiazem is also a Class IV antiarrhythmic drug, a non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker, with a similar mechanism of action to verapamil.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Vaughan Williams Class | Primary Mechanism | Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| Class I (Sodium Channel Blockers) | Blocks fast sodium channels | IA: Procainamide, Quinidine; IB: Lignocaine; IC: Flecainide |\n| Class II (Beta-Blockers) | Blocks beta-adrenergic receptors | Atenolol, Metoprolol, Propranolol |\n| Class III (Potassium Channel Blockers) | Blocks potassium channels, prolongs repolarization | Amiodarone, Sotalol, Dofetilide |\n| Class IV (Calcium Channel Blockers) | Blocks L-type calcium channels | Verapamil, Diltiazem |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Class III drugs like Amiodarone prolong the QT interval by blocking potassium channels.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring intraoperative monitoring, Class III antiarrhythmics like amiodarone can cause significant QT prolongation on the ECG, which must be carefully monitored to prevent Torsades de Pointes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2017 AHA/ACC/HRS Guideline for Management of Patients With Ventricular Arrhythmias and the Prevention of Sudden Cardiac Death: Recommends amiodarone for rhythm control in various ventricular and supraventricular arrhythmias.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lignocaine | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Atenolol | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Amiodarone | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Verapamil | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Diltiazem | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) This question requires knowledge of the Vaughan Williams classification of antiarrhythmic drugs. Lig** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
