  "question": "With regard to smooth (visceral) muscle:\nA Excitation depends more on the influx of extracellular calcium than release from internal stores\nB It contains no actin or myosin filaments\nC It classically relaxes when it is stretched\nD It contains an extensive T-tubular system\nE It is innervated through somatic motor nerve endings",
  "options": {
    "A": "Excitation depends more on the influx of extracellular calcium than release from internal stores",
    "B": "It contains no actin or myosin filaments",
    "C": "It classically relaxes when it is stretched",
    "D": "It contains an extensive T-tubular system",
    "E": "It is innervated through somatic motor nerve endings"
  },
  "answer": "A) In smooth muscle, actin and myosin filaments occur but are less obvious on microscopy, giving it a non-striated appearance. Most smooth muscle has extensive electrically conducting gap junctions between cells which allows\npropagation of waves of electrical excitation through the tissue. Smooth muscle is usually under autonomic (involuntary nervous) or hormonal control, unlike skeletal muscle which is under somatic control. Unlike skeletal muscle, smooth muscle can generate active tension in the absence of any neural activity (latch bridge mechanism).\nThere is a vesicular sarcoplasmic reticulum close to the membrane (caveolae), but no T-tubular system. This is because the slow speed of smooth muscle does not require an elaborate mechanism for intracellular calcium release. For this reason, and because of the higher surface area to volume ratio of smooth muscle cells, excitation depends more on the influx of extracellular calcium\nthan release from internal stores since smooth muscle has a less well-developed sarcoplasmic reticulum.\nThe intrinsic myogenic response in smooth muscle opposes stretch. The result is that contraction may be generated by mechanical stretch of muscle fibres, for example in blood vessel walls. This is partly the basis for autoregulation of\nblood flow in the cerebral, coronary, and renal beds. It also plays a role in the peristaltic movements of material in the intestine.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Smooth muscle: slow, steady, and always reaching for external calcium.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, as smooth muscle excitation relies predominantly on the influx of extracellular calcium. This is a key physiological distinction from skeletal muscle, where internal calcium stores are the primary source for contraction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSmooth muscle cells are uniquely adapted for slow, sustained contractions, which is reflected in their calcium handling. Unlike skeletal muscle, smooth muscle possesses a less elaborate sarcoplasmic reticulum and lacks an extensive T-tubular system. Its excitation-contraction coupling is primarily driven by the influx of extracellular calcium through voltage-gated channels, facilitated by its higher surface area to volume ratio. This mechanism allows for fine-tuned, prolonged contractile responses essential for functions like peristalsis and vascular tone regulation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Smooth muscle does contain actin and myosin filaments, although they are not arranged in sarcomeres, which gives it a non-striated appearance.\nOption C (Incorrect): Smooth muscle classically contracts when stretched due to an intrinsic myogenic response, which is crucial for autoregulation in blood vessels and peristalsis.\nOption D (Incorrect): Smooth muscle lacks an extensive T-tubular system; its slower contraction speed and higher surface area to volume ratio negate the need for such a rapid calcium delivery system.\nOption E (Incorrect): Smooth muscle is innervated by the autonomic (involuntary) nervous system, not somatic motor nerve endings, which control skeletal muscle.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Smooth Muscle | Skeletal Muscle |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Striations** | Absent | Present |\n| **T-tubules** | Absent/Rudimentary | Extensive |\n| **Primary Ca2+ Source** | Extracellular influx | Sarcoplasmic Reticulum |\n| **Innervation** | Autonomic (involuntary) | Somatic (voluntary) |\n| **Stretch Response** | Contracts (myogenic) | No intrinsic contraction |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Smooth muscle loves extracellular calcium; it's its main squeeze.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn fluoroscopy or endoscopy, one might observe the rhythmic contractions (peristalsis) of smooth muscle in the GI tract, or during vascular surgery, appreciate the vasospasm of arterial smooth muscle.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis question pertains to foundational human physiology, not a specific clinical guideline. Therefore, no single guideline applies directly.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Excitation depends more on the influx of extracellular calcium than release | ✅ Correct |\n| B | It contains no actin or myosin filaments | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It classically relaxes when it is stretched | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It contains an extensive T-tubular system | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It is innervated through somatic motor nerve endings | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) In smooth muscle, actin and myosin filaments occur but are less obvious on microscopy, giving it a n** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
