  "id": 140143,
  "question": "With regard to chemical neurotransmitters:\nA Noradrenaline is the predominant neurotransmitter found between first- and second-order sympa-thetic neurones\nB The nerve endings of second-order parasympathetic neurones release acetylcholine that acts on nicotinic cholinergic receptors\nC The neuromuscular junction releases acetylcholine that acts on muscarinic cholinergic receptors\nD The nucleus accumbens and sub-stantia nigra are rich in dopamine\nE The locus coeruleus and peri-aqueductal grey are rich in acetylcholine",
  "options": {
    "A": "Noradrenaline is the predominant neurotransmitter found between first- and second-order sympa-thetic neurones",
    "B": "The nerve endings of second-order parasympathetic neurones release acetylcholine that acts on nicotinic cholinergic receptors",
    "C": "The neuromuscular junction releases acetylcholine that acts on muscarinic cholinergic receptors",
    "D": "The nucleus accumbens and sub-stantia nigra are rich in dopamine",
    "E": "The locus coeruleus and peri-aqueductal grey are rich in acetylcholine"
  },
  "answer": "D) The nervous system can be arbitrarily divided into the somatic (or ‘voluntary’) and autonomic (or ‘involuntary’) parts. The autonomic nervous system consists of two arms, namely the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems. Both sympathetic and parasympathetic fibres consist of two neurones (first-order or preganglionic, and second-order or postganglionic) and two synapses (the synaptic cleft between the first- and second-order neurones and the synaptic cleft between the second-order neurone and the organ or effector). There are key differences between both the neurones and the synapses of the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems.\nFirst-order (preganglionic) sympathetic and parasympathetic neurones are myelinated, whereas second-order (postganglionic) sympathetic and parasym-pathetic neurones are small, unmyelinated fibres. In both the sympathetic and\nparasympathetic nervous systems, preganglionic neurones release acetylcho-line which acts on postsynaptic nicotinic cholinergic receptors. However, they differ at the second synapse (between second-order neurones and the effector) where noradrenaline is the principal chemical neurotransmitter used within the sympathetic nervous system (although this is not entirely true because the post-ganglionic sympathetic nerve fibres to the sweat glands, the piloerector muscles and a few blood vessels are cholinergic), but acetylcholine is the principal neurotransmitter used within the parasympathetic nervous system (but this time acting on muscarinic cholinergic receptors).\nThe neuromuscular junction (the synapse between somatic motor neurones and skeletal muscle) operates by way of acetylcholine acting through nicotinic acetylcholine receptors. The substantia nigra is a dense area of dopaminergic\nneurones which forms part of the basal ganglia; degeneration leads to Parkinson’s disease. The periaqueductal grey is a region rich in endogenous opioids which\nis believed to play a pivotal role in attenuation of painful stimuli through descending inhibition from higher centres. The noradrenergic-rich locus coeruleus is believed to play a key role in attention. The nucleus accumbens is dopamine-rich and plays an important role in addiction and reward. The adre-nal medulla is an endocrine gland but is effectively a specialized second-order (postganglionic) sympathetic nerve terminal that secretes approximately 70 per cent adrenaline, 30 per cent noradrenaline. Excess catecholamines are secreted by the adrenal medulla in a condition known as a phaeochromocytoma, which is a rare tumour of the adrenal gland. A thorough grounding of the aforementioned chemical neurotransmitters is imperative if one is to understand certain disease states and how particular drugs act within the nervous system.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Dopamine: The brain's reward and movement maestro, from substantia nigra to nucleus accumbens.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. This question tests fundamental knowledge of neuroanatomy and neurotransmitter distribution. Option D correctly identifies the nucleus accumbens and substantia nigra as regions rich in dopamine, which is crucial for understanding reward pathways and motor control.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe substantia nigra is a critical component of the basal ganglia, densely populated with dopaminergic neurons whose degeneration leads to Parkinson's disease. The nucleus accumbens, also rich in dopamine, plays a pivotal role in the brain's reward system and is implicated in addiction. Understanding these specific anatomical distributions of neurotransmitters is essential for comprehending neurological disorders and pharmacological interventions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Noradrenaline is the predominant neurotransmitter released by *second-order* (postganglionic) sympathetic neurones at the effector organ, not between first- and second-order sympathetic neurones. Acetylcholine is released between first- and second-order sympathetic neurones.\nOption B (Incorrect): The nerve endings of second-order parasympathetic neurones release acetylcholine, but it acts on *muscarinic* cholinergic receptors at the effector organ, not nicotinic. Nicotinic receptors are found at the ganglion.\nOption C (Incorrect): The neuromuscular junction releases acetylcholine, but it acts on *nicotinic* cholinergic receptors on skeletal muscle, not muscarinic.\nOption E (Incorrect): The locus coeruleus is rich in *noradrenaline*, and the periaqueductal grey is rich in *endogenous opioids*, not acetylcholine.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Neurotransmitter | Location/System | Receptor Type |\n|-----------------|-----------------------------------|-------------------|\n| Acetylcholine   | Preganglionic sympathetic/parasympathetic | Nicotinic |\n| Acetylcholine   | Postganglionic parasympathetic | Muscarinic |\n| Acetylcholine   | Neuromuscular junction | Nicotinic |\n| Noradrenaline   | Postganglionic sympathetic | Adrenergic |\n| Dopamine        | Substantia nigra, Nucleus accumbens | Dopaminergic |\n| Noradrenaline   | Locus Coeruleus | Adrenergic |\n| Endogenous Opioids | Periaqueductal Grey | Opioid |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know your neurotransmitter maps; location dictates function and pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn Parkinson's disease, advanced imaging like DaTscan (dopamine transporter scan) can show reduced dopamine transporter activity in the striatum, reflecting the degeneration of dopaminergic neurons originating from the substantia nigra.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Neurology (AAN) Guidelines for Parkinson's Disease (e.g., 2018): These guidelines address the management of Parkinson's disease, which is fundamentally linked to the degeneration of dopaminergic neurons in the substantia nigra.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Noradrenaline is the predominant neurotransmitter found between first- and  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The nerve endings of second-order parasympathetic neurones release acetylch | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The neuromuscular junction releases acetylcholine that acts on muscarinic c | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The nucleus accumbens and sub-stantia nigra are rich in dopamine | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The locus coeruleus and peri-aqueductal grey are rich in acetylcholine | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The nervous system can be arbitrarily divided into the somatic (or ‘voluntary’) and autonomic (or ‘i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
