  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Ticks are tiny, but their bite can bring big trouble like Lyme.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D because Borrelia burgdorferi, the causative agent of Lyme disease, is classically transmitted via an arthropod vector, specifically ticks. This question tests fundamental knowledge of microbial pathogenesis and transmission routes, which is critical for understanding disease prevention and treatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nVector-borne diseases represent a significant category of infectious diseases where pathogens are transmitted between hosts via an arthropod intermediary. For Borrelia burgdorferi, the black-legged tick (Ixodes scapularis) serves as the primary vector, acquiring the spirochete from infected small mammals and birds, and then transmitting it to humans during a blood meal. Understanding this specific transmission cycle is crucial for public health interventions, diagnosis, and prevention strategies, such as tick avoidance and prompt removal, thereby preventing the systemic manifestations of Lyme disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Neisseria meningitidis is primarily transmitted via respiratory droplets, not sexually. It causes meningitis and meningococcemia.\nOption B (Incorrect): Corynebacterium diphtheriae, the cause of diphtheria, is spread through respiratory droplets, not food-borne routes.\nOption C (Incorrect): Clostridium tetani spores enter the body through contaminated wounds, particularly deep puncture wounds, not via inhalation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Rickettsia rickettsii, the agent of Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever, is also transmitted by arthropod vectors (ticks), not through contaminated wounds with soil.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Pathogen | Primary Mode of Entry | Associated Disease |\n|---|---|---|\n| Neisseria meningitidis | Respiratory droplets | Meningitis, Meningococcemia |\n| Corynebacterium diphtheriae | Respiratory droplets | Diphtheria |\n| Clostridium tetani | Contaminated wounds | Tetanus |\n| Borrelia burgdorferi | Arthropod vector (ticks) | Lyme Disease |\n| Rickettsia rickettsii | Arthropod vector (ticks) | Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know your vectors! Ticks transmit Lyme (Borrelia) and RMSF (Rickettsia).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn physical exam, an expanding erythematous rash with central clearing (erythema migrans) is the classic early sign of Lyme disease, often resembling a \"bull's-eye\" target. This rash is a clinical diagnosis and typically does not require advanced imaging.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) 2020 Guidelines for the Prevention, Diagnosis, and Treatment of Lyme Disease. These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for managing all stages of Lyme disease, emphasizing early diagnosis and appropriate antibiotic therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Neisseria meningitidis – sexually transmitted entry | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Corynebacterium diphtheriae – food-borne entry | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Clostridium tetani – inhalation entry | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Borrelia burgdorferi – arthropod vector-borne entry | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Rickettsia rickettsii – contami-nated wound with soil entry | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Borrelia burgorferi is spread by ticks and is caused by Lyme disease. Rickettsia rickettsii is also ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
