  "id": 140147,
  "question": "Opioids:\nA Commonly cause diarrhoea\nB Act only centrally\nC Mediate most of their beneficial effects and side effects through V-receptors\nD Lead to tolerance\nE Can be reversed by flumazenil",
  "options": {
    "A": "Commonly cause diarrhoea",
    "B": "Act only centrally",
    "C": "Mediate most of their beneficial effects and side effects through V-receptors",
    "D": "Lead to tolerance",
    "E": "Can be reversed by flumazenil"
  },
  "answer": "D) Opioids are mainly used in the hospital setting for their analgesic properties. They are now believed to act both peripherally (outside the central nervous system) and within the CNS itself. Unfortunately, opioids exert most of their beneficial effects and side effects through the same opioid receptor (m-receptors). It is therefore unlikely that we will ever be able to develop a synthetic opioid agent that has the analgesic properties of other opioids without their unpleasant side effects.\nOpioids induce side effects through both excitatory and inhibitory mechanisms. Excitatory effects are:\n\n• Pinpoint pupils (direct effect of opioids on the Edinger–Westphal nucleus) • Nausea and vomiting (direct effect on the area postrema)\n• Pruritus (due to mast-cell degranulation and histamine release) • Dysphoria and euphoria (direct effect on the CNS)\nInhibitory effects are:\n\n• Cardiorespiratory depression • Sedation\n• Relaxation of smooth muscles – constipation, urinary retention\n\nConstipation and nausea/vomiting are common side effects of opioids. It is therefore always a good idea to prescribe laxatives and antiemetics whenever an opioid is prescribed.\nOpioids cause tolerance, dependence, and withdrawal with increasing use. Tolerance means increasing dosages of the drug needed to be used in order to obtain the same effect.\nIt is important to know how to reverse the effects of opioids because opioid overdose may be fatal. Specific opioid antagonists include naloxone and naltrex-one. Flumazenil antagonizes the effects of benzodiazepines.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Opioids: Great pain relief, but tolerance is a real pain.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D. Opioids are well-known to cause tolerance, a critical pharmacological effect where increasing doses are required to achieve the same therapeutic effect over time.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOpioid tolerance is a fundamental concept in pain management, signifying a reduced response to a drug after repeated administration, necessitating higher doses for equivalent analgesia. This phenomenon is distinct from physical dependence and addiction but often coexists, contributing to the complexities of long-term opioid therapy and the risk of withdrawal symptoms upon cessation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Opioids commonly cause constipation due to relaxation of smooth muscles in the GI tract, not diarrhea.\nOption B (Incorrect): Opioids act both centrally within the CNS and peripherally, mediating effects in various tissues outside the brain and spinal cord.\nOption C (Incorrect): Opioids mediate most of their beneficial effects and side effects through mu (m)-receptors, not V-receptors (which are vasopressin receptors).\nOption E (Incorrect): Flumazenil is an antagonist for benzodiazepines, while opioid effects are specifically reversed by opioid antagonists like naloxone and naltrexone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Drug Class | Primary Receptor | Key Side Effects | Specific Antagonist |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Opioids | Mu (μ) | Constipation, respiratory depression, nausea, sedation, tolerance | Naloxone, Naltrexone |\n| Benzodiazepines | GABA-A | Sedation, respiratory depression, amnesia | Flumazenil |\n| Vasopressin | V1, V2 | Hypertension, water retention | Conivaptan, Tolvaptan |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Opioid tolerance means more drug for the same effect.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR or on physical exam, opioid overdose presents with classic pinpoint pupils, bradypnea, and decreased level of consciousness.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Clinical Practice Guideline for Prescribing Opioids (2022) emphasizes monitoring for tolerance and managing opioid-induced side effects.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Commonly cause diarrhoea | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Act only centrally | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Mediate most of their beneficial effects and side effects through V-recepto | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lead to tolerance | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Can be reversed by flumazenil | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Opioids are mainly used in the hospital setting for their analgesic properties. They are now believe** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
