  "question": "Type I hypersensitivity:\nA Is caused by antigen reacting with IgM antibodies\nB Results in mast-cell degranulation\nC Is characterized by the Arthus reaction\nD Takes 48–72 hours to develop\nE Is caused by the formation of antibody–antigen complexes",
  "options": {
    "A": "Is caused by antigen reacting with IgM antibodies",
    "B": "Results in mast-cell degranulation",
    "C": "Is characterized by the Arthus reaction",
    "D": "Takes 48–72 hours to develop",
    "E": "Is caused by the formation of antibody–antigen complexes"
  },
  "answer": "B) Hypersensitivity is a condition in which undesirable tissue damage follows the development of humoral or cell-mediated immunity. Gell and Coombs classified hypersensitivity reactions into four types. However, some also include a fifth type, as shown in the following.\nGell and Coombs’ classification of hypersensitivity reactions\n\n• Type I: Mast-cell degranulation mediated by pre-formed IgE bound to mast cells. Immediate (within minutes). Anaphylaxis, atopic allergies.\n• Type II: Antibodies directed towards antigens present on the surface of cells or tissue components. Humoral antibodies participate directly in injuring cells by predisposing them to phagocytosis or lysis. Initiates within several hours. Good examples are transfusion reactions, autoimmune haemolytic anaemia, and Goodpasture’s syndrome.\n• Type III: Formation of antibody–antigen complexes (immune complex mediated). Initiates within several hours. Good examples are the Arthus reaction, serum sickness, and SLE.\n• Type IV: Delayed type of hypersensitivity. Cell-mediated. T-lymphocytes involved. Granulomatous conditions. Initiation time is 24–72 hours. Contact dermatitis.\n• Type V: Due to the formation of stimulatory autoantibodies in autoimmune conditions such as Graves’ disease.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When IgE meets antigen, mast cells explode, and so does the patient's blood pressure!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, \"Results in mast-cell degranulation.\" Type I hypersensitivity, also known as immediate hypersensitivity, is fundamentally driven by the binding of antigens to IgE antibodies on mast cells, leading to their rapid degranulation and release of inflammatory mediators.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nType I hypersensitivity is an immediate reaction mediated by IgE antibodies. Upon re-exposure to an antigen, these antigens cross-link IgE molecules pre-bound to Fc receptors on mast cells and basophils. This cross-linking triggers a cascade of intracellular events, culminating in the rapid degranulation of these cells. The release of pre-formed mediators like histamine, tryptase, and proteases, along with newly synthesized mediators such as leukotrienes and prostaglandins, causes the characteristic symptoms of allergic reactions, ranging from localized urticaria to systemic anaphylaxis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Type I hypersensitivity is mediated by IgE antibodies, not IgM. IgM is primarily involved in the primary immune response and is not the key mediator for Type I reactions.\nOption C (Incorrect): The Arthus reaction is a classic example of a Type III hypersensitivity reaction, which is characterized by immune complex formation, not Type I.\nOption D (Incorrect): Type I hypersensitivity is an immediate reaction, developing within minutes. Reactions taking 48–72 hours to develop are characteristic of Type IV (delayed-type) hypersensitivity.\nOption E (Incorrect): The formation of antibody–antigen complexes (immune complexes) is the hallmark of Type III hypersensitivity reactions, not Type I.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Type | Mediator | Time | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| I | IgE, Mast cells | Minutes | Anaphylaxis, Atopic allergies |\n| II | IgG, IgM | Hours | Transfusion reactions, Autoimmune hemolytic anemia |\n| III | Immune complexes (Ag-Ab) | Hours | Arthus reaction, Serum sickness, SLE |\n| IV | T-lymphocytes | 24-72 hours | Contact dermatitis, Granulomatous conditions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: IgE + Mast cells = Immediate Type I reaction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn severe anaphylaxis, imaging might show diffuse airway edema (laryngeal/tracheal narrowing on X-ray/CT), pulmonary edema, or signs of hypoperfusion. Intraoperatively, one might observe sudden hypotension, bronchospasm, urticaria, or angioedema.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAnaphylaxis: a practice parameter update 2015. J Allergy Clin Immunol. 2015. This guideline recommends prompt recognition and epinephrine administration as the cornerstone of treatment for anaphylaxis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is caused by antigen reacting with IgM antibodies | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Results in mast-cell degranulation | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Is characterized by the Arthus reaction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Takes 48–72 hours to develop | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Is caused by the formation of antibody–antigen complexes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Hypersensitivity is a condition in which undesirable tissue damage follows the development of humora** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "B"
