  "options": {
    "A": "All muscles of the tongue are innervated via the hypoglossal nerve",
    "B": "Special taste sensation on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is through the mandibular divi-sion of the trigeminal nerve",
    "C": "It is composed of smooth musculature",
    "D": "Genioglossus muscle protrudes the tongue",
    "E": "Its epithelium is of the glandular columnar variety"
  },
  "answer": "D) The tongue is composed of striated, voluntary, or skeletal muscle, not smooth muscle. The tongue assists in the formation of a food bolus and propagation towards the back of the mouth and thence into the oesophagus. The tongue also plays a key role in the suckling reflex in neonates, in the articulation of speech and the special sense of taste. Its epithelium is composed of stratified squamous (protective) epithelium as, like the skin, it is subject to ‘wear and tear’. Tumours arising from the tongue are therefore typically squamous cell carcinomas.\nSpecial taste sensation is by way of the chorda tympani division of the facial nerve for the anterior two-thirds of the tongue and the glossopharyngeal nerve for the posterior one-third. Taste sensation on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is therefore commonly lost in a facial nerve (or Bell’s) palsy. Somatic sensation is by way of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve for the anterior two-thirds of the tongue (lingual nerve) and the glossopharyngeal nerve for the posterior\none-third.\nAll the muscles of the tongue are supplied by the hypoglossal or 12th cranial nerve, with the exception of the palatoglossus muscle which is supplied by the pharyngeal plexus of nerves (IX, X, and sympathetics). The hypoglossal nerve may be injured in a carotid endarterectomy or submandibular gland procedures. The most important muscle to know about is the genioglossus muscle, which serves to protrude the tongue. When genioglossal muscle tone is lost, as in someone with a decreased level of consciousness, or a fractured mandible (where the genioglossus muscle arises), the tongue falls back and obstructs the airway, rapidly resulting in hypoxia and death if basic life support measures are not quickly instigated.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't let the tongue be a silent killer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, which accurately identifies the genioglossus muscle as the primary protruder of the tongue. This function is critically important for maintaining airway patency and preventing obstruction.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe genioglossus is the largest and most important extrinsic muscle of the tongue, originating from the mental spine of the mandible and fanning out into the tongue. Its contraction pulls the tongue forward and downward, preventing it from falling posteriorly and obstructing the pharynx. Loss of genioglossal tone, often seen in patients with decreased consciousness (e.g., during anesthesia, sedation, or coma) or in cases of mandibular fracture, can lead to rapid upper airway obstruction, hypoxia, and potentially death if not promptly recognized and managed.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Not all muscles of the tongue are innervated by the hypoglossal nerve; the palatoglossus muscle is a notable exception, receiving its motor supply from the pharyngeal plexus (via vagus nerve).\nOption B (Incorrect): Special taste sensation on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is conveyed by the chorda tympani branch of the facial nerve (CN VII), not the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve (CN V3), which provides general somatic sensation to this area.\nOption C (Incorrect): The tongue is composed of striated, voluntary (skeletal) muscle, allowing for precise and conscious movements, not smooth musculature.\nOption E (Incorrect): The tongue's epithelium is primarily stratified squamous, which is well-suited for protection against mechanical abrasion and chemical irritation from food, rather than glandular columnar epithelium.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Anterior 2/3 Tongue | Posterior 1/3 Tongue | General Tongue Muscles |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Special Taste** | Chorda Tympani (Facial N.) | Glossopharyngeal N. | N/A |\n| **Somatic Sensation** | Lingual N. (Mandibular Div. Trigeminal N.) | Glossopharyngeal N. | N/A |\n| **Motor Innervation** | N/A | N/A | Hypoglossal N. (except Palatoglossus) |\n| **Palatoglossus Motor** | N/A | N/A | Pharyngeal Plexus (IX, X, Sympathetics) |\n| **Muscle Type** | Striated, Voluntary | Striated, Voluntary | Striated, Voluntary |\n| **Epithelium** | Stratified Squamous | Stratified Squamous | Stratified Squamous |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Genioglossus: the tongue's airway guardian.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, during procedures like carotid endarterectomy or submandibular gland excision, the hypoglossal nerve is at risk of injury, which can manifest as tongue deviation towards the injured side upon protrusion. On imaging (e.g., MRI), loss of genioglossus tone can be visualized as posterior displacement of the tongue base, contributing to upper airway obstruction.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Anesthesiologists (ASA) Practice Guidelines for Management of the Difficult Airway (2022). Recommends strategies for maintaining airway patency, including maneuvers that address tongue base obstruction.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | All muscles of the tongue are innervated via the hypoglossal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Special taste sensation on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is through | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is composed of smooth musculature | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Genioglossus muscle protrudes the tongue | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Its epithelium is of the glandular columnar variety | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The tongue is composed of striated, voluntary, or skeletal muscle, not smooth muscle. The tongue ass** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
