  "question": "Type III Hypersensitivity:\nA Is mediated by specifically sensi-tized T-lymphocytes\nB May cause allergic rhinitis\nC Is a feature of nickel sensitivity\nD May occur in systemic lupus erythematosus\nE Is cell mediated",
  "options": {
    "A": "Is mediated by specifically sensi-tized T-lymphocytes",
    "B": "May cause allergic rhinitis",
    "C": "Is a feature of nickel sensitivity",
    "D": "May occur in systemic lupus erythematosus",
    "E": "Is cell mediated"
  },
  "answer": "D) Type III hypersensitivity reactions are mediated by antibodies. SLE is a type III hypersensitivity reaction where large amounts of immune complexes form between nuclear antigens and antibodies. Allergic rhinitis is a type I hypersensitivity reaction. Type IV reactions are cell-mediated through specifically sensitized\nT-lymphocytes. Nickel sensitivity is a Type IV hypersensitivity reaction.\nAllergic rhinitis is a Type I hypersensitivity reaction. SLE is a Type III hyper-sensitivity reaction where large amounts of immune complexes form between nuclear antigens and antibodies.\nLatex allergies can be one of three types:\n\n• Irritant contact dermatitis (non-immune)\n• Allergic contact dermatitis (Type IV hypersensitivity reaction)\n• Immediate hypersensitivity (Type I hypersensitivity reaction or anaphylaxis) – what everyone worries about!",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Immune complexes are the 'complex' culprits in Type III hypersensitivity!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, as Type III hypersensitivity reactions are characterized by the formation of immune complexes that deposit in tissues, leading to inflammation and damage. Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) is a classic example of a Type III hypersensitivity reaction, where autoantibodies form immune complexes with nuclear antigens.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nType III hypersensitivity involves the formation of antigen-antibody complexes (immune complexes) in the circulation. These complexes can deposit in various tissues, such as blood vessel walls, glomeruli, and joints. Once deposited, they activate the complement system and attract inflammatory cells like neutrophils, leading to tissue damage through the release of lysosomal enzymes and reactive oxygen species. In SLE, the body produces autoantibodies against self-antigens (e.g., DNA, histones), forming these pathogenic immune complexes that contribute to the multi-organ manifestations of the disease.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This describes a Type IV (delayed-type) hypersensitivity reaction, which is cell-mediated, not Type III.\nOption B (Incorrect): Allergic rhinitis is a classic example of a Type I (immediate) hypersensitivity reaction, mediated by IgE antibodies.\nOption C (Incorrect): Nickel sensitivity is a form of contact dermatitis, which is a Type IV (delayed-type) hypersensitivity reaction.\nOption E (Incorrect): Type III hypersensitivity is antibody-mediated through immune complexes, not directly cell-mediated. Cell-mediated reactions are characteristic of Type IV hypersensitivity.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hypersensitivity Type | Mediator | Mechanism | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Type I (Immediate) | IgE | Mast cell degranulation, histamine release | Allergic rhinitis, Anaphylaxis |\n| Type II (Cytotoxic) | IgG, IgM | Antibody-mediated cell destruction, complement activation | Hemolytic anemia, Goodpasture's Syndrome |\n| Type III (Immune Complex) | IgG, IgM (immune complexes) | Immune complex deposition, complement activation, inflammation | Systemic Lupus Erythematosus, Serum sickness |\n| Type IV (Delayed) | T-lymphocytes | T-cell mediated cytokine release, macrophage activation | Contact dermatitis (e.g., nickel), TB test |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the 'ABCD' mnemonic for hypersensitivity types: Anaphylactic, Body-mediated, Complex-mediated, Delayed.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn SLE, imaging might reveal joint effusions on X-ray/MRI, glomerulonephritis on renal biopsy (light microscopy showing immune complex deposits), or pericardial/pleural effusions on chest X-ray/CT, all indicative of systemic inflammation driven by immune complex deposition.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2019 European League Against Rheumatism (EULAR)/American College of Rheumatology (ACR) Classification Criteria for Systemic Lupus Erythematosus: These criteria emphasize the role of autoantibodies and clinical manifestations consistent with immune complex disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is mediated by specifically sensi-tized T-lymphocytes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | May cause allergic rhinitis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Is a feature of nickel sensitivity | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | May occur in systemic lupus erythematosus | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Is cell mediated | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Type III hypersensitivity reactions are mediated by antibodies. SLE is a type III hypersensitivity r** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
