  "question": "An 83-year-old man has chest pain, breathlessness, and ankle oedema. On clinical examination, cardiomegaly is identified and a subsequent diagnosis of viral myocarditis is made. Which of the following microorganisms is most likely responsible for this illness:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Rhinovirus",
    "B": "Mumps",
    "C": "Coronavirus",
    "D": "Adenovirus",
    "E": "Coxsackie B"
  },
  "answer": "E) 135. E: Coxsackie B\nMyocarditis is most commonly caused by Coxsackie group B virus and may be preceded by gastrointestinal or respiratory symptoms. Rhinoviruses, coronavi-ruses, and adenoviruses are associated with the common cold, influenza-like ill-nesses, and gastrointestinal disturbances. Mumps causes orchitis and parotitis/ parotidomegaly.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the heart aches from a virus, think Coxsackie B!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Coxsackie B because it is the most common viral cause of myocarditis, a condition characterized by chest pain, breathlessness, and cardiomegaly. The clinical presentation of heart failure symptoms in an elderly patient aligns with the known manifestations of Coxsackie B infection. This question tests knowledge of common viral etiologies for specific cardiac conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCoxsackie B virus, a member of the enterovirus family, has a known tropism for cardiac muscle cells. Infection can lead to direct viral damage to cardiomyocytes and trigger an autoimmune response, resulting in inflammation and necrosis of the myocardium. This process manifests clinically as myocarditis, often presenting with symptoms of heart failure like dyspnea and edema, and signs like cardiomegaly. The immune response can sometimes lead to chronic inflammation and dilated cardiomyopathy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Rhinovirus) (Incorrect): Rhinoviruses are primarily associated with the common cold and upper respiratory tract infections, not typically severe cardiac involvement like myocarditis.\nOption B (Mumps) (Incorrect): Mumps virus is classically known for causing parotitis (inflammation of salivary glands) and orchitis (inflammation of testes), not myocarditis as its primary or most common cardiac manifestation.\nOption C (Coronavirus) (Incorrect): While some coronaviruses (e.g., SARS-CoV-2) can cause myocarditis, the general association for 'Coronavirus' in this context is with common colds, influenza-like illnesses, and gastrointestinal disturbances, making it less likely than Coxsackie B for the *most common* viral myocarditis.\nOption D (Adenovirus) (Incorrect): Adenoviruses are commonly linked to respiratory infections, conjunctivitis, and gastroenteritis, but are less frequently implicated as the primary cause of viral myocarditis compared to Coxsackie B.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Microorganism | Primary Association | Cardiac Involvement |\n|---|---|---|\n| Coxsackie B | Viral Myocarditis, Pericarditis | Most common cause of viral myocarditis |\n| Rhinovirus | Common Cold, URI | Rare/mild |\n| Mumps | Parotitis, Orchitis | Rare myocarditis, usually mild |\n| Coronavirus | Common Cold, URI, GI (some strains: severe respiratory, myocarditis) | Variable, less common than Coxsackie B for general viral myocarditis |\n| Adenovirus | URI, Conjunctivitis, Gastroenteritis | Less common cause of myocarditis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Coxsackie B: The heart's most common viral foe.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, you would observe ventricular dysfunction, wall motion abnormalities, and potentially pericardial effusion. Cardiac MRI would show myocardial edema and late gadolinium enhancement, indicative of inflammation and fibrosis. Endomyocardial biopsy, if performed, would reveal inflammatory infiltrates and cardiomyocyte necrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2013 European Society of Cardiology (ESC) Working Group on Myocardial and Pericardial Diseases Position Statement on Myocarditis. It recommends diagnostic criteria and management strategies for myocarditis, including viral etiologies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rhinovirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mumps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Coronavirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Adenovirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Coxsackie B | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 135. E: Coxsackie B\nMyocarditis is most commonly caused by Coxsackie group B virus and may be preced** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
