  "answer": "D) 145. D: p53 and Rb-1 are tumour suppressor genes\nTumour suppressor genes encode proteins that negatively regulate cell prolifera-tion and thus suppress tumour growth. p53 and Rb-1 are good examples located on chromosomes 17 and 13, respectively. Normal p53 is the so-called ‘guardian of the genome’ and triggers apoptosis and cell-cycle arrest in genetically damaged cells (i.e., it is pro-apoptotic). Mutations in p53 there-fore result in the propagation of genetically damaged cells and tumourigenesis. Indeed, approximately 50 per cent of human tumours contain mutations in the\np53 gene. p53-related cancers are more aggressive and have a poorer prognosis.\nIn contrast to oncogenes, tumours caused by tumour suppressor genes are gener-ally caused by mutations that result in a loss of function of the gene product; neoplastic growth resulting from the loss of the protective role of tumour sup-pressor genes. Loss of tumour suppressor function usually requires the inacti-vation of both alleles of the gene, so that all of the protective effect of tumour suppressor genes is lost. That is, tumour suppressor genes are generally deemed to behave in a recessive manner.\nCellular proliferation is therefore tightly regulated by two sets of opposing functioning genes: the growth-promoting genes (proto-oncogenes) and the nega-tive cell-cycle regulators (tumour suppressor genes). Abnormal activation of proto-oncogenes and/or loss of function of tumour suppressor genes leads to the transformation of a normal cell into a cancer cell.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Guardians of the genome, p53 and Rb-1 keep cancer at bay.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer D accurately identifies p53 and Rb-1 as classic examples of tumor suppressor genes. These genes are crucial for regulating cell proliferation and preventing uncontrolled growth, acting as the body's natural defense against cancer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTumor suppressor genes encode proteins that negatively regulate cell proliferation, effectively suppressing tumor growth. p53, often called the 'guardian of the genome,' is a prime example, located on chromosome 17. It triggers apoptosis and cell-cycle arrest in genetically damaged cells, acting as a pro-apoptotic factor to eliminate potentially cancerous cells. Rb-1, on chromosome 13, is another critical tumor suppressor that controls cell cycle progression. The loss of function of both alleles of these genes is typically required for neoplastic transformation, highlighting their recessive nature in cancer development.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): They encode proteins that negatively regulate growth, not positively. Their function is to halt or slow cell division.\nOption B (Incorrect): Tumor suppressor genes generally behave in a recessive manner, requiring inactivation of both alleles for their protective effect to be lost.\nOption C (Incorrect): Loss-of-function (not gain-of-function) of tumor suppressor genes results in neoplastic growth, as their protective role is removed.\nOption E (Incorrect): p53 normally functions as a pro-apoptotic factor, initiating programmed cell death in damaged cells, not preventing it.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Tumor Suppressor Genes | Proto-Oncogenes |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Function** | Negatively regulate cell proliferation; suppress tumor growth | Positively regulate cell proliferation; promote growth |\n| **Mode of Action** | Loss of function leads to cancer (recessive) | Gain of function leads to cancer (dominant) |\n| **Examples** | p53, Rb-1, BRCA1/2 | RAS, MYC, HER2 |\n| **Effect of Mutation** | Loss of protective role, allowing uncontrolled growth | Uncontrolled cell division, promoting tumor formation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tumor suppressors are the brakes; oncogenes are the gas.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly visible, the absence of functional tumor suppressor genes like p53 or Rb-1 is often correlated with more aggressive tumor phenotypes seen on imaging (e.g., larger size, rapid growth, metastasis) or observed intraoperatively (e.g., poorly differentiated tumors, extensive local invasion). Genetic testing of tumor biopsies can confirm mutations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment: Colorectal (Version 1.2023) or Breast/Ovarian/Pancreatic (Version 2.2024) frequently discuss germline mutations in tumor suppressor genes (e.g., p53 in Li-Fraumeni syndrome, BRCA1/2) and recommend specific screening and management strategies based on these findings.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | They encode proteins that posi-tively regulate growth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | They behave in a dominant fashion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gain-of-function of tumour sup-pressor genes results in neoplastic growth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | p53 and Rb-1 are tumour sup-pressor genes | ✅ Correct |\n| E | p53 normally functions as an anti-apoptotic factor | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 145. D: p53 and Rb-1 are tumour suppressor genes\nTumour suppressor genes encode proteins that negati** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
