  "question": "With regard to the transpyloric plane (of Addison):",
  "options": {
    "A": "It is halfway between the supra-sternal notch and umbilicus",
    "B": "It lies at the level of T12",
    "C": "It lies at the origin of the inferior mesenteric artery",
    "D": "It lies level with the hilum of the kidneys",
    "E": "It is the point at which the aorta bifurcates"
  },
  "answer": "D) 147. D: It lies level with the hilum of the kidneys\nThe transpyloric plane (of Addison) is an important landmark. It lies halfway between the suprasternal notch and the symphysis pubis at the level of L1. It coincides with the following:\n• L1 vertebra\n• Fundus of gallbladder • Hilum of kidneys\n• Hilum of spleen\n• Pylorus of the stomach (hence the name transpyloric) • Termination of the spinal cord in adults\n• Neck of pancreas\n• Origin of the portal vein\nSection 3: SBA Answers and Explanations 285\n• Origin of the superior (not inferior) mesenteric artery • Duodenojejunal flexure\n• Attachment of transverse mesocolon • Tip of 9th costal cartilage\nThe aorta bifurcates at the level of L4, not L1.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 L1: The transpyloric plane, a landmark for many, a mystery to none!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, stating that the transpyloric plane lies level with the hilum of the kidneys. This plane is a crucial anatomical landmark, and its association with the renal hila is one of its defining characteristics.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe transpyloric plane, also known as Addison's plane, is a horizontal line located halfway between the suprasternal notch and the symphysis pubis, typically at the level of the L1 vertebra. Its significance stems from the multitude of vital structures it transects or coincides with. These include the pylorus of the stomach (giving it its name), the fundus of the gallbladder, the hilum of both kidneys and spleen, the neck of the pancreas, the origin of the superior mesenteric artery, and the duodenojejunal flexure. Understanding these relationships is fundamental for surgical planning, diagnostic imaging interpretation, and anatomical localization.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): It is halfway between the supra-sternal notch and umbilicus. The transpyloric plane is halfway between the suprasternal notch and the symphysis pubis, not the umbilicus.\nOption B (Incorrect): It lies at the level of T12. The transpyloric plane lies at the level of the L1 vertebra, not T12.\nOption C (Incorrect): It lies at the origin of the inferior mesenteric artery. The transpyloric plane coincides with the origin of the superior mesenteric artery, not the inferior mesenteric artery.\nOption E (Incorrect): It is the point at which the aorta bifurcates. The aorta bifurcates at the level of L4, which is significantly lower than the transpyloric plane at L1.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Landmark/Plane | Vertebral Level | Key Coincidences |\n|---|---|---|\n| Transpyloric Plane (Addison's) | L1 | Pylorus, Kidney Hila, SMA origin, Pancreatic neck |\n| Umbilicus | L3-L4 | Often used as a surface landmark, but variable |\n| Aortic Bifurcation | L4 | Common iliac arteries |\n| Inferior Mesenteric Artery Origin | L3 | Origin of IMA |\n| Supracristal Plane | L4 | Highest point of iliac crests, often used for lumbar puncture |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The transpyloric plane at L1 is a busy intersection for key abdominal structures.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a CT scan, the transpyloric plane can be identified by locating the L1 vertebral body and then tracing a horizontal line. This plane will typically transect the pylorus of the stomach, the neck of the pancreas, and the hila of the kidneys. Intraoperatively, it guides the surgeon to the location of these structures, particularly during upper abdominal procedures or when localizing the renal pedicles.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nGray's Anatomy (42nd Edition, 2020): This foundational anatomical text provides comprehensive details on the transpyloric plane and its associated structures, serving as the authoritative reference for such anatomical landmarks.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is halfway between the supra-sternal notch and umbilicus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It lies at the level of T12 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It lies at the origin of the inferior mesenteric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It lies level with the hilum of the kidneys | ✅ Correct |\n| E | It is the point at which the aorta bifurcates | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 147. D: It lies level with the hilum of the kidneys\nThe transpyloric plane (of Addison) is an import** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
