  "answer": "A) 152. A: Peptidoglycan\nProkaryotes have peptidoglycan in their cell walls, which makes them susceptible to penicillin. Sterol and endoplasmic reticulum are features of eukaryotic cells. Bacteria generally contain single, circular chromosomes (plasmids). Prokaryotes contain 70S, rather than 80S ribosomes, which are characteristic of eukaryotes.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Peptidoglycan: The bacterial signature, penicillin's target.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, Peptidoglycan. This question tests fundamental knowledge distinguishing prokaryotic from eukaryotic cells, a critical concept in understanding bacterial biology and antimicrobial action.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nProkaryotes, specifically bacteria, possess a unique cell wall composed of peptidoglycan, a polymer of sugars and amino acids. This structural component provides rigidity and protection, and its presence is a defining characteristic that differentiates them from eukaryotic cells. Clinically, the peptidoglycan cell wall is the primary target for many classes of antibiotics, such as penicillin, which inhibit its synthesis, leading to bacterial cell lysis and death.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Sterols in their membranes are characteristic of eukaryotic cells (e.g., cholesterol in animal cells), not prokaryotes, with a few exceptions like Mycoplasma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Prokaryotes typically have a single, circular chromosome (often referred to as a plasmid), not multiple linear chromosomes like eukaryotes.\nOption D (Incorrect): An endoplasmic reticulum is a complex membrane-bound organelle found in eukaryotic cells, involved in protein and lipid synthesis. Prokaryotes lack membrane-bound organelles.\nOption E (Incorrect): Prokaryotes possess smaller 70S ribosomes, whereas eukaryotes have larger 80S ribosomes. This difference is exploited by certain antibiotics targeting bacterial protein synthesis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Prokaryotes (Bacteria)         | Eukaryotes (Human Cells)       |\n|---------------------|--------------------------------|--------------------------------|\n| Cell Wall           | Peptidoglycan (most)           | Cellulose/Chitin (plants/fungi), None (animals) |\n| Membrane Sterols    | Absent (except Mycoplasma)     | Present (e.g., cholesterol)    |\n| Chromosomes         | Single, circular (plasmid)     | Multiple, linear               |\n| Endoplasmic Reticulum | Absent                         | Present                        |\n| Ribosome Size       | 70S                            | 80S                            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peptidoglycan is the bacterial Achilles' heel, targeted by penicillin.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile not directly visualized, the presence of peptidoglycan is inferred by Gram staining (Gram-positive vs. Gram-negative) of intraoperative cultures, guiding empiric antibiotic choices.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nInfectious Diseases Society of America (IDSA) Guidelines for the Treatment of Antimicrobial-Resistant Gram-Negative Infections (2022) recommend specific antibiotics based on bacterial cell wall characteristics and resistance patterns.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Peptidoglycan | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Sterols in their membranes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 2–6 chromosomes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | An endoplasmic reticulum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Larger 80S ribosomes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 152. A: Peptidoglycan\nProkaryotes have peptidoglycan in their cell walls, which makes them susceptib** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
