  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Omentum: The abdomen's fatty, four-layered, surgical superhero.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is correct because the greater omentum provides a well-established surgical route to access the lesser sac, typically by incising between the greater curvature of the stomach and the transverse colon. This anatomical relationship is crucial for various intra-abdominal procedures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe greater omentum, a four-layered peritoneal fold, is not only a route to the lesser sac but also a vital surgical tool. Its rich vascularity, supplied by the right and left gastroepiploic arteries, allows it to be mobilized for buttressing anastomoses or performing omental patch repairs for perforated ulcers. Often called the 'great policeman of the abdomen,' it localizes infection by adhering to inflamed areas, preventing generalized peritonitis, and can plug hernial sacs, demonstrating its paramount surgical importance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The text explicitly states the greater omentum is of 'paramount surgical importance,' contradicting this option.\nOption B (Incorrect): The greater omentum is supplied by the right and left gastroepiploic arteries, not the gastric arteries.\nOption C (Incorrect): The greater omentum is formed from a double sheet of peritoneum, fused and folded, comprising four layers, not two.\nOption E (Incorrect): The anterior layers of the greater omentum descend from the greater curvature of the stomach, while the lesser omentum arises from the lesser curvature.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Greater Omentum | Lesser Omentum |\n|---|---|---|\n| Layers | Four | Two |\n| Origin | Greater curvature of stomach | Lesser curvature of stomach & proximal duodenum |\n| Arterial Supply | Gastroepiploic arteries | Gastric & Hepatic arteries |\n| Surgical Importance | High (infection localization, patch repair, access to lesser sac) | Moderate (forms part of lesser sac boundary, contains portal triad) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The 'great policeman' always knows the way to the lesser sac.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the greater omentum is easily identified as a fatty, apron-like structure overlying the intestines. Access to the lesser sac is typically achieved by incising the avascular plane of the greater omentum between the greater curvature of the stomach and the transverse colon, or by dividing the gastrocolic ligament.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nWorld Society of Emergency Surgery (WSES) Guidelines for the Management of Peptic Ulcer Perforation (2020): Recommends omental patch repair (Graham patch) as a standard procedure for small, uncomplicated perforated peptic ulcers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It has no surgical importance | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is supplied by the right and left gastric arteries | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is two layers thick | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It provides a route of access to the lesser sac | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The anterior layers descend from the lesser curvature of the stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 157. D: It provides a route of access to the lesser sac\nThe greater omentum (or gastrocolic omentum)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
