  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Small islets, big impact: endocrine pancreas, metabolic maestro.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, stating that Islets of Langerhans constitute only 2% of the pancreatic volume. This is accurate, highlighting the disproportionately small volume of endocrine tissue compared to its vital physiological role.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe endocrine pancreas, composed of the Islets of Langerhans, is a ductless system, secreting hormones directly into the bloodstream. While small in volume (approximately 2% of the gland), these islets are crucial for metabolic regulation. The remaining pancreatic volume is predominantly exocrine tissue (80%) and ducts/blood vessels. This anatomical distinction underscores the specialized function of endocrine cells in systemic hormone delivery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The endocrine pancreas, by definition, secretes hormones directly into the bloodstream, not into a highly branched ductal system. Ducts are characteristic of exocrine glands.\nOption B (Incorrect): Glucagon is secreted from alpha (α)-islet cells, not beta (β)-islet cells. Beta cells are responsible for insulin secretion.\nOption D (Incorrect): Somatostatin is secreted from delta (δ)-islet cells, not alpha (α)-islet cells. Alpha cells secrete glucagon.\nOption E (Incorrect): Glucagon has a reciprocal action to insulin; it is glycogenolytic (breaks down glycogen) and gluconeogenic (forms new glucose), not stimulatory for glycogenesis (glycogen formation).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Islet Cell Type | Hormone Secreted | Primary Action |\n|-----------------|------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Alpha (α)       | Glucagon         | Glycogenolysis, Gluconeogenesis (raises blood glucose) |\n| Beta (β)        | Insulin          | Glucose uptake, Glycogenesis (lowers blood glucose) |\n| Delta (δ)       | Somatostatin     | Inhibits insulin and glucagon secretion |\n| F (PP)          | Pancreatic Polypeptide | Regulates pancreatic exocrine and endocrine function |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Islets are tiny but mighty, regulating metabolism with precision.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., CT, MRI), the pancreas is visualized, but individual islets are too small to be seen. Pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors (PNETs) arising from islet cells may appear as hypervascular lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Neuroendocrine Tumors (2023) recommend imaging and biochemical workup for suspected functional or non-functional PNETs.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It secretes hormones into a highly branched ductal system | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Glucagon is secreted from b-islet cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Islets of Langerhans make up only 2 per cent of the volume of the gland | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Somatostatin is secreted from a-islet cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Glucagon stimulates glycogenesis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 158. C: Islets of Langerhans make up only 2 per cent of the volume of the gland\nThe endocrine tissue** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
