  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 HIV: The ultimate T-cell terrorist.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, as HIV, the virus causing acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS), specifically targets and destroys CD4 T-lymphocytes. This destruction leads to severe immunodeficiency, which is the defining characteristic of AIDS.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHIV exhibits tropism for CD4 T-lymphocytes, binding to the CD4 receptor and co-receptors (CCR5 or CXCR4) to gain entry into these crucial immune cells. Once inside, the viral reverse transcriptase converts its RNA genome into DNA, which integrates into the host cell's genome. Viral replication within these cells ultimately leads to their lysis and death, progressively depleting the CD4 T-cell count and compromising the adaptive immune system. This severe lymphopenia renders the host susceptible to opportunistic infections and malignancies characteristic of AIDS.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): HIV possesses a single-stranded RNA genome, not a double-stranded DNA genome. It is a retrovirus.\nOption B (Incorrect): HIV is an enveloped virus, meaning it has an outer lipid bilayer derived from the host cell membrane.\nOption C (Incorrect): HIV is a retrovirus, and a defining feature of retroviruses is the presence of reverse transcriptase, an enzyme crucial for converting its RNA genome into DNA.\nOption D (Incorrect): HIV is a member of the retrovirus family, specifically the Lentivirus genus, not the adenovirus group. Adenoviruses are DNA viruses.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | HIV (Retrovirus) | Adenovirus |\n|---|---|---|\n| Genome Type | Single-stranded RNA | Double-stranded DNA |\n| Envelope | Present | Absent |\n| Reverse Transcriptase | Present | Absent |\n| Primary Target Cells | CD4 T-lymphocytes | Epithelial cells (respiratory, GI, ocular) |\n| Disease | AIDS, immunodeficiency | Respiratory infections, conjunctivitis, gastroenteritis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HIV = Retrovirus + RNA + Reverse Transcriptase + CD4 destruction.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging in AIDS patients often reveals opportunistic infections like Pneumocystis pneumonia (diffuse ground-glass opacities on CT), Kaposi's sarcoma (cutaneous lesions, visceral nodules), or CNS toxoplasmosis (ring-enhancing lesions on MRI). Intraoperatively, one might encounter lymphadenopathy or unusual infections.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n\"Guidelines for the Use of Antiretroviral Agents in Adults and Adolescents with HIV\" (2023) by the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) recommends prompt initiation of antiretroviral therapy (ART) for all individuals with HIV to suppress viral replication, preserve immune function, and prevent disease progression.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A double-stranded genome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lacks a viral envelope | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lacks reverse transcriptase | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is a member of the adenovirus group | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Destroys CD4 T-lymphocytes | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 160. E: Destroys CD4 T-lymphocytes\nHIV is the virus responsible for causing AIDS. It multiplies in C** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
