  "id": 140203,
  "question": "A mother notices that her newborn baby boy is drool-ing excessively; on feeding him, he swallows normally, but moments later starts to cough and appears to choke on the milk, which is brought up through his nose. Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Oesophageal atresia",
    "B": "Duodenal atresia",
    "C": "Small bowel atresia",
    "D": "Gastric outlet obstruction",
    "E": "Congenital diaphragmatic hernia"
  },
  "answer": "A) 164. A: Oesophageal atresia Oesophageal atresia is a congenital condition affecting 1 in 3000–4500 births. It is a developmental disorder of the oesophagus, which results in the oesophagus ending as a blind-ended pit. Only 10 per cent of those born with this congenital condition are born with this in isolation, with the remainder having some other form of congenital abnormality. Two-thirds of those born with this condition also have a tracheo-oesophageal fistula present. Other associated abnormali-ties include vertebral anomalies, anorectal anomalies, cardiac, renal, and limb malformations – the so-called VACTERL association. Diagnosis is confirmed by passing a nasogastric tube, which subsequently coils in the lower oesophagus and is visible on chest X-ray. It is considered a surgical emergency.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Drool, choke, and nose-milk flow? Esophageal atresia, you know!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Oesophageal atresia. The classic presentation of excessive drooling, choking, and regurgitation of milk through the nose immediately after feeding in a newborn is pathognomonic for oesophageal atresia, indicating an inability for milk to pass into the stomach.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nOesophageal atresia is a congenital anomaly where the oesophagus ends in a blind pouch, preventing the passage of food to the stomach. The excessive drooling occurs because saliva cannot be swallowed. Upon feeding, milk accumulates in the blind-ended oesophagus, leading to regurgitation, coughing, and choking, often with milk exiting through the nose. The presence of a tracheo-oesophageal fistula (common in two-thirds of cases) can exacerbate respiratory symptoms by allowing milk to enter the airway. This condition is a surgical emergency and is often associated with other congenital anomalies as part of the VACTERL association.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Duodenal atresia) (Incorrect): Presents with bilious vomiting, abdominal distension, and a 'double bubble' sign on X-ray, typically without the immediate choking/drooling on first feeds.\nOption C (Small bowel atresia) (Incorrect): Presents with bilious vomiting and abdominal distension, usually later than duodenal atresia, and does not cause immediate choking/drooling.\nOption D (Gastric outlet obstruction) (Incorrect): Typically presents with non-bilious projectile vomiting, often later in infancy (e.g., pyloric stenosis), and does not cause immediate choking/drooling or nasal regurgitation.\nOption E (Congenital diaphragmatic hernia) (Incorrect): Primarily causes severe respiratory distress due to lung hypoplasia and mediastinal shift, often with a scaphoid abdomen, not primarily feeding intolerance with choking and drooling.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Key Symptoms | Diagnostic Clue | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Oesophageal Atresia | Excessive drooling, choking/coughing with feeds, nasal regurgitation | Inability to pass NGT, coiled NGT on X-ray | Surgical repair |\n| Duodenal Atresia | Bilious vomiting, abdominal distension | 'Double bubble' sign on X-ray | Surgical repair |\n| Pyloric Stenosis | Non-bilious projectile vomiting (2-8 weeks old), palpable 'olive' | Ultrasound: elongated pyloric channel, thickened muscle | Pyloromyotomy |\n| Hirschsprung's Disease | Failure to pass meconium, abdominal distension, bilious vomiting | Rectal biopsy: absence of ganglion cells | Surgical resection of aganglionic segment |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Newborn drooling and choking on first feed? Think oesophageal atresia.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, a nasogastric tube will be seen coiled in the upper oesophageal pouch. Intraoperatively, the blind-ending upper and lower oesophageal segments are identified, often with a tracheo-oesophageal fistula to the distal segment.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) Clinical Report 2014: Management of Esophageal Atresia and Tracheoesophageal Fistula. Recommends early diagnosis and surgical correction, often with a primary anastomosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Oesophageal atresia | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Duodenal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Small bowel atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Gastric outlet obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Congenital diaphragmatic hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 164. A: Oesophageal atresia Oesophageal atresia is a congenital condition affecting 1 in 3000–4500 b** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
