  "question": "A newborn presents with pro-fuse bilious vomiting at birth with fullness in the epigastric region. AXR shows the ‘double bubble’ sign. Which of the following pathologies is this associated with?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Oesophageal atresia",
    "B": "Congenital intestinal obstruction",
    "C": "Gastric outlet obstruction",
    "D": "Duodenal atresia",
    "E": "Meconium ileus"
  },
  "answer": "D) 165. D: Duodenal atresia The incidence of duodenal atresia is 1 in 5000 births in the UK. The ‘double bubble’ sign indicates gas in the stomach and proximal duodenum. If not treated it becomes fatal as a result of fluid shifts and electrolyte imbalances. Fullness in the epigastric region is a result of the stomach being full of gas. In oesophageal atresia the baby typically presents with choking rather than vomiting. In gastric outlet obstruction there is no bile in the vomit and, most importantly, it presents later at about 4 weeks whereas duodenal atresia presents at birth. In congenital intestinal obstruction a plain film will show more pathognomonic features of obstruction. There is an association of duodenal atresia with Down’s syndrome.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Double bubble, double trouble, unless you fix it on the double!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Duodenal atresia. The classic 'double bubble' sign on AXR in a newborn with profuse bilious vomiting and epigastric fullness is pathognomonic for duodenal atresia, indicating complete obstruction at the duodenum.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDuodenal atresia results from failed recanalization of the duodenal lumen during fetal development, leading to complete obstruction. This prevents passage of gastric and duodenal contents, causing distension of the stomach and proximal duodenum, which appears as two distinct gas-filled bubbles on plain radiography. The obstruction is distal to the ampulla of Vater, hence the presence of bile in the vomitus. Its presentation at birth with bilious vomiting is a critical diagnostic clue, and it has a known association with Down's syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Oesophageal atresia typically presents with choking, drooling, and respiratory distress due to inability to swallow, not primarily bilious vomiting and a 'double bubble' sign.\nOption B (Incorrect): While duodenal atresia is a form of congenital intestinal obstruction, 'congenital intestinal obstruction' is too broad and less specific than duodenal atresia, which is uniquely identified by the 'double bubble' sign.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gastric outlet obstruction (e.g., pyloric stenosis) typically presents later, around 4-6 weeks of age, and the vomiting is non-bilious as the obstruction is proximal to the bile duct entry.\nOption E (Incorrect): Meconium ileus is an obstruction of the small intestine by abnormally thick meconium, often associated with cystic fibrosis. Imaging typically shows a 'ground glass' appearance or dilated loops, not the specific 'double bubble' of duodenal atresia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Presentation | Key Imaging | Vomit Type |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Duodenal Atresia | Bilious vomiting at birth, epigastric fullness | 'Double Bubble' sign on AXR | Bilious |\n| Oesophageal Atresia | Choking, drooling, respiratory distress at birth | Coiled NG tube in oesophagus, absent stomach gas | Non-bilious (regurgitation) |\n| Pyloric Stenosis | Non-bilious projectile vomiting (4-6 weeks) | 'String sign' or 'shoulder sign' on UGI, 'target sign' on ultrasound | Non-bilious |\n| Meconium Ileus | Abdominal distension, failure to pass meconium | 'Ground glass' appearance, dilated loops, microcolon | Bilious (if obstruction is distal) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bilious vomiting in a neonate is always a surgical emergency until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn AXR, the 'double bubble' sign represents distended stomach and proximal duodenum separated by the pylorus. Intraoperatively, a dilated stomach and proximal duodenum will be evident, with a collapsed distal duodenum, confirming the atresia.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) guidelines on neonatal surgical emergencies emphasize prompt recognition and management of intestinal obstructions like duodenal atresia to prevent complications.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Oesophageal atresia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Congenital intestinal obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gastric outlet obstruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Duodenal atresia | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Meconium ileus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 165. D: Duodenal atresia The incidence of duodenal atresia is 1 in 5000 births in the UK. The ‘doubl** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
