  "id": 140209,
  "question": "A 42-year-old woman undergoes right total mastectomy with axil-lary lymph node clearance for breast cancer. Two days post-operatively it was noted that she had winging of her right scapula. This is most likely caused by damage to which of the following nerves?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Musculocutaneous nerve",
    "B": "Axillary nerve",
    "C": "Long thoracic nerve",
    "D": "Pectoral nerve",
    "E": "Subscapular nerve"
  },
  "answer": "C) 170. C: Long thoracic nerve The long thoracic nerve of Bell (C5, C6, C7) supplies the serratus anterior muscle and is responsible for lateral rotation and protraction of the scapula. Owing to its long, relatively superficial course it is susceptible to damage and can be damaged during breast surgery. Injuries can also result from direct trauma or stretching during sports. The winged scapula is most prominent when the patient pushes the outstretched arm against a wall.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Preserve the Long Thoracic, or your patient will be 'winged' for life!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, the Long thoracic nerve. Damage to this nerve during axillary dissection is a well-known complication, leading to paralysis of the serratus anterior muscle and the characteristic finding of scapular winging.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe long thoracic nerve (of Bell) originates from the ventral rami of C5, C6, and C7. It descends on the superficial surface of the serratus anterior muscle, which it innervates. The serratus anterior is crucial for protraction and upward rotation of the scapula, anchoring it to the thoracic wall. Its long, superficial course makes it particularly vulnerable during axillary lymph node clearance, especially in the superior and lateral aspects of the axilla. When the serratus anterior is paralyzed, the medial border of the scapula becomes prominent, especially when the patient pushes against a wall, creating the 'winged' appearance.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The Musculocutaneous nerve innervates the anterior compartment of the arm (biceps, brachialis, coracobrachialis) and provides sensory innervation to the lateral forearm. Its damage would affect elbow flexion and forearm sensation, not scapular stability.\nOption B (Incorrect): The Axillary nerve (C5, C6) innervates the deltoid and teres minor muscles, responsible for shoulder abduction and external rotation, respectively. Damage would result in impaired shoulder abduction and sensory loss over the lateral shoulder, not scapular winging.\nOption D (Incorrect): The Pectoral nerves (medial and lateral) innervate the pectoralis major and minor muscles. Damage would affect adduction and medial rotation of the arm, and depression of the shoulder, but not directly cause scapular winging.\nOption E (Incorrect): The Subscapular nerves (upper and lower) innervate the subscapularis and teres major muscles, involved in medial rotation and adduction of the arm. Damage would impair these movements, not lead to scapular winging.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Nerve | Origin | Innervates | Clinical Deficit |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Long Thoracic | C5, C6, C7 | Serratus Anterior | Scapular winging, difficulty with overhead arm movements |\n| Axillary | C5, C6 | Deltoid, Teres Minor | Loss of shoulder abduction, sensory loss over lateral shoulder |\n| Thoracodorsal | C6, C7, C8 | Latissimus Dorsi | Weakness in arm adduction, extension, internal rotation |\n| Medial Pectoral | C8, T1 | Pectoralis Major (sternocostal head), Pectoralis Minor | Weakness in arm adduction/medial rotation, shoulder depression |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Scapular winging = Long thoracic nerve = Serratus anterior.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, the long thoracic nerve is typically identified running on the superficial aspect of the serratus anterior muscle, often lateral to the lateral thoracic artery. It is a key structure to identify and preserve during axillary lymph node dissection. Post-operatively, physical examination reveals the medial border of the scapula protruding posteriorly, especially when the patient pushes against a wall or attempts to raise the arm overhead.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology: Breast Cancer (Version 4.2023). These guidelines emphasize meticulous surgical technique during axillary dissection to minimize nerve injury, including the long thoracic nerve, to preserve upper extremity function and quality of life.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Musculocutaneous nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Axillary nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Long thoracic nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Pectoral nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Subscapular nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 170. C: Long thoracic nerve The long thoracic nerve of Bell (C5, C6, C7) supplies the serratus anter** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "C"
