  "id": 140211,
  "question": "A 25-year-old female was involved in a road traffic accident and suffered a significant head injury. She is being monitored in the neurosurgical intensive care unit (ICU). Her BP is 100/70 and she has a HR) of 80 bpm. Her cur-rent intracranial pressure (ICP) is 10 mmHg. Which of the fol-lowing is her cerebral perfusion pressure?",
  "options": {
    "A": "70 mmHg",
    "B": "170 mmHg",
    "C": "90 mmHg",
    "D": "180 mmHg",
    "E": "40 mmHg"
  },
  "answer": "A) 172. A: 70 mmHg MAP is calculated using the formula: 1/3(pulse pressure) + diastolic pressure. In this case, MAP = 1/3(100 − 70) + 70 = 80 mmHg. CPP can be calculated using the MAP and ICP: CPP = MAP – ICP. In this case, CPP = 80 − 10 = 70 mmHg. Conservative management of raised ICP involves sedation, intubation keeping ICP at 10 mmHg and maintaining CPP at 60–70 mmHg. CPP is maintained by a phenomenon called autoregulation. Autoregulation is impaired in head injury patients and CPP <70 mmHg is associated with a poor outcome. Therefore, the priority is to maintain CPP as these patients are susceptible to brain injury caused by hypotension.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keep the brain fed: MAP minus ICP equals CPP!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is 70 mmHg, which is derived by first calculating the Mean Arterial Pressure (MAP) from the given blood pressure, and then subtracting the Intracranial Pressure (ICP) from the MAP. This calculation is fundamental for assessing brain perfusion in head injury patients.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCerebral Perfusion Pressure (CPP) is a critical parameter in neurocritical care, representing the net pressure gradient driving blood flow to the brain. It is calculated as MAP minus ICP. In this case, with a BP of 100/70 mmHg, the MAP is calculated as 70 + 1/3(100-70) = 80 mmHg. Subtracting the ICP of 10 mmHg yields a CPP of 70 mmHg. Maintaining adequate CPP, typically above 60-70 mmHg, is crucial in traumatic brain injury patients to prevent secondary brain injury, especially given that cerebral autoregulation is often impaired.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 170 mmHg is an arbitrary number and does not correspond to any physiological calculation related to CPP.\nOption C (Incorrect): 90 mmHg would result if MAP was incorrectly calculated as 100 mmHg (systolic pressure) and ICP was subtracted, or if MAP was 100 and ICP was 10.\nOption D (Incorrect): 180 mmHg is an arbitrary number and does not correspond to any physiological calculation related to CPP.\nOption E (Incorrect): 40 mmHg would result if MAP was incorrectly calculated as 50 mmHg, which is not derived from the given blood pressure.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Parameter | Definition | Normal Range | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **MAP** | Average arterial pressure during a single cardiac cycle | 70-100 mmHg | Indicator of organ perfusion pressure |\n| **ICP** | Pressure within the craniospinal compartment | 5-15 mmHg | Elevated ICP can compromise brain perfusion |\n| **CPP** | Net pressure gradient driving blood flow to the brain | 60-70 mmHg (TBI target) | Critical for preventing cerebral ischemia |\n| **Autoregulation** | Brain's ability to maintain constant cerebral blood flow despite changes in MAP | Effective MAP 50-150 mmHg | Often impaired in TBI, making CPP management vital |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: CPP = MAP - ICP. Always calculate MAP first!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a head CT, signs of elevated ICP might include effacement of sulci, compression of basal cisterns, midline shift, or hydrocephalus. Intraoperatively, during craniotomy, brain swelling and tightness would be observed, indicating high ICP.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nBrain Trauma Foundation Guidelines (2019): Recommend maintaining CPP between 60-70 mmHg in adult TBI patients to optimize outcomes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 70 mmHg | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 170 mmHg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 90 mmHg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | 180 mmHg | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | 40 mmHg | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 172. A: 70 mmHg MAP is calculated using the formula: 1/3(pulse pressure) + diastolic pressure. In th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "A"
