  "answer": "C) 174. C: Ewing sarcoma Ewing sarcoma is the second most common primary bone tumour in children. It typically affects the diaphysis of long tubular bones, particular the femur. Microscopic examination of the tumour reveals small, round blue cells of unknown origin. Patients typically present with pain and an enlarging mass. Osteosarcoma histology reveals malignant osteoblasts producing osteoid and are usually fairly aggressive tumours, with 20 per cent having pulmonary metas-tases on presentation. Myeloma is the most common primary bone tumour but typically affects patients over the age of 50. Malignant fibrous histiocytoma tumours on histology consist of spindle cells and giant cells.",
