  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't be blue, Ewing's the clue!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Ewing sarcoma. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the patient's age (9-year-old boy), the location of the mass (femur), and the characteristic histological finding of \"small round blue cells\" on bone biopsy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEwing sarcoma is the second most common primary bone tumor in children and adolescents, typically affecting the diaphysis of long bones like the femur. Its hallmark microscopic appearance is that of uniform, small, round cells with scant cytoplasm, often described as \"small round blue cells\" due to their basophilic nuclei. This distinct histology, combined with the patient's age and presentation of leg pain and a large femoral mass, makes Ewing sarcoma the most probable diagnosis among the given options.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Osteosarcoma typically presents with malignant osteoblasts producing osteoid, not small round blue cells. While it affects children, the histology is distinct.\nOption B (Incorrect): Chondrosarcoma is a cartilaginous tumor, and its histology would show malignant cartilage-forming cells, not small round blue cells. It is also less common in this young age group for primary bone tumors.\nOption D (Incorrect): Malignant fibrous histiocytoma (now often reclassified as undifferentiated pleomorphic sarcoma) typically shows spindle cells and giant cells on histology, which is different from small round blue cells.\nOption E (Incorrect): Myeloma is the most common primary bone tumor but predominantly affects older adults, typically over the age of 50, making it highly unlikely in a 9-year-old.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Ewing Sarcoma | Osteosarcoma | Myeloma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Typical Age** | Children/Adolescents | Adolescents/Young Adults | >50 years |\n| **Common Location** | Diaphysis of long bones (femur) | Metaphysis of long bones (distal femur, proximal tibia) | Axial skeleton (vertebrae, ribs, skull) |\n| **Histology** | Small round blue cells | Malignant osteoblasts producing osteoid | Plasma cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Small round blue cells in a child's long bone = Ewing.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, Ewing sarcoma often presents with a permeative lytic lesion with an \"onion skin\" periosteal reaction due to layers of new bone formation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Guidelines for Ewing Sarcoma (e.g., COG AEWS1031, 2010). These guidelines recommend a multidisciplinary approach including chemotherapy, surgery, and/or radiation therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Osteosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Chondrosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Ewing sarcoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Malignant fibrous histiocytoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Myeloma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 174. C: Ewing sarcoma Ewing sarcoma is the second most common primary bone tumour in children. It ty** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
