  "answer": "A) 191. A: Is a reversible transformation of one type of terminally differentiated cell into another fully differentiated cell type Metaplasia occurs as a tissue response to environmental stress. This causes a reversible transformation of one type of terminally differentiated cell into another fully differentiated cell type, for example, glandular metaplasia of the lower oesophagus (Barrett’s oesophagus) – a change from non-keratinising stratified squamous epithelium into columnar (glandular) epithelium.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Metaplasia: A cellular costume change, but they can always change back!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer accurately defines metaplasia as a reversible transformation of one differentiated cell type into another. This cellular adaptation is a key concept in pathology, often occurring in response to chronic irritation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMetaplasia is a protective cellular adaptation where one mature cell type is replaced by another mature cell type better able to withstand a specific stressor. Crucially, this change is reversible if the inciting stress is removed. A classic example is Barrett's esophagus, where the normal stratified squamous epithelium of the distal esophagus transforms into columnar glandular epithelium, which is more resistant to acid reflux but carries a risk of dysplasia and adenocarcinoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Metaplasia is fundamentally a reversible process; irreversibility would imply a more permanent, often neoplastic, change.\nOption C (Incorrect): This describes both hypertrophy (increase in cell size) and hyperplasia (increase in cell number), which are distinct cellular adaptations from metaplasia.\nOption D (Incorrect): This describes hypertrophy, an increase in the size of individual cells, not a change in cell type.\nOption E (Incorrect): This describes atrophy, a decrease in cell number or size, which is the opposite of the adaptive changes seen in metaplasia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Term | Definition | Reversibility | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Metaplasia | Transformation of one differentiated cell type into another | Yes | Barrett's esophagus (squamous to columnar) |\n| Hyperplasia | Increase in the number of cells | Yes | Endometrial hyperplasia, prostatic hyperplasia |\n| Hypertrophy | Increase in the size of individual cells | Yes | Cardiac hypertrophy, skeletal muscle growth |\n| Atrophy | Decrease in cell size and/or number | Yes | Disuse atrophy, denervation atrophy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Metaplasia is reversible; think \"M\" for Mature cell change.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, Barrett's esophagus appears as salmon-pink, velvety columnar mucosa extending proximally from the gastroesophageal junction, replacing the normal pale, glistening squamous epithelium. Biopsies are essential for definitive diagnosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Diagnosis and Management of Barrett's Esophagus (2015). Recommends endoscopic surveillance for patients with Barrett's esophagus to detect dysplasia and early cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Is a reversible transformation of one type of terminally dif-ferentiated ce | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Is an irreversible transformation of one type of terminally dif-ferentiated | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Is an increase in the size and number of cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is an increase in the size of cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Is a decrease in the number of cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 191. A: Is a reversible transformation of one type of terminally differentiated cell into another fu** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
