  "answer": "D) 192. D: Peutz–Jeghers syndrome Peutz–Jeghers syndrome, also known as hereditary intestinal polyposis syn-drome, is an autosomal dominant genetic disease characterised by the devel-opment of benign hamartomatous polyps in the gastrointestinal tract and hyperpigmented macules on the lips and oral mucosa.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't 'spot' the diagnosis, 'Peutz' it together!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, Peutz–Jeghers syndrome, is accurately identified. This condition is classically associated with the development of hamartomatous polyps throughout the gastrointestinal tract, making it the definitive choice among the given options.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeutz–Jeghers syndrome (PJS) is an autosomal dominant genetic disorder caused by a germline mutation in the STK11 (LKB1) tumor suppressor gene. It is characterized by the development of benign hamartomatous polyps, predominantly in the small intestine but also in the stomach and colon. A hallmark clinical feature is the presence of mucocutaneous hyperpigmented macules, particularly around the mouth, buccal mucosa, nostrils, and digits. While the polyps are histologically benign hamartomas, they carry a significant risk of malignant transformation, and patients with PJS have an increased lifetime risk of various cancers, including colorectal, gastric, pancreatic, breast, lung, and gynecological cancers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Turner syndrome is a chromosomal disorder (45, XO) primarily affecting females, characterized by short stature, ovarian dysgenesis, and cardiac anomalies, not hamartomatous GI polyps.\nOption B (Incorrect): Kartagener syndrome is a primary ciliary dyskinesia, an autosomal recessive disorder characterized by the triad of situs inversus, chronic sinusitis, and bronchiectasis, with no association with GI polyps.\nOption C (Incorrect): Klinefelter syndrome is a chromosomal disorder (47, XXY) affecting males, characterized by hypogonadism, gynecomastia, and infertility, not hamartomatous GI polyps.\nOption E (Incorrect): Di George syndrome is a developmental defect of the 3rd and 4th pharyngeal pouches, leading to T-cell immunodeficiency, hypocalcemia, and congenital heart defects, with no association with GI polyps.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Syndrome | Inheritance | Polyp Type | Key Features | Cancer Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Peutz-Jeghers Syndrome | Autosomal Dominant | Hamartomatous | Mucocutaneous pigmentation, GI polyps | Increased GI & extra-GI |\n| Familial Adenomatous Polyposis (FAP) | Autosomal Dominant | Adenomatous | Hundreds/thousands of colonic polyps | Near 100% colorectal cancer |\n| Lynch Syndrome (HNPCC) | Autosomal Dominant | Adenomatous | Few polyps, but rapid progression; microsatellite instability | Increased colorectal, endometrial, ovarian, etc. |\n| Juvenile Polyposis Syndrome | Autosomal Dominant | Hamartomatous | Numerous juvenile polyps, often in colon | Increased GI cancer |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hamartomatous polyps + mucocutaneous spots = Peutz-Jeghers.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy or capsule endoscopy reveals characteristic pedunculated or sessile hamartomatous polyps throughout the GI tract, often with a 'tree-like' branching pattern, which can lead to intussusception.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Genetic Testing and Management of Hereditary Gastrointestinal Cancer Syndromes (2015) recommends surveillance for PJS patients including endoscopy, colonoscopy, and imaging for extra-intestinal cancers.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Turner syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Kartagener syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Kinefelter syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Peutz–Jeghers syndrome | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Di George syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 192. D: Peutz–Jeghers syndrome Peutz–Jeghers syndrome, also known as hereditary intestinal polyposis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
