  "answer": "D) 198. D: Natural killer cells Natural killer (NK) cells form part of the innate immune system. They make up about 10 per cent of the peripheral blood lymphocytes. They have no T-cell recep-tors; however, they have the ability to kill virally infected cells and tumour cells.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When viruses hide, NK cells seek and destroy!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nNatural killer (NK) cells are a crucial component of the innate immune system, uniquely equipped to identify and eliminate virus-infected cells and tumor cells without prior sensitization. This makes them a primary defense mechanism against viral threats.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nNK cells operate through a \"missing self\" recognition mechanism, where they detect cells that have downregulated MHC class I molecules, a common strategy employed by viruses to evade cytotoxic T-lymphocytes. Upon recognition, NK cells release perforins and granzymes, inducing apoptosis in the target cell. This rapid, non-specific killing capability is vital in the early stages of viral infection before adaptive immunity is fully engaged.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): T-cells, specifically cytotoxic T-lymphocytes (CTLs), also kill virus-infected cells, but they are part of the adaptive immune system and require specific antigen presentation via MHC class I molecules and prior sensitization. NK cells are part of the innate system and do not require this.\nOption B (Incorrect): Neutrophils are phagocytic cells primarily involved in combating bacterial and fungal infections through engulfment and enzymatic degradation, not direct killing of virus-infected host cells.\nOption C (Incorrect): Complement is a system of proteins that enhances the ability of antibodies and phagocytic cells to clear microbes and damaged cells, promotes inflammation, and directly attacks the cell membranes of pathogens, but does not directly kill virus-infected host cells in this manner.\nOption E (Incorrect): Plasma cells are differentiated B lymphocytes responsible for producing and secreting large quantities of antibodies, which neutralize pathogens or mark them for destruction, but they do not directly kill virus-infected cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Cell Type | Immune System Branch | Primary Function | Target Recognition |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Natural Killer (NK) Cells | Innate | Kill virus-infected & tumor cells | \"Missing self\" (low MHC I) |\n| Cytotoxic T-Lymphocytes (CTLs) | Adaptive | Kill virus-infected & tumor cells | Specific antigen via MHC I |\n| Neutrophils | Innate | Phagocytosis of bacteria/fungi | Opsonized pathogens, PAMPs |\n| Plasma Cells | Adaptive | Antibody production | Specific antigens (indirect) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NK cells are the innate immune system's rapid response team against viral invaders and cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn cases of severe viral infection, imaging might show diffuse organ inflammation (e.g., viral pneumonia on CT chest, hepatitis on abdominal ultrasound), and intraoperatively, affected tissues might appear edematous or necrotic, reflecting the host's immune response, including NK cell activity.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis question pertains to foundational immunology principles, which are extensively covered in standard medical textbooks such as \"Janeway's Immunobiology\" (10th Ed.) or \"Abbas' Basic Immunology\" (7th Ed.). No specific surgical society guideline directly addresses this basic cellular mechanism.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | T-cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Neutrophils | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Complement | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Natural killer cells | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Plasma cells | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 198. D: Natural killer cells Natural killer (NK) cells form part of the innate immune system. They m** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
