  "answer": "B) 200. B: Rhabdomyosarcoma Rhabdomyosarcoma is a malignant skeletal muscle neoplasm. It usually presents in children and adolescents and can occur in any skeletal muscle in the body. It has three variants: embryonal, alveolar, and pleomorphic. The rhabdomyoblast – the diagnostic cell in all types – contains eccentric eosinophilic granular cyto-plasm rich in thick and thin filaments. The rhabdomyoblasts may be round or elongate; the latter are known as tadpole or strap cells and may contain cross-striations visible by light microscopy.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Skeletal muscle gone rogue? Think Rhabdomyosarcoma!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe provided answer correctly identifies Rhabdomyosarcoma as a malignant tumor of skeletal muscle (mesenchymal) origin. This is a direct recall question testing knowledge of tumor classification based on tissue of origin and malignant potential.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRhabdomyosarcoma is the most common soft tissue sarcoma in children and adolescents, arising from primitive mesenchymal cells committed to skeletal muscle differentiation. Its hallmark is the rhabdomyoblast, a diagnostic cell characterized by eccentric eosinophilic granular cytoplasm rich in actin and myosin filaments, which may form visible cross-striations. The three main variants—embryonal, alveolar, and pleomorphic—reflect different stages of muscle differentiation and often have distinct clinical presentations and prognoses.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Osteoma is a benign tumor of bone tissue, not skeletal muscle.\nOption C (Incorrect): Leiomyosarcoma is a malignant tumor of smooth muscle origin, not skeletal muscle.\nOption D (Incorrect): Lipoma is a benign tumor of adipose (fat) tissue, not skeletal muscle.\nOption E (Incorrect): Adenoma is a benign tumor of glandular epithelial tissue, not mesenchymal or skeletal muscle origin.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tumor Type | Tissue Origin | Malignancy |\n|---|---|---|\n| Rhabdomyosarcoma | Skeletal Muscle | Malignant |\n| Leiomyosarcoma | Smooth Muscle | Malignant |\n| Osteoma | Bone | Benign |\n| Lipoma | Adipose Tissue | Benign |\n| Adenoma | Glandular Epithelium | Benign |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: 'Rhabdo' means striated muscle; 'sarcoma' means malignant mesenchymal tumor.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (CT/MRI), rhabdomyosarcomas typically appear as ill-defined, rapidly growing soft tissue masses, often with heterogeneous enhancement. Intraoperatively, they can be infiltrative, friable, and may have areas of necrosis or hemorrhage.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nChildren's Oncology Group (COG) Guidelines for Rhabdomyosarcoma (various years, e.g., 2020): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for diagnosis, staging, and multimodal treatment, including surgery, chemotherapy, and radiation therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Osteoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Rhabdomyosarcoma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Leiomyosarcoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lipoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Adenoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 200. B: Rhabdomyosarcoma Rhabdomyosarcoma is a malignant skeletal muscle neoplasm. It usually presen** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
