  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a punctum points, an epidermal cyst it anoints!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Epidermal cyst. The presence of a firm lump with skin attachment and a visible punctum is a classic presentation for an epidermal cyst, particularly in the head and neck region.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nEpidermal cysts, also known as epidermoid cysts, arise from the proliferation of epidermal cells within the dermis, often due to occlusion of a pilosebaceous unit or traumatic implantation. They are benign and filled with keratinous debris. The characteristic punctum is the opening of the follicular infundibulum, which can sometimes exude material, making it a key diagnostic feature. Their firm consistency is due to the accumulated keratin and lipid content.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymph nodes are typically mobile, not attached to the skin, and lack a punctum. They are usually soft to firm but not typically fixed with skin attachment.\nOption B (Incorrect): Branchial cysts are congenital, usually located along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, and are typically smooth, mobile, and fluctuant, without skin attachment or a punctum.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thyroglossal cysts are midline neck masses, often moving with tongue protrusion, and are congenital. They do not typically have skin attachment or a punctum.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cystic hygromas (lymphatic malformations) are soft, compressible, transilluminable masses, usually presenting in infancy or early childhood, and do not have a punctum or skin attachment.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Epidermal Cyst | Branchial Cleft Cyst | Thyroglossal Duct Cyst | Lymph Node |\n| :------------------ | :------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- | :---------------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- |\n| **Location** | Anywhere, common head/neck, often subcutaneous | Lateral neck, anterior SCM, often near angle of mandible | Midline neck, moves with tongue protrusion | Anywhere, common cervical chain |\n| **Skin Attachment** | Often attached, may have punctum | Usually not attached | Usually not attached | Not attached, mobile |\n| **Punctum** | **Characteristic** | Absent | Absent | Absent |\n| **Mobility** | Variable, can be fixed if inflamed | Mobile, fluctuant | Mobile, moves with tongue | Mobile (unless matted/malignant) |\n| **Consistency** | Firm, rubbery | Soft, fluctuant | Soft, fluctuant | Soft to firm |\n| **Origin** | Traumatic implantation or blocked pilosebaceous | Congenital (branchial arch remnant) | Congenital (thyroglossal duct remnant) | Inflammatory, infectious, neoplastic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Punctum + skin attachment = Epidermal cyst until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, an epidermal cyst typically appears as a well-circumscribed, hypoechoic or mixed echogenicity mass with posterior acoustic enhancement, sometimes showing a tract to the skin. Intraoperatively, it presents as a well-encapsulated cyst filled with cheesy, malodorous keratinous material.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) guidelines for benign skin lesions (e.g., 2019): Emphasize clinical diagnosis for epidermal cysts, with excision recommended for symptomatic, infected, or cosmetically bothersome lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Branchial cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystic hygroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Epidermal cyst | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 46. E: Epidermal cyst Epidermal cysts originate in the skin and have a characteristic punctum. They ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
