  "answer": "D) 47. D: Cystic hygroma A cystic hygroma is a lymphangioma which usually presents in childhood. Cystic hygromas typically occur in the neck and transilluminate.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When it glows, it's often a hygroma!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cystic Hygroma. This diagnosis is strongly supported by the classic presentation of a soft, fluctuant, transilluminating cystic neck mass in a 14-year-old girl, which is highly characteristic of a lymphatic malformation.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCystic hygromas are congenital lymphatic malformations, specifically a type of lymphangioma, resulting from sequestration of lymphatic tissue that fails to connect to the main lymphatic system. They are most commonly found in the neck (75%) and axilla, often presenting in infancy or early childhood, though they can manifest later. The key feature of transillumination is due to their thin-walled, fluid-filled nature, distinguishing them from solid masses or those with denser contents.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Lymph nodes are typically firm, non-transilluminating, and may be tender if inflamed or enlarged due to infection or malignancy.\nOption B (Incorrect): Branchial cysts are typically located along the anterior border of the sternocleidomastoid muscle, but while cystic, they do not classically transilluminate as clearly or consistently as a cystic hygroma.\nOption C (Incorrect): Thyroglossal cysts are midline neck masses, often infrahyoid, and characteristically move with tongue protrusion, which is not described here. They also do not typically transilluminate.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Cystic Hygroma | Branchial Cyst | Thyroglossal Cyst | Lymph Node |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Location** | Lateral neck (often posterior triangle), axilla | Lateral neck, anterior to SCM | Midline neck, moves with tongue | Anywhere, often lateral neck |\n| **Consistency** | Soft, fluctuant | Soft, fluctuant | Soft, fluctuant | Firm to rubbery |\n| **Transillumination** | **Classic (positive)** | Usually negative/poor | Negative | Negative |\n| **Age of Presentation** | Infancy/childhood | Childhood/adolescence | Childhood/adolescence | Any age |\n| **Origin** | Lymphatic malformation | Branchial arch remnant | Thyroglossal duct remnant | Lymphatic tissue |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Transillumination in a pediatric neck mass strongly suggests a cystic hygroma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a cystic hygroma appears as a multiloculated, anechoic or hypoechoic mass with thin septations. Intraoperatively, it is a soft, thin-walled, multi-cystic lesion filled with clear or straw-colored lymphatic fluid.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Otolaryngology–Head and Neck Surgery (AAO-HNS) Clinical Practice Guideline: Evaluation of the Neck Mass in Children (2012, reaffirmed 2017) recommends ultrasound as the initial imaging modality for most pediatric neck masses.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Lymph node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Branchial cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cystic hygroma | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 47. D: Cystic hygroma A cystic hygroma is a lymphangioma which usually presents in childhood. Cystic** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
