  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the gut's in a knot, an AXR's your first shot!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is the correct answer because the clinical presentation of colicky abdominal pain, vomiting, distended abdomen, and increased bowel sounds is highly suggestive of bowel obstruction. A plain abdominal X-ray (AXR) is the appropriate initial investigation for suspected bowel obstruction, especially when gallstone ileus is a possibility given the history of gallstones.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nBowel obstruction is a surgical emergency characterized by mechanical impedance to the passage of intestinal contents. The classic signs include colicky abdominal pain, vomiting, abdominal distension, and altered bowel sounds. An AXR is the first-line imaging modality, often revealing dilated loops of bowel, air-fluid levels, and a paucity of gas in the distal bowel. In cases of gallstone ileus, specific findings on AXR can include pneumobilia (air in the biliary tree), dilated small bowel loops, and visualization of an ectopic gallstone, often in the ileum, confirming the diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This patient has obstructive jaundice due to a pancreatic head tumor, with failed ERCP. The next appropriate investigation and intervention to relieve the obstruction would be Percutaneous Transhepatic Cholangiopancreatography (PTC) for anterograde stenting, not MRCP, which is diagnostic.\nOption B (Incorrect): This patient presents with classic symptoms of acute cholecystitis (right upper quadrant pain, fever, vomiting, neutrophilia). The initial and most appropriate investigation is an ultrasound scan, not a contrast-enhanced CT, which is typically reserved for complications or equivocal ultrasound findings.\nOption D (Incorrect): This patient has acute pancreatitis (epigastric pain, high amylase, pyrexia, obstructive liver picture). The initial investigation to identify the cause (e.g., gallstones) and assess for complications is an ultrasound scan, not a pelvic X-ray, which is irrelevant to the presentation.\nOption E (Incorrect): This patient has a common bile duct stone causing obstructive jaundice. The appropriate investigation and therapeutic intervention for CBD stones is Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) for stone extraction, not Percutaneous Transhepatic Cholangiopancreatography (PTC), which is typically reserved for failed ERCP or proximal obstructions.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Presentation | Initial Investigation |\n| :-------------------- | :-------------------- |\n| Suspected Bowel Obstruction | Plain Abdominal X-ray (AXR) |\n| Acute Cholecystitis | Ultrasound Scan |\n| Acute Pancreatitis (initial) | Ultrasound Scan |\n| CBD Stone (diagnostic & therapeutic) | ERCP |\n| Obstructive Jaundice (failed ERCP) | PTC |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For suspected bowel obstruction, AXR is your first-line imaging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn AXR for bowel obstruction, look for dilated bowel loops, air-fluid levels, and a 'ladder pattern'. For gallstone ileus, also seek pneumobilia and an ectopic calcified gallstone.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) Appropriateness Criteria for Suspected Small Bowel Obstruction (2020) recommends AXR as the initial imaging study, followed by CT if AXR is inconclusive or if the diagnosis remains uncertain.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A 65-year-old woman is referred with a 4-month history of weight loss and p | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | A 43-year-old woman who is rather overweight presents with a 3-day history  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | A 60-year-old woman with a previous history of gallstones presents with col | ✅ Correct |\n| D | A 35-year-old man with a history of alcohol abuse presents to A&E with a 2- | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | A 45-year-old woman presents with right upper quadrant pain and vomiting. H | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 48. C: A 60-year-old woman with a previous history of gallstones presents with colicky abdominal pai** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
