  "answer": "C) 50. C: Cannulated screws Cannulated screws are preferred in younger patients with intracapsular fractures and thereby preserving the head of the femur. This is because femoral head prostheses have a limited lifespan.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Preserve the young hip; screw it, don't replace it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Cannulated screws. This approach is preferred for younger patients (35-year-old) with intracapsular femoral neck fractures to preserve the femoral head, which is crucial given their longer life expectancy and higher activity levels.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCannulated screws provide stable internal fixation, allowing for biological healing of the femoral head. Their minimally invasive nature reduces surgical trauma, and by preserving the patient's native joint, they avoid the complications and limited lifespan associated with prosthetic implants like hemiarthroplasty, which would necessitate revision surgery in a young, active individual. This strategy aims to maintain the patient's natural anatomy and function for as long as possible.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Traction) (Incorrect): Traction is a temporary measure for pain relief and alignment, not a definitive treatment for a femoral neck fracture requiring surgical stabilization.\nOption B (Dynamic hip screw) (Incorrect): A Dynamic Hip Screw (DHS) is typically used for intertrochanteric fractures, not intracapsular femoral neck fractures, where it can lead to excessive collapse and shortening.\nOption D (Intramedullary hip screw) (Incorrect): Similar to DHS, intramedullary nails are primarily indicated for intertrochanteric or subtrochanteric fractures, not for intracapsular femoral neck fractures.\nOption E (Hemiarthroplasty) (Incorrect): Hemiarthroplasty is generally reserved for older, less active patients with displaced femoral neck fractures due to the limited lifespan of prostheses and the desire to preserve the native joint in younger individuals.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Young Patient (<60) Intracapsular | Elderly Patient (>60) Displaced Intracapsular | Intertrochanteric Fracture |\n| :------ | :-------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------- |\n| Goal    | Head preservation                | Early mobilization, pain relief               | Stable fixation             |\n| Tx      | Cannulated screws (ORIF)         | Hemiarthroplasty / Total Hip Arthroplasty     | DHS / IMN                   |\n| Risk    | AVN, non-union                   | Dislocation, infection                        | Malunion, hardware failure  |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Young patient + intracapsular femoral neck = save the head with screws.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain X-ray, an intracapsular femoral neck fracture will show a break within the joint capsule, often with displacement. Intraoperatively, careful reduction under fluoroscopy is critical before percutaneous placement of cannulated screws, ensuring proper alignment and compression.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) guidelines emphasize internal fixation for femoral neck fractures in young patients to preserve the femoral head, contrasting with arthroplasty for older, displaced fractures.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Traction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Dynamic hip screw | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cannulated screws | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Intramedullary hip screw | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Hemiarthroplasty | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 50. C: Cannulated screws Cannulated screws are preferred in younger patients with intracapsular frac** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
