  "question": "Which is a feature of the posterior third of the tongue?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Filiform papillae",
    "B": "Fungiform papillae",
    "C": "Sensory innervations from the internal laryngeal nerve",
    "D": "Sensory innervations from the chordae tympani",
    "E": "Villiform papillae"
  },
  "answer": "C) 54. C: Sensory innervations from the internal laryngeal nerve The posterior one-third of the tongue is innervated (light touch and special taste sensation) by branches of the glossopharyngeal (IX) and vagus (X) nerves. The chorda tympani supplies special taste sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, and light touch to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is supplied by the lingual nerve. Filiform (for gripping food) and fungiform (for sweet/salty taste) papillae are found on the anterior aspect of the tongue. Valate papillae are found further back but still on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue and are concerned with bitter taste. Foliate papillae are found on the sides of the tongue and are concerned with sour taste. The mucous membrane covering the posterior one-third of the tongue is devoid of papillae but has a nodular irregular surface caused by the presence of underlying lymphoid tissue, the lingual tonsil.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Posterior tongue: CN IX and X rule the taste and touch.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies the sensory innervation of the posterior third of the tongue. The posterior one-third of the tongue receives both general sensation and special taste sensation primarily from the glossopharyngeal (IX) and vagus (X) nerves, with the internal laryngeal nerve being a branch of the vagus.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe posterior third of the tongue is unique in its innervation and surface features. General and special sensory innervation is predominantly supplied by the glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX), with some contribution from the vagus nerve (CN X) via its internal laryngeal branch, particularly for taste and sensation near the epiglottis. This region is characterized by the absence of typical papillae, instead featuring a nodular surface due to underlying lymphoid tissue, known as the lingual tonsil, which plays a role in the immune system.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Filiform papillae are mechanical papillae found on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, primarily for gripping food, and lack taste buds.\nOption B (Incorrect): Fungiform papillae are mushroom-shaped papillae located on the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, containing taste buds for sweet and salty sensations.\nOption D (Incorrect): The chorda tympani, a branch of the facial nerve (CN VII), provides special taste sensation to the anterior two-thirds of the tongue, not the posterior third.\nOption E (Incorrect): Villiform papillae are not a recognized primary type of papillae on the human tongue; the posterior third is notably devoid of typical papillae.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Anterior Two-Thirds of Tongue | Posterior One-Third of Tongue |\n|---|---|---|\n| **General Sensation** | Lingual nerve (from CN V3) | Glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX) |\n| **Special Taste Sensation** | Chorda tympani (from CN VII) | Glossopharyngeal nerve (CN IX), Vagus nerve (CN X via internal laryngeal nerve) |\n| **Motor Innervation** | Hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) | Hypoglossal nerve (CN XII) |\n| **Papillae Present** | Filiform, Fungiform, Vallate, Foliate | None (nodular surface due to lingual tonsil) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Posterior tongue = Glossopharyngeal (IX) and Vagus (X) nerves.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring endoscopy or direct laryngoscopy, the posterior third of the tongue appears as a bumpy, irregular surface due to the underlying lymphoid tissue of the lingual tonsil, lacking the distinct papillae seen anteriorly. This area is often assessed for hypertrophy or lesions.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is foundational anatomical knowledge, not typically covered by specific clinical guidelines. It is a core concept in textbooks such as Gray's Anatomy (42nd Edition, 2020) and Netter's Atlas of Human Anatomy (8th Edition, 2022).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Filiform papillae | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fungiform papillae | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Sensory innervations from the internal laryngeal nerve | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Sensory innervations from the chordae tympani | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Villiform papillae | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 54. C: Sensory innervations from the internal laryngeal nerve The posterior one-third of the tongue ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
