  "question": "Which is a feature of the hepatic artery?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Supplies the same amount of blood to the liver as the portal vein",
    "B": "Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein",
    "C": "Contains blood with the same oxygenation as the portal vein",
    "D": "Does not supply blood to hepatic metastases",
    "E": "Divides the liver into anatomical segments"
  },
  "answer": "B) 55. B: Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein The liver has a rich blood supply derived from two sources: two-thirds from the portal vein, the remaining one-third from the hepatic artery. Portal vein blood is rich in nutrients absorbed from the intestine but has a relatively low oxygen tension. Hepatic arterial blood contains few nutrients but is rich in oxygen. The hepatic artery supplies roughly 50 per cent of the oxygen delivered to the liver and the portal vein the other 50 per cent of hepatic oxygen supply. The liver is divided into segments by planes defined by the main hepatic veins (Couinaud classification). Purposeful embolization of hepatic arterial branches may be used to treat hepatic metastases.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The liver's oxygen balance: quantity vs. quality, a perfect arterial-portal duet.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B, stating that the hepatic artery provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein. This is accurate because despite the portal vein supplying more blood volume, the hepatic artery delivers a higher concentration of oxygen, resulting in an approximately equal contribution to the liver's total oxygen supply.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe liver uniquely receives a dual blood supply: two-thirds from the portal vein and one-third from the hepatic artery. While the portal vein carries nutrient-rich, deoxygenated blood from the intestines, the hepatic artery delivers oxygen-rich blood. Crucially, although the hepatic artery accounts for only about one-third of the total blood flow, its high oxygen saturation means it contributes roughly 50% of the liver's total oxygen supply, with the portal vein providing the other 50%. This balanced oxygen delivery is vital for hepatic metabolic function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The hepatic artery supplies only one-third of the liver's blood volume, while the portal vein supplies two-thirds, not the same amount.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hepatic arterial blood is rich in oxygen, whereas portal vein blood has a relatively low oxygen tension, so their oxygenation is not the same.\nOption D (Incorrect): The hepatic artery is the primary blood supply to hepatic metastases, which is why arterial embolization is a treatment strategy.\nOption E (Incorrect): The liver is divided into anatomical segments by planes defined by the main hepatic veins (Couinaud classification), not by the hepatic artery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature           | Hepatic Artery                 | Portal Vein                    |\n|-------------------|--------------------------------|--------------------------------|\n| Blood Flow        | ~1/3 of total hepatic flow     | ~2/3 of total hepatic flow     |\n| Oxygen Supply     | ~50% of total hepatic oxygen   | ~50% of total hepatic oxygen   |\n| Oxygen Content    | High oxygen tension            | Low oxygen tension             |\n| Nutrient Content  | Few nutrients                  | Rich in absorbed nutrients     |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hepatic artery = 1/3 flow, 1/2 O2. Portal vein = 2/3 flow, 1/2 O2.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn Doppler ultrasound, the hepatic artery typically shows a high-resistance waveform, while the portal vein shows continuous, low-velocity flow. During surgery, the hepatic artery is a pulsatile, bright red vessel, distinct from the larger, non-pulsatile, darker portal vein.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAASLD (American Association for the Study of Liver Diseases) Practice Guidance 2021: Management of Hepatocellular Carcinoma. This guideline discusses the role of transarterial chemoembolization (TACE) which targets the hepatic arterial supply to tumors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Supplies the same amount of blood to the liver as the portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Contains blood with the same oxygenation as the portal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Does not supply blood to hepatic metastases | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Divides the liver into anatomical segments | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) 55. B: Provides the same amount of oxygen to the liver as the portal vein The liver has a rich blood** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
