  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Keloids: They don't know their boundaries, so you must enforce them!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A, \"May respond to pressure dressing.\" Keloid scars are characterized by excessive collagen deposition that extends beyond the original wound margins, and various non-surgical treatments, including pressure therapy, are often employed to manage them.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nKeloid scars result from an abnormal wound healing response leading to excessive fibroblast proliferation and collagen synthesis. Pressure dressings work by inducing hypoxia, reducing blood flow, and increasing collagenase activity, which helps to flatten and soften the scar. This mechanical compression also reduces fibroblast activity and collagen production, making it a cornerstone in the non-surgical management and prevention of keloid recurrence, often used in conjunction with steroid injections or silicone sheeting.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Keloid scars classically extend *beyond* the limits of the original surgical wound, distinguishing them from hypertrophic scars which remain confined to the wound margins.\nOption C (Incorrect): Keloid scars are most common on areas of high skin tension or trauma, such as the sternum, deltoid region, earlobes, and neck, rather than flexure surfaces of the limbs.\nOption D (Incorrect): The use of subcuticular sutures, while beneficial for wound closure, does not prevent keloid formation, as keloid predisposition is an intrinsic biological response.\nOption E (Incorrect): Re-excision of keloid scars typically leads to a high rate of recurrence, often with a larger and more aggressive keloid, making it a less favorable primary treatment unless combined with adjuvant therapies like radiation or steroid injections.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Keloid Scar | Hypertrophic Scar |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Extent** | Extends beyond original wound margins | Confined to original wound margins |\n| **Growth** | Progressive, often doesn't regress | May regress spontaneously |\n| **Common Sites** | Sternum, deltoid, earlobes | Any site of injury |\n| **Recurrence after Excision** | High | Low |\n| **Treatment Response** | Pressure, steroids, radiation, cryotherapy | Pressure, steroids, silicone sheeting |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Keloids grow beyond borders; pressure and steroids are your friends, re-excision is not.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively or clinically, a keloid appears as a firm, rubbery, raised, often pruritic lesion that extends into the surrounding normal skin, with ill-defined borders that are distinct from the original incision line.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Dermatology (AAD) Guidelines for the Management of Scars (2014): Recommends intralesional corticosteroids, silicone gel sheeting, and pressure therapy as first-line treatments for keloids.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | May respond to pressure dressing | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Occurs within the limits of the surgical wound | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Is most common on flexure sur-faces of the limbs | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Can be prevented by subcuticular sutures | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | May be re-excised with good results | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 58. A: May respond to pressure dressing Keloid scars extend beyond the margins of the wound (unlike ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
