  "answer": "E) 69. E: Is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament The liver weighs 1500 g and is the largest organ in the body. It receives 30 per cent of the body’s total cardiac output (1500 mL blood flow/min). The liver is drained by the hepatic veins into the inferior vena cava. The nerve supply of the liver is by the right vagus nerve via the celiac ganglia and left vagus, which is supplied directly into the porta hepatis. Sympathetic innervation is carried on vessels. The liver is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Liver's falciform: Your anterior anchor, not just a pretty fold!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is the correct answer because the falciform ligament is a well-known anatomical structure that attaches the liver to the anterior abdominal wall and the diaphragm. This peritoneal fold is a key landmark in liver anatomy and surgical approaches. Understanding these basic anatomical relationships is crucial for safe surgical practice.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe falciform ligament is a double layer of peritoneum that extends from the anterior abdominal wall, specifically from the umbilicus to the diaphragm, and then onto the anterior and superior surfaces of the liver. It contains the ligamentum teres hepatis (round ligament of the liver) in its free inferior border, which is the obliterated umbilical vein. This ligament serves as a crucial anatomical landmark during abdominal surgery, particularly for liver resections or trauma, as it helps define the left and right lobes of the liver superficially and provides a relatively avascular plane for initial access.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The liver typically weighs around 1500 g in an adult, not 750 g.\nOption B (Incorrect): The liver receives approximately 30% of the body's total cardiac output, which is about 1500 mL/min, not 60%.\nOption C (Incorrect): The hepatic veins drain directly into the inferior vena cava (IVC), not the superior vena cava (SVC).\nOption D (Incorrect): The liver's parasympathetic nerve supply from the right vagus nerve is primarily via the celiac ganglia, not the superior mesenteric ganglia.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Characteristic | Correct Value | Incorrect Option Value |\n|---|---|---|\n| Weight | 1500 g | 750 g (Option A) |\n| Cardiac Output | 30% | 60% (Option B) |\n| Venous Drainage | Inferior Vena Cava | Superior Vena Cava (Option C) |\n| Vagal Nerve Supply | Celiac Ganglia | Superior Mesenteric Ganglia (Option D) |\n| Diaphragmatic Attachment | Falciform Ligament | (Option E is correct) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Liver's falciform ligament: anterior attachment, contains round ligament.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nDuring laparotomy, the falciform ligament is a prominent, sickle-shaped peritoneal fold visible on the anterior surface of the liver, extending to the diaphragm and anterior abdominal wall. On cross-sectional imaging like CT, it appears as a linear structure in the anterior abdomen, often seen containing the hypodense ligamentum teres.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association for the Surgery of Trauma (AAST) Liver Injury Grading Scale (2018): While not a guideline on anatomy itself, this widely used scale for liver trauma implicitly relies on detailed anatomical understanding of liver ligaments and structures for accurate grading and management decisions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It weighs 750 g | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It receives 60 per cent of the body’s total cardiac output | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It drains through hepatic veins into the superior vena cava | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It receives its nerve supply from the right vagus via the superior mesenter | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 69. E: Is attached to the diaphragm by the falciform ligament The liver weighs 1500 g and is the lar** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
