  "question": "Which of the following is a recognized curative treatment option for localized carcinoma of the prostate?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Radiotherapy",
    "B": "Lithotripsy",
    "C": "Hormonal treatment",
    "D": "Cytotoxic therapy",
    "E": "Tamsulosin"
  },
  "answer": "A) 73. A: Radiotherapy Recognized curative treatment for localized carcinoma of the prostate includes primarily surgery, radiation therapy, and proton therapy. Alternative treatments (hormonal therapy, chemotherapy, cryosurgery, and high-intensity focused ultrasound (HIFU)) can halt the progression of disease but not provide a cure. Tamsulosin is an a1a-selective alpha-blocker used in the symptomatic treatment of benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Zap it or snip it, but don't just block it!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nRadiotherapy is a recognized curative treatment option for localized carcinoma of the prostate. This answer is correct because both surgery and radiation therapy are established modalities aimed at eradicating the disease in its localized stage.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nRadiotherapy, encompassing external beam radiation therapy (EBRT) and brachytherapy, delivers high-energy radiation to the prostate gland. This radiation induces DNA damage in cancer cells, leading to their death and preventing further proliferation. For localized prostate cancer, radiotherapy offers a non-invasive or minimally invasive approach to achieve tumor eradication, often with efficacy comparable to radical prostatectomy, by precisely targeting the tumor while minimizing collateral damage to surrounding healthy tissues like the rectum and bladder.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Lithotripsy is a medical procedure used to break up stones in the kidney, bladder, or ureter, not a treatment for prostate cancer.\nOption C (Incorrect): Hormonal treatment (androgen deprivation therapy) for prostate cancer is primarily palliative, aiming to slow disease progression by reducing testosterone levels, but it is not considered curative for localized disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cytotoxic therapy (chemotherapy) is typically reserved for advanced, metastatic prostate cancer and is not a curative option for localized disease.\nOption E (Incorrect): Tamsulosin is an alpha-blocker used to relieve symptoms of benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) by relaxing smooth muscle in the prostate and bladder neck; it has no role in treating prostate cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Treatment Type | Indication | Curative Intent | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Radiotherapy | Localized Prostate Ca | Yes | DNA damage to cancer cells |\n| Radical Prostatectomy | Localized Prostate Ca | Yes | Surgical removal of prostate |\n| Hormonal Therapy | Advanced/Metastatic Prostate Ca | No (Palliative) | Androgen deprivation |\n| Tamsulosin | BPH symptoms | No | Alpha-1 blocker, smooth muscle relaxation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Localized prostate cancer: surgery or radiation for cure.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn multiparametric MRI (mpMRI), localized prostate cancer may appear as a T2 hypointense lesion with restricted diffusion and early contrast enhancement within the peripheral or transition zone, guiding biopsy and treatment planning.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Prostate Cancer (e.g., 2024). Recommends active surveillance, radical prostatectomy, or radiation therapy (EBRT or brachytherapy) as primary treatment options for localized prostate cancer, depending on risk stratification and patient factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Radiotherapy | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Lithotripsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hormonal treatment | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cytotoxic therapy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Tamsulosin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) 73. A: Radiotherapy Recognized curative treatment for localized carcinoma of the prostate includes p** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
