  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't assume normality; non-parametric tests always have your back.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is correct because non-parametric tests are robust statistical tools that do not require the assumption of a normal (Gaussian) distribution for the population data. Therefore, they can certainly be applied to data that is normally distributed, although parametric tests might be more powerful in such cases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA normal distribution is a fundamental concept in statistics, characterized by its symmetrical bell-shaped curve where the mean, median, and mode are all identical. It is uniquely defined by its mean and standard deviation, which quantify its central tendency and spread, respectively. Parametric tests, such as t-tests or ANOVA, assume that the data follows a specific distribution, typically normal. In contrast, non-parametric tests (e.g., Mann-Whitney U, Wilcoxon signed-rank) make no such assumptions about the population distribution, making them highly versatile. While parametric tests are generally more powerful when their assumptions are met, non-parametric tests provide a valid and often necessary alternative, even for normally distributed data, especially when sample sizes are small or assumptions are questionable.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): A normal population is uniquely defined by its mean and its *standard deviation*, not its median. While the mean, median, and mode are equal in a normal distribution, the standard deviation is crucial for defining its spread.\nOption B (Incorrect): Approximately 95% of the population lies within *two* standard deviations of the mean, not one. One standard deviation from the mean encompasses about 68% of the population.\nOption C (Incorrect): A chi-squared test can be appropriately applied to normally distributed data, particularly when analyzing categorical variables derived from such a population. The distribution's linearity is not a prerequisite for its application.\nOption E (Incorrect): Approximately 2.5% (or 25 out of 1000) of the population would be expected to be more than two standard deviations from the mode (which is the same as the mean in a normal distribution), not fewer than 5 out of 1000.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Normal Distribution | Parametric Tests | Non-Parametric Tests |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Defining Parameters | Mean & Standard Deviation | Assumes specific distribution (e.g., normal) | No distribution assumption |\n| Mean/Median/Mode | All equal | Uses mean, SD | Uses median, ranks |\n| % within 1 SD | ~68% | | |\n| % within 2 SD | ~95% | | |\n| % > 2 SD (each tail) | ~2.5% | | |\n| Power | Higher if assumptions met | Lower, but robust | |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Non-parametric tests are the statistical safety net for any data distribution.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nUnderstanding normal distribution helps interpret clinical trial data, such as the distribution of patient responses to a new surgical technique or the range of expected outcomes for a procedure. For instance, a normal distribution of post-operative pain scores would inform the expected range of patient discomfort.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCONSORT 2010 Statement: Updated Guidelines for Reporting Parallel Group Randomized Trials. This guideline emphasizes transparent reporting of statistical methods, including assumptions about data distribution and the choice of statistical tests, which implicitly relies on understanding these concepts.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The population may be uniquely defined by its mean and its median values | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | About 95 per cent of the popu-lation lies within one standard deviation of  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It would be inappropriate to apply a chi-squared test because the distribut | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Non-parametric tests could be used | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Fewer than 5 out of 1000 of the population would be expected to be more tha | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 75. D: Non-parametric tests could be used A normal distribution is shown to be a symmetrical bell-sh** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
