  "question": "Splenectomy increases suscepti-bility to which of the following organisms?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Streptococcus pyogenes",
    "B": "Schistosoma haematobium",
    "C": "Bacteroides fragilis",
    "D": "Neisseria meningitidis",
    "E": "Staphylococcus aureus"
  },
  "answer": "D) 77. D: Neisseria meningitidis The spleen plays an important role in the removal of dead and dying erythrocytes and in the defence against microbes. Removal of the spleen (splenectomy) leaves the host susceptible to a wide array of pathogens, but especially to encapsulated organisms. Certain bacteria have evolved ways of evading the human immune system. One way is through the production of a ‘slimy’ capsule on the outside of the bacterial cell wall. Such a capsule resists phagocytosis and ingestion by macrophages and neutrophils. This allows them not only to escape direct destruction by phagocytes, but also to avoid stimulating T-cell responses through the presentation of bacterial peptides by macrophages. The only way that such organisms can be defeated is by making them more ‘palatable’ by coating their capsular polysaccharide surfaces in opsonizing antibody. The production of antibody against capsular polysaccharide primar-ily occurs through mechanisms that are independent of T-cells. The spleen plays a central role in both the initiation of the antibody response and the phagocytosis of opsonized encapsulated bacteria from the bloodstream. This helps to explain why the asplenic individuals are most susceptible to infection from encapsulated organisms, notably Streptococcus pneumoniae (pneumococcus), Neisseria meningitidis (meningococcus), and Haemophilus influenzae. The risk of acquiring these infections is reduced by immunizing individuals against such organisms and by placing patients on prophylactic penicillin, in most cases for the rest of their life. In addition, asplenic individuals should be advised to wear a MedicAlert bracelet to warn other healthcare professionals of their condition.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No spleen, no shield: encapsulated bugs run wild.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, Neisseria meningitidis, because splenectomy significantly impairs the immune response to encapsulated bacteria. The spleen is critical for both initiating antibody responses and phagocytosing these specific pathogens, making asplenic individuals highly susceptible to overwhelming infections.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe spleen plays a pivotal role in adaptive immunity, particularly against encapsulated organisms. It is a primary site for the production of opsonizing antibodies against capsular polysaccharides, which are often T-cell independent. Furthermore, the spleen efficiently filters and phagocytoses opsonized encapsulated bacteria from the bloodstream. Without the spleen, individuals lose this crucial defense mechanism, leading to overwhelming post-splenectomy infection (OPSI) by pathogens like Neisseria meningitidis, Streptococcus pneumoniae, and Haemophilus influenzae.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Streptococcus pyogenes is not typically considered an encapsulated organism primarily cleared by the spleen in the same critical manner as N. meningitidis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Schistosoma haematobium is a parasitic trematode, not a bacterium, and its immune evasion and clearance mechanisms are distinct from encapsulated bacteria.\nOption C (Incorrect): Bacteroides fragilis is an anaerobic bacterium, and while it can cause infections, it is not a classic encapsulated organism for which the spleen is the primary defense against overwhelming sepsis.\nOption E (Incorrect): Staphylococcus aureus is a common pathogen, but it is not an encapsulated organism whose clearance is critically dependent on the spleen in the same way as N. meningitidis or S. pneumoniae.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Organism Type | Key Feature | Splenic Role | Post-Splenectomy Risk |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Encapsulated Bacteria | Polysaccharide capsule resists phagocytosis | Antibody production (T-cell independent), phagocytosis of opsonized bacteria | High risk of OPSI (e.g., S. pneumoniae, N. meningitidis, H. influenzae) |\n| Non-encapsulated Bacteria | Lack prominent capsule | Less critical for primary clearance of systemic infection | Lower risk of OPSI compared to encapsulated |\n| Parasites | Complex life cycles, diverse immune responses | Variable, not primary defense against systemic parasitic infection | Not directly related to OPSI from encapsulated bacteria |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Splenectomy = OPSI risk from encapsulated organisms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT, accessory spleens (splenules) may be identified, which, if missed during splenectomy, can sometimes provide residual immune function but also be a source of recurrent hematologic disease. Intraoperatively, careful identification and removal of all splenic tissue, including accessory spleens, is crucial.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guidelines for Immunization of Persons with Asplenia or Hyposplenia (updated periodically, e.g., 2020). Recommends vaccination against S. pneumoniae, N. meningitidis, and H. influenzae type b, and often prophylactic antibiotics.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Streptococcus pyogenes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Schistosoma haematobium | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Bacteroides fragilis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Neisseria meningitidis | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Staphylococcus aureus | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) 77. D: Neisseria meningitidis The spleen plays an important role in the removal of dead and dying er** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
