  "question": "Which one of the following regarding myoglobin in skeletal muscle is correct?\nA It binds and stores oxygen for rapid release during falling Po2\nB It contains a magnesium cofactor\nC It releases oxygen at high Po2\nD It exhibits cooperative binding with O2 (sigmoid dissociation curve)\nE It is devoid of iron",
  "options": {
    "A": "It binds and stores oxygen for rapid release during falling Po2",
    "B": "It contains a magnesium cofactor",
    "C": "It releases oxygen at high Po2",
    "D": "It exhibits cooperative binding with O2 (sigmoid dissociation curve)",
    "E": "It is devoid of iron"
  },
  "answer": "A) Myoglobin is a single-chain globular protein containing a haem group\n(iron-containing porphyrin) with eight alpha helices and a hydrophobic core. Being monomeric, it has instant binding with oxygen rather than the cooperative binding seen in haemoglobin. It has a hyperbolic dissociation curve. Its function is to store oxygen in muscle tissues for rapid release during times of need, as in exercise.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Myoglobin: the muscle's secret weapon for oxygen on demand.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption A is correct because myoglobin's primary role in skeletal muscle is to bind and store oxygen, releasing it rapidly when local oxygen partial pressure (Po2) falls, such as during intense muscle activity. This ensures an immediate oxygen supply for mitochondrial respiration.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMyoglobin is a monomeric heme protein found in muscle cells, characterized by a single heme group containing iron. Its high affinity for oxygen allows it to efficiently bind and store O2 at physiological Po2 levels within the muscle. Unlike hemoglobin, myoglobin does not exhibit cooperative binding, resulting in a hyperbolic oxygen dissociation curve. This high affinity and non-cooperative binding enable myoglobin to act as an oxygen reservoir, readily releasing its bound oxygen to the mitochondria when the muscle's metabolic demand increases and local Po2 drops significantly, thus supporting sustained aerobic metabolism during periods of intense contraction.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Myoglobin contains an iron-containing heme group, not a magnesium cofactor. Magnesium is a cofactor for many enzymes but not directly part of myoglobin's oxygen-binding site.\nOption C (Incorrect): Myoglobin has a very high affinity for oxygen and only releases it when Po2 is very low, typically below 20 mmHg, not at high Po2.\nOption D (Incorrect): Myoglobin is a monomer and does not exhibit cooperative binding; therefore, its oxygen dissociation curve is hyperbolic, not sigmoid. Cooperative binding is characteristic of multimeric proteins like hemoglobin.\nOption E (Incorrect): Myoglobin contains a heme group, which is an iron-containing porphyrin, essential for oxygen binding.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Myoglobin | Hemoglobin |\n|---|---|---|\n| Structure | Monomer (single polypeptide chain) | Tetramer (four polypeptide chains) |\n| Heme groups | 1 | 4 |\n| O2 Binding Curve | Hyperbolic | Sigmoid |\n| O2 Affinity | High (releases O2 at very low Po2) | Lower (releases O2 more readily at higher Po2) |\n| Cooperative Binding | No | Yes |\n| Primary Function | O2 storage in muscle | O2 transport in blood |\n| Location | Muscle cells | Red blood cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Myoglobin is muscle's personal O2 tank, ready for rapid deployment.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn cases of severe muscle injury (rhabdomyolysis), myoglobin is released into the bloodstream. While not directly visualized on imaging, its presence in urine (myoglobinuria) can cause dark, reddish-brown urine, and elevated serum myoglobin levels are a key diagnostic marker. Intraoperatively, severe muscle trauma could lead to rhabdomyolysis, requiring vigilance for kidney protection.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Emergency Physicians (ACEP) Clinical Policy: Critical Issues in the Evaluation and Management of Adult Patients Presenting to the Emergency Department with Rhabdomyolysis (2017). This guideline discusses the role of myoglobin in diagnosis and management, recommending monitoring for acute kidney injury.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It binds and stores oxygen for rapid release during falling Po2 | ✅ Correct |\n| B | It contains a magnesium cofactor | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It releases oxygen at high Po2 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It exhibits cooperative binding with O2 (sigmoid dissociation curve) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It is devoid of iron | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Myoglobin is a single-chain globular protein containing a haem group\n(iron-containing porphyrin) wit** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
