  "question": "The following table shows the results for a screening test for pancreatic cancer in 100 people:\n\nDisease Disease positive negative\nTest positive\t4\t5\nTest negative\t1\t90\n\nWhich of the following is true?\nA The positive predictive value is 0.95\nB The sensitivity is 0.95\nC The specificity is 0.8\nD The negative predictive value is 0.99\nE The sensitivity and specific-ity depends on the disease prevalence",
  "options": {
    "A": "The positive predictive value is 0.95",
    "B": "The sensitivity is 0.95",
    "C": "The specificity is 0.8",
    "D": "The negative predictive value is 0.99",
    "E": "The sensitivity and specific-ity depends on the disease prevalence"
  },
  "answer": "D) The sensitivity indicates how sensitive the test is at picking up those people who have the disease. It is equal to the number of people who are both disease-positive and test-positive divided by the number who are disease-positive. In this example, it is 4/5. The specificity indicates how good the test is at picking up those people who do not have the disease. It is equal to the number of people who are both disease-negative and test-negative divided by the number of people who are disease-negative. In this example it is 90/95.\nThe positive predictive value estimates the probability that a subject, who has a positive test, truly has the disease. In this example, it is 4/9. The negative\npredictive value estimates the probability that a subject who has a negative test truly does not have the disease. Here it is 90/91. The sensitivity and specificity are independent of disease prevalence.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A negative test with high NPV means you're likely in the clear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is correct. The negative predictive value (NPV) is calculated as the number of true negatives divided by the total number of negative tests, which in this case is 90/91, approximately 0.989, rounding to 0.99.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe negative predictive value (NPV) represents the probability that a patient who tests negative for a disease truly does not have the disease. A high NPV, as seen here, is crucial for ruling out a disease, especially in screening contexts where avoiding unnecessary further investigation or anxiety for healthy individuals is important. It helps clinicians confidently tell a patient with a negative test result that they are very unlikely to have the condition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The positive predictive value (PPV) is calculated as true positives / (true positives + false positives) = 4 / (4 + 5) = 4/9 ≈ 0.44, not 0.95.\nOption B (Incorrect): Sensitivity is calculated as true positives / (true positives + false negatives) = 4 / (4 + 1) = 4/5 = 0.8, not 0.95.\nOption C (Incorrect): Specificity is calculated as true negatives / (true negatives + false positives) = 90 / (90 + 5) = 90/95 ≈ 0.947, not 0.8.\nOption E (Incorrect): Sensitivity and specificity are intrinsic properties of the test itself and are independent of disease prevalence. Positive predictive value and negative predictive value, however, are highly dependent on disease prevalence.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Metric | Formula | What it measures |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sensitivity | TP / (TP + FN) | Probability of a positive test given the disease is present (True Positive Rate) |\n| Specificity | TN / (TN + FP) | Probability of a negative test given the disease is absent (True Negative Rate) |\n| Positive Predictive Value (PPV) | TP / (TP + FP) | Probability of having the disease given a positive test result |\n| Negative Predictive Value (NPV) | TN / (TN + FN) | Probability of not having the disease given a negative test result |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NPV and PPV are prevalence-dependent; Sensitivity and Specificity are not.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhen interpreting imaging for screening (e.g., mammogram, CT for lung cancer), a high NPV means a negative scan is highly reassuring, while a high PPV means a positive scan is highly concerning for disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe USPSTF (U.S. Preventive Services Task Force) guidelines for screening tests emphasize the importance of understanding these metrics to ensure that screening benefits outweigh potential harms, considering prevalence.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The positive predictive value is 0.95 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The sensitivity is 0.95 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The specificity is 0.8 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The negative predictive value is 0.99 | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The sensitivity and specific-ity depends on the disease prevalence | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The sensitivity indicates how sensitive the test is at picking up those people who have the disease.** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "D"
