  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the heart aches from a bug, think Coxsackie B.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of chest pain, breathlessness, ankle edema, and cardiomegaly points to heart failure, with viral myocarditis as the diagnosed etiology. Coxsackie B virus is the most frequently implicated pathogen in viral myocarditis, making it the most likely cause.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCoxsackie B virus, a member of the enterovirus family, exhibits cardiotropism, meaning it has a particular affinity for cardiac muscle cells. Infection can lead to direct viral damage to cardiomyocytes and trigger an immune response that further contributes to myocardial inflammation and injury. This process can result in dilated cardiomyopathy and heart failure, consistent with the patient's symptoms and cardiomegaly.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Rhinovirus is primarily associated with the common cold and is not a common cause of myocarditis.\nOption B (Incorrect): Mumps virus is known for causing parotitis (swollen salivary glands) and orchitis (testicular inflammation), not typically myocarditis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Coronaviruses are primarily associated with respiratory illnesses (e.g., common cold, COVID-19) and while they can cause myocarditis, Coxsackie B is historically a more common cause.\nOption D (Incorrect): Adenoviruses are linked to respiratory, gastrointestinal, and conjunctival infections, but are less frequently the cause of myocarditis compared to Coxsackie B.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Virus Type | Primary Association | Myocarditis Link |\n| :--------- | :------------------ | :--------------- |\n| Coxsackie B | GI/Respiratory symptoms | Most common cause of viral myocarditis |\n| Rhinovirus | Common cold | Rare/not primary cause |\n| Mumps | Parotitis, Orchitis | Rare cause |\n| Adenovirus | Respiratory, GI, Conjunctivitis | Less common cause |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Coxsackie B: the heart's viral nemesis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiogram, you would likely see cardiomegaly, ventricular dilation, and impaired systolic function. Cardiac MRI is crucial for diagnosing myocarditis, showing myocardial edema (T2-weighted imaging) and late gadolinium enhancement (LGE) indicating inflammation and fibrosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2013 European Society of Cardiology (ESC) Position Statement on Myocarditis: Recommends cardiac MRI as a key non-invasive diagnostic tool and endomyocardial biopsy for definitive diagnosis in specific clinical scenarios.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Rhinovirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Mumps | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Coronavirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Adenovirus | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Coxsackie B | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 135. E: Coxsackie B\nMyocarditis is most commonly caused by Coxsackie group B virus and may be preced** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
