  "answer": "E) 139. E: Are responsible for causing Kuru in humans\nPrions are a novel, infectious agent composed of protein only. They differ from all known pathogens. They lack nucleic acid and cannot be consid-ered microorganisms. They are highly resistant to decontamination methods such as standard autoclaving (heat), disinfectants (chemicals), and ionizing radiation.\nIf abnormal prion protein is inoculated into a normal host, conformational changes are induced in the normal host prions resulting in their conversion to abnormal host prions. These abnormal host proteins then induce further confor-mational changes in remaining normal host prions. Thus, the original inocu-lated protein is able to catalyse a chain reaction in which host proteins become conformationally abnormal. This is unaccompanied by inflammation, immune reaction, or cytokine release.\nWell-known prion diseases include Kuru, scrapie, bovine spongiform encephalop-athy (BSE), and Creutzfeldt–Jakob disease (CJD). Kuru is probably one of the most fascinating stories to have emerged from any epidemiological investigation. It occurred in villages occupied by the Fore tribes in the highlands of New Guinea who practised ritual cannibalism as a rite of mourning for their dead. The first cases occurred in the 1950s and involved progressive loss of voluntary control, followed by death within a year of the onset of symptoms. Interestingly, Kuru occurred only in individuals who participated in cannibalistic feasts. Such can-nibalism was believed to be responsible for the transmission of prions in Kuru.\nThere is still much work to be done in determining the exact modes of transmis-sion of prions and in enhancing our understanding of the molecular biology of prions. In addition, the exact interrelations between the different prion-related diseases (e.g., BSE and a new-variant CJD) needs to be clarified.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Prions: Protein-only, no DNA, sterilization-resistant, Kuru's cause.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is the correct answer. Prions are unique infectious agents composed solely of protein, and Kuru is a well-documented human prion disease linked to ritualistic cannibalism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPrions represent a distinct class of infectious agents, differing fundamentally from viruses, bacteria, and fungi. They lack nucleic acid, are not considered microorganisms, and cause disease by inducing conformational changes in normal host proteins, rather than by genetic mutation. This protein-only mechanism makes them highly resistant to conventional sterilization methods like heat, disinfectants, and radiation. Kuru, a neurodegenerative prion disease, gained notoriety for its epidemiological link to the consumption of infected brain tissue among the Fore tribe in New Guinea.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Prions are protein-only infectious particles, not microorganisms, as they lack cellular structure and nucleic acid.\nOption B (Incorrect): Prions are notoriously resistant to standard sterilization techniques, including autoclaving, chemical disinfectants, and radiation.\nOption C (Incorrect): A defining characteristic of prions is their lack of nucleic acid (DNA or RNA), distinguishing them from all other known pathogens.\nOption D (Incorrect): Prion diseases are caused by the misfolding and aggregation of host prion proteins, not by inducing mutations in the host's DNA.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Prions | Viruses | Bacteria |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Composition | Protein only | Nucleic acid + protein coat | Cells (DNA, RNA, protein) |\n| Nucleic Acid | Absent | Present | Present |\n| Reproduction | Induce conformational change in host proteins | Replicate within host cells | Binary fission |\n| Sterilization Resistance | High (resistant to standard methods) | Variable | Variable |\n| Example Disease | Kuru, CJD, BSE | Influenza, HIV | Strep throat, TB |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Prions: Protein-only, no nucleic acid, resistant to sterilization, cause Kuru.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMRI in Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) may show characteristic cortical ribboning or basal ganglia hyperintensity. Intraoperatively, extreme care with specialized sterilization protocols for instruments exposed to high-risk tissues is paramount due to prion resistance.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nCDC Guidelines for Infection Control in CJD (2010): Recommends specific, enhanced sterilization protocols for instruments potentially contaminated with prion-infected tissues.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Are infectious microorganisms | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Are destroyed by sterilization | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Contain nucleic acid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cause disease by inducing muta-tions in the DNA of the host | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Are responsible for causing Kuru in humans | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) 139. E: Are responsible for causing Kuru in humans\nPrions are a novel, infectious agent composed of ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
