  "id": 140470,
  "question": "A 2-year-old boy is referred with a scrotal swelling during the day. At night, it resolves. On examination, there is a fluctu-ant transilluminable swelling in the right scrotum. It is not pos-sible to get above the swelling. No bowel sounds are auscultated in the swelling. Select the likely diagnosis.",
  "options": {
    "A": "Inguinal hernia",
    "B": "Epispadias",
    "C": "Hypospadias",
    "D": "Non-communicating hydrocele",
    "E": "Communicating hydrocele"
  },
  "answer": "E) The testis descends from the posterior wall of the abdomen into the scrotum via the inguinal canal. It carries a pouch of peritoneum called the processus vaginalis. In a child’s first year, the processus vaginalis becomes obliterated, leaving the tunica vaginalis surrounding the testis. If this does not occur, the scrotal sac fills with peritoneal fluid via a communicating hydrocele. Owing to the continuity with the peritoneal cavity, the swelling will increase in size during standing and resolve when lying down. If the sac fills with bowel contents, an inguinal hernia will be present. A non-communicating hydrocele occurs when the processus vaginalis has closed, but the reabsorption of fluid from the tunica vaginalis is incomplete. This condition is present at birth and does not change in size.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Day swelling, night shrinking, fluid's linking: it's a communicating thing!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, Communicating hydrocele. The clinical presentation of a scrotal swelling that fluctuates (present during the day, resolves at night), is transilluminable, and lacks bowel sounds, is pathognomonic for a communicating hydrocele.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA communicating hydrocele results from a patent processus vaginalis, which is an embryological remnant connecting the peritoneal cavity to the tunica vaginalis. This patency allows peritoneal fluid to flow into the scrotum, causing swelling. The swelling increases with activity and gravity (during the day) and resolves when the child lies down (at night) as the fluid drains back into the peritoneal cavity. The fluid-filled nature explains its fluctuance and transillumination, while the absence of bowel contents confirms it is not a hernia.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Inguinal hernia) is incorrect: While an inguinal hernia can fluctuate, the absence of bowel sounds and positive transillumination rule out bowel contents, which are characteristic of a hernia.\nOption B (Epispadias) is incorrect: Epispadias is a congenital anomaly of the urethra, not a scrotal swelling.\nOption C (Hypospadias) is incorrect: Hypospadias is also a congenital anomaly of the urethra, unrelated to scrotal swelling.\nOption D (Non-communicating hydrocele) is incorrect: A non-communicating hydrocele occurs when the processus vaginalis has closed, trapping fluid in the tunica vaginalis. It does not fluctuate or resolve with position changes and is typically constant in size.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Communicating Hydrocele | Non-communicating Hydrocele | Inguinal Hernia |\n| :------------------ | :---------------------- | :-------------------------- | :--------------------------- |\n| Fluctuation/Diurnal | Yes (day/night) | No | Yes |\n| Transillumination | Yes | Yes | No |\n| Bowel Sounds | No | No | Yes (if bowel present) |\n| Reducibility | Yes (fluid returns) | No | Yes (contents return) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fluctuating, transilluminable scrotal swelling in a child? Think communicating hydrocele.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a communicating hydrocele appears as an anechoic (fluid-filled) collection within the scrotum, often demonstrating a narrow neck extending into the inguinal canal, representing the patent processus vaginalis. Intraoperatively, a patent processus vaginalis would be identified and ligated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Urological Association (AUA) Guideline on the Management of Inguinal Hernia in Children (2014, reaffirmed 2020) recommends surgical repair for symptomatic or persistent hydroceles in children over 1 year of age.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Inguinal hernia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Epispadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypospadias | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Non-communicating hydrocele | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Communicating hydrocele | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The testis descends from the posterior wall of the abdomen into the scrotum via the inguinal canal. ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
