  "question": "With regard to the lungs:\nA The left lung has three lobes\nB The horizontal fissure is present in the left lung\nC Each lung has eight bronchopul-monary segments\nD A foreign body is more likely to enter the left bronchus than the right\nE The lungs receive a dual blood supply",
  "options": {
    "A": "The left lung has three lobes",
    "B": "The horizontal fissure is present in the left lung",
    "C": "Each lung has eight bronchopul-monary segments",
    "D": "A foreign body is more likely to enter the left bronchus than the right",
    "E": "The lungs receive a dual blood supply"
  },
  "answer": "E) The right and left lungs are not mirror images of each other. While the right lung is composed of three lobes, the left lung possesses only two. Each of the lobes, in turn, are separated by fissures or interlobar clefts. Thus, on the right, there must be two fissures separating three separate lobes (these are the oblique and the horizontal fissures, respectively). On the left there is only one fissure separating the two lobes and that is the oblique fissure. Thus the horizontal fissure exists only on the right.\nThere are typically ten anatomically definable bronchopulmonary segments within each lung, each containing a segmental (tertiary) bronchus, a segmental artery, a segmental vein, lymphatics, and autonomic nerves and separated from their adjacent segments by connective tissue. Each is pyramidal in shape with its apex towards the lung root and its base towards the surface of the lung, and each is anatomically and functionally separate from the rest. The importance of understanding bronchopulmonary segments is that diseased segments, since they are structural units, can be selectively removed surgically (segmentectomy). Nowadays, this can be performed by video-assisted thoracoscopic surgery (VATS).\nThe right bronchus is shorter, wider, and more vertical than the left bronchus so that foreign bodies that fall down the trachea are more likely to enter the right bronchus. Furthermore, material aspirated by a supine, comatose, or anaesthe-tised patient would tend to gravitate into the apical segment of the right lower lobe, which is consequently a common site for aspiration pneumonia and abscess formation.\nThe lungs receive a dual blood supply by way of the pulmonary artery and the bronchial arteries. Thus, obstruction of a small pulmonary arteriole by a pulmonary embolus has no effect in an otherwise healthy individual with an intact bronchial circulation. In such circumstances, pulmonary embolism usu-ally results in infarction only when the circulation is already inadequate, as in patients with heart or lung disease. A large embolus that impacts in the main pulmonary artery, or that lodges at the bifurcation (as a saddle embolus), results in sudden death.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Lungs: Two lungs, two circulations, double the resilience.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E, stating that the lungs receive a dual blood supply. This is a fundamental anatomical and physiological fact, crucial for understanding lung function and pathology, as it provides a protective mechanism against ischemia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe lungs are uniquely supplied by two distinct circulatory systems: the pulmonary artery, which carries deoxygenated blood for gas exchange, and the bronchial arteries, which supply oxygenated blood to the lung tissue itself (bronchi, connective tissue, visceral pleura). This dual supply is vital; for instance, in cases of small pulmonary emboli, the bronchial circulation can often maintain the viability of the affected lung tissue, preventing infarction in otherwise healthy individuals. This redundancy highlights the body's intricate design to ensure organ resilience.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The left lung typically has two lobes (upper and lower), not three. The right lung has three lobes.\nOption B (Incorrect): The horizontal fissure is present only in the right lung, separating the upper and middle lobes. The left lung only has an oblique fissure.\nOption C (Incorrect): Each lung typically has ten bronchopulmonary segments, not eight. These segments are surgically important units.\nOption D (Incorrect): A foreign body is more likely to enter the right bronchus than the left because the right bronchus is shorter, wider, and more vertical.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Right Lung | Left Lung | Clinical Relevance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Lobes | 3 (Upper, Middle, Lower) | 2 (Upper, Lower) | Surgical resection planning |\n| Fissures | Oblique & Horizontal | Oblique only | Anatomical landmarks for lobectomy |\n| Bronchus | Shorter, wider, more vertical | Longer, narrower, more angled | Foreign body aspiration risk |\n| Segments | Typically 10 | Typically 10 | Segmentectomy for localized disease |\n| Blood Supply | Dual (Pulmonary & Bronchial) | Dual (Pulmonary & Bronchial) | Protection against ischemia, PE outcomes |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the right lung is 'right' for foreign bodies and has 'more' lobes.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a chest X-ray or CT, a foreign body would most commonly be visualized in the right main bronchus or its lower lobe branches. During a segmentectomy, the surgeon meticulously dissects along the intersegmental planes, often identified by inflation/deflation techniques or dye injection, to preserve healthy lung parenchyma.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nACCP Guidelines for Antithrombotic Therapy for VTE Disease (2016): Recommends specific anticoagulation strategies for pulmonary embolism, acknowledging the variable clinical impact depending on embolus size and patient comorbidities.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The left lung has three lobes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The horizontal fissure is present in the left lung | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Each lung has eight bronchopul-monary segments | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | A foreign body is more likely to enter the left bronchus than the right | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | The lungs receive a dual blood supply | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) The right and left lungs are not mirror images of each other. While the right lung is composed of th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
