  "question": "Which one of the following is true of haemoglobin?\nA Most haemoglobin circulates as free protein in plasma\nB Oxygen attaches to the globin chains\nC Each haemoglobin molecule com-bines with eight oxygen atoms\nD In normal adult haemoglobin, iron exists in the ferric state\nE Normal adult haemoglobin contains two alpha and two gamma chains",
  "options": {
    "A": "Most haemoglobin circulates as free protein in plasma",
    "B": "Oxygen attaches to the globin chains",
    "C": "Each haemoglobin molecule com-bines with eight oxygen atoms",
    "D": "In normal adult haemoglobin, iron exists in the ferric state",
    "E": "Normal adult haemoglobin contains two alpha and two gamma chains"
  },
  "answer": "C) The formation of haemoglobin is:\n• Four pyrrole rings ® protoporphyrin IX\n• Protoporphyrin IX + Fe2+ ® haem\n• Haem + polypeptide (globin) ® haemoglobin chain (alpha or beta)\n• Two alpha chains + two beta chains ® haemoglobin A (normal adult Hb)\nIn normal adult haemoglobin, iron exists in the reduced, or ferrous (Fe2+) state, rather than the ferric (Fe3+) state. Oxygen combines with the ferrous iron that is present within the haem molecules and not with the globin chains. The globin molecules that surround the haem molecule serve two key functions; they form a microenvironment in which the Fe2+ is protected from oxidation and also con-tribute to the unique oxygen binding properties of haemoglobin (allosterism and cooperativity). When iron exists in the ferric state, instead of the normal ferrous state, the haemoglobin is known as methaemoglobin. This is abnormal and has a reduced oxygen-carrying capacity, resulting in cyanosis.\nHaemoglobin consisting of two alpha and two gamma chains is foetal haemoglobin. Normal adult haemoglobin contains two alpha and two beta chains. Since each haemoglobin chain has a haem prosthetic group, there are four iron atoms in each haemoglobin molecule. Each of these can bind with one molecule of oxygen, making a total of four molecules of oxygen (or eight oxygen atoms) that can be transported by each haemoglobin molecule.\nWhy do we have red blood cells?\n• Primarily for the transport of haemoglobin and oxygen. If haemoglobin molecules were free in the plasma (and not wrapped up inside red cells) they would get filtered through the capillary membrane into the tis-sue spaces, or through the glomerular membrane and would escape into the urine. For haemoglobin to remain in the bloodstream, it must exist inside RBCs.\n• There are enzyme systems in the red cell that help to prevent haemoglobin breakdown. For example, methaemoglobin reductase converts ferric (Fe3+) methaemoglobin back to ferrous (Fe2+) haemoglobin.\n• Carbonic anhydrase is restricted to the red cells and is crucial in CO2 transport.\n• The chemical environment in the cell, especially the presence of DPG, dis-places the dissociation curve to the right so that oxygen unloads readily in active tissues.\n• If haemoglobin were free in plasma, the viscosity of blood would rise to intolera-ble levels and colloid osmotic pressure would increase considerably. The viscosity effect is especially important in capillaries where the presence of red cells in blood gives it an anomalously low viscosity (Fahraeus–Lindqvist effect).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hemoglobin's ferrous four heme groups bind eight oxygen atoms, no more, no less!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C. Each hemoglobin molecule is a tetramer, containing four heme groups, each capable of binding one oxygen molecule. Therefore, one hemoglobin molecule binds four oxygen molecules, which equates to eight oxygen atoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHemoglobin is a complex protein designed for efficient oxygen transport. Its structure consists of four polypeptide chains (globin) and four heme prosthetic groups. Each heme group contains a central ferrous (Fe2+) iron atom, which is the actual site of oxygen binding. Since there are four heme groups per hemoglobin molecule, it can bind four molecules of O2, and as each O2 molecule contains two oxygen atoms, this totals eight oxygen atoms per hemoglobin molecule. This precise stoichiometry is crucial for its physiological function.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Most hemoglobin circulates within red blood cells, not as free protein in plasma. Free hemoglobin would be filtered by the kidneys and cause significant osmotic and viscosity issues.\nOption B (Incorrect): Oxygen attaches to the ferrous iron (Fe2+) within the heme groups, not directly to the globin chains. The globin chains provide a protective microenvironment and contribute to allosteric regulation.\nOption D (Incorrect): In normal adult hemoglobin, iron exists in the reduced, or ferrous (Fe2+) state. If iron is in the ferric (Fe3+) state, it forms methemoglobin, which cannot effectively bind oxygen.\nOption E (Incorrect): Normal adult hemoglobin (HbA) contains two alpha and two beta chains. Hemoglobin with two alpha and two gamma chains is fetal hemoglobin (HbF).\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Normal Adult Hb (HbA) | Fetal Hb (HbF) | Methemoglobin |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Chains | 2 alpha, 2 beta | 2 alpha, 2 gamma | 2 alpha, 2 beta (typically) |\n| Iron State | Ferrous (Fe2+) | Ferrous (Fe2+) | Ferric (Fe3+) |\n| Oxygen Binding | High affinity | Higher affinity than HbA | Reduced/None |\n| Clinical Relevance | Primary O2 transporter | Higher O2 affinity for fetal O2 transfer | Causes cyanosis, reduced O2 delivery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: One Hb molecule binds 4 O2 molecules, totaling 8 oxygen atoms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPatients with significant methemoglobinemia (where iron is in the ferric state) may present with cyanosis that does not improve with oxygen administration, and their arterial blood may appear chocolate brown, which can be observed during blood draws or in the operating room.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNo specific guideline applies to basic hemoglobin structure and function; this is foundational biochemistry and physiology.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Most haemoglobin circulates as free protein in plasma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Oxygen attaches to the globin chains | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Each haemoglobin molecule com-bines with eight oxygen atoms | ✅ Correct |\n| D | In normal adult haemoglobin, iron exists in the ferric state | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Normal adult haemoglobin contains two alpha and two gamma chains | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) The formation of haemoglobin is:\n• Four pyrrole rings ® protoporphyrin IX\n• Protoporphyrin IX + Fe2+** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
