  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the adrenal gland screams, think pheo.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is C, Pheochromocytoma. This diagnosis is strongly indicated by the classic triad of episodic hypertension, an adrenal mass, and elevated catecholamines, which are the hallmark features of this neuroendocrine tumor.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPheochromocytomas are rare tumors originating from chromaffin cells of the adrenal medulla, which are part of the sympathetic nervous system. These tumors autonomously synthesize and secrete excessive amounts of catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine, and dopamine). The episodic release of these potent vasoconstrictors and cardiac stimulants leads to paroxysmal hypertension, palpitations, headaches, and sweating, directly explaining the patient's presentation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Adrenal cortical carcinoma arises from the adrenal cortex and typically produces steroid hormones (e.g., cortisol, aldosterone, androgens), not catecholamines, and would not cause episodic hypertension via this mechanism.\nOption B (Incorrect): Adrenal cortical hyperplasia involves the adrenal cortex and also produces steroid hormones, not catecholamines. It would not present with elevated catecholamines or episodic hypertension in this manner.\nOption D (Incorrect): Ganglioneuroma is a benign tumor of neural crest origin, often found in the sympathetic nervous system. While it can produce catecholamines, it is typically non-secretory or secretes them in much smaller, less symptomatic amounts compared to pheochromocytoma, and episodic hypertension is not its primary presentation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Neuroblastoma is a malignant tumor of neural crest origin, primarily affecting infants and young children. While it can produce catecholamines, it is rare in a 52-year-old and typically presents with a palpable mass, systemic symptoms, and less commonly with episodic hypertension as the primary complaint in adults.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Pheochromocytoma | Adrenal Cortical Carcinoma | Adrenal Cortical Adenoma/Hyperplasia |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Origin** | Adrenal Medulla (chromaffin cells) | Adrenal Cortex | Adrenal Cortex |\n| **Hormones** | Catecholamines (Epi, Norepi, Dopamine) | Steroids (Cortisol, Aldosterone, Androgens) | Steroids (Cortisol, Aldosterone, Androgens) |\n| **Key Presentation** | Episodic HTN, palpitations, sweating, adrenal mass | Cushing's, Conn's, virilization/feminization, mass effect | Cushing's, Conn's, incidentaloma |\n| **Age Group** | Any, peak 30-50s | Any, peak 40-60s | Any |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The \"rule of 10s\" is a classic mnemonic for pheochromocytoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn CT or MRI, pheochromocytomas typically appear as well-defined, often heterogeneous adrenal masses with high T2 signal on MRI and avid contrast enhancement on CT. Intraoperatively, they are often highly vascular and can cause significant hemodynamic instability upon manipulation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Pheochromocytoma and Paraganglioma (2014) recommends biochemical testing for catecholamine excess in patients with an adrenal incidentaloma and hypertension.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adrenal cortical carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Adrenal cortical hyperplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pheochromocytoma | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Ganglioneuroma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Neuroblastoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Phaeochromocytoma is a neoplasm of the adrenal medulla. Patients present with a triad of hypertensio** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
