  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the heart's filled with pink gunk, think amyloid, not junk!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Amyloid. This diagnosis is supported by the post-mortem finding of extensive replacement of the myocardium by an acellular, eosinophilic material in a patient with progressive congestive cardiac failure, which is highly characteristic of cardiac amyloidosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAmyloidosis is a group of diseases characterized by the extracellular deposition of insoluble fibrillar proteins (amyloid) in various organs, including the heart. These deposits are typically acellular, amorphous, and eosinophilic on H&E staining, perfectly matching the description. In cardiac amyloidosis, the amyloid infiltrates the myocardium, leading to a restrictive cardiomyopathy that impairs diastolic filling and causes progressive congestive heart failure. The classic diagnostic feature is apple-green birefringence under polarized light after Congo red staining, confirming the presence of amyloid fibrils.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cholesterol deposits tend to dissolve during routine tissue processing, leaving behind empty clefts or outlines, not an acellular eosinophilic material.\nOption B (Incorrect): Calcium salt deposits are typically deeply basophilic (blue/purple) on H&E staining, not eosinophilic (pink/red).\nOption C (Incorrect): Myocyte fibrinoid necrosis, while eosinophilic, would involve necrotic myocytes and inflammatory cells, thus being moderately cellular, not acellular.\nOption D (Incorrect): A post-infarctive cicatrix (scar) is primarily composed of dense collagen, which is acellular and eosinophilic, but the description \"extensive replacement\" in the context of progressive CHF without mention of prior infarct points more strongly to a systemic infiltrative process like amyloidosis.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Material | H&E Staining | Cellularity | Special Stains/Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Amyloid | Eosinophilic, amorphous | Acellular | Congo Red: Apple-green birefringence |\n| Calcium Salts | Basophilic, granular | Acellular | Von Kossa stain |\n| Cholesterol | Empty clefts/spaces | Acellular | Sudan stains (on frozen sections) |\n| Fibrinoid Necrosis | Eosinophilic, smudgy | Moderately cellular | PAS positive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acellular eosinophilic myocardial infiltrates + CHF = Amyloid until proven otherwise.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn echocardiography, cardiac amyloidosis often presents with increased left ventricular wall thickness (pseudohypertrophy) with preserved or reduced ejection fraction, and a characteristic \"granular sparkling\" appearance. Cardiac MRI with late gadolinium enhancement shows a diffuse, often global, subendocardial or transmural enhancement pattern that is difficult to suppress, distinguishing it from ischemic or hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\n2023 ACC/AHA/HFSA Guideline for the Management of Heart Failure: Recommends screening for cardiac amyloidosis in patients with unexplained heart failure with preserved ejection fraction (HFpEF) and left ventricular hypertrophy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cholesterol | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Calcium salt deposits | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Myocyte fibrinoid necrosis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Post-infarctive cicatrix (scar) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Amyloid | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) Amyloid is an acellular material that is eosinophilic. After Congo red staining, there is apple-gree** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
