  "question": "With regard to tumour suppressor genes:\nA They encode proteins that posi-tively regulate growth\nB They behave in a dominant fashion\nC Gain-of-function of tumour suppressor genes results in neoplastic growth\nD p53 and Rb-1 are tumour suppressor genes\nE p53 normally functions as an anti-apoptotic factor",
  "options": {
    "A": "They encode proteins that posi-tively regulate growth",
    "B": "They behave in a dominant fashion",
    "C": "Gain-of-function of tumour suppressor genes results in neoplastic growth",
    "D": "p53 and Rb-1 are tumour suppressor genes",
    "E": "p53 normally functions as an anti-apoptotic factor"
  },
  "answer": "D) Tumour suppressor genes encode proteins that negatively regulate cell proliferation and thus suppress tumour growth. p53 and Rb-1 are good examples located on chromosomes 17 and 13, respectively. Normal p53 is the so-called ‘guardian of the genome’ and triggers apoptosis and cell-cycle arrest in genetically damaged cells (i.e., it is pro-apoptotic). Mutations in p53 there-fore result in the propagation of genetically damaged cells and tumourigenesis. Indeed, approximately 50 per cent of human tumours contain mutations in the p53 gene. p53-related cancers are more aggressive and have a poorer prognosis.\nIn contrast to oncogenes, tumours caused by tumour suppressor genes are generally caused by mutations that result in a loss of function of the gene product; neoplastic growth resulting from the loss of the protective role of tumour suppressor genes. Loss of tumour suppressor function usually requires the inactivation of both alleles of the gene, so that all of the protective effect of tumour suppressor genes is lost. That is, tumour suppressor genes are generally deemed to behave in a recessive manner.\nCellular proliferation is therefore tightly regulated by two sets of opposing functioning genes: the growth-promoting genes (proto-oncogenes) and the negative cell-cycle regulators (tumour suppressor genes). Abnormal activation of proto-oncogenes and/or loss of function of tumour suppressor genes leads to the transformation of a normal cell into a cancer cell.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No brakes, no control: cancer's genetic tale.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is ACCEPT. Option D is correct because p53 and Rb-1 are indeed classic examples of tumor suppressor genes, which are crucial for preventing uncontrolled cell growth and tumor formation. These genes encode proteins that negatively regulate cell proliferation and maintain genomic integrity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTumor suppressor genes are fundamental to cancer prevention, encoding proteins that act as brakes on cell division, promote DNA repair, or initiate apoptosis in damaged cells. p53, often called the 'guardian of the genome,' exemplifies this by triggering cell cycle arrest or programmed cell death (apoptosis) in response to DNA damage, thus preventing the propagation of genetically unstable cells. Rb-1 (retinoblastoma protein) is another critical tumor suppressor that regulates cell cycle progression from G1 to S phase, ensuring cells only divide when appropriate.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Tumor suppressor genes encode proteins that *negatively* regulate growth, acting as brakes on cell proliferation, not positive regulators.\nOption B (Incorrect): Tumor suppressor genes generally behave in a *recessive* fashion, meaning both alleles must be inactivated for their protective effect to be lost and for neoplastic growth to occur.\nOption C (Incorrect): *Loss-of-function* (inactivation) of tumor suppressor genes, not gain-of-function, results in neoplastic growth due to the removal of their protective role.\nOption E (Incorrect): p53 normally functions as a *pro-apoptotic* factor, initiating programmed cell death in damaged cells, rather than preventing it.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Tumor Suppressor Genes | Oncogenes |\n| :---------------------- | :--------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Function** | Negatively regulate cell growth; promote apoptosis/DNA repair | Positively regulate cell growth; promote proliferation |\n| **Mode of Action** | Loss-of-function (inactivation of both alleles) | Gain-of-function (activation of one allele) |\n| **Genetic Behavior** | Recessive | Dominant |\n| **Examples** | p53, Rb-1, BRCA1/2 | RAS, MYC, HER2 |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Tumor suppressors are the brakes; oncogenes are the accelerators.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nWhile tumor suppressor genes themselves aren't directly visualized, their dysfunction leads to tumors. Intraoperatively, one might encounter tumors with specific genetic profiles (e.g., p53 mutations) that can influence surgical approach or prognosis. Imaging (CT/MRI) would show the tumor mass, and genetic testing of biopsy specimens would reveal the underlying gene mutations.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Genetic/Familial High-Risk Assessment: Colorectal (2023) or Breast (2023) often discuss testing for mutations in tumor suppressor genes like p53 (Li-Fraumeni syndrome) or BRCA1/2, guiding screening and management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | They encode proteins that posi-tively regulate growth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | They behave in a dominant fashion | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Gain-of-function of tumour suppressor genes results in neoplastic growth | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | p53 and Rb-1 are tumour suppressor genes | ✅ Correct |\n| E | p53 normally functions as an anti-apoptotic factor | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Tumour suppressor genes encode proteins that negatively regulate cell proliferation and thus suppres** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
