  "question": "With regard to gastric acid secretion:\nA It is inhibited by gastrin\nB It is potentiated by histamine\nC It commences only when food enters the stomach\nD It is stimulated by the glossopharyngeal nerve\nE It is stimulated by somatostatin",
  "options": {
    "A": "It is inhibited by gastrin",
    "B": "It is potentiated by histamine",
    "C": "It commences only when food enters the stomach",
    "D": "It is stimulated by the glossopharyngeal nerve",
    "E": "It is stimulated by somatostatin"
  },
  "answer": "B) There are 3 classic phases of gastric acid secretion:\nCephalic (preparatory) phase [significant]: This results in the production of gas-tric acid before food actually enters the stomach. It is triggered by the sight, smell, thought, and taste of food acting via the vagus nerve.\nGastric phase [most significant]: This is initiated by the presence of food in the stomach, particularly protein-rich food.\nIntestinal phase [least significant]: The presence of amino acids and food in the duodenum stimulate acid production.\nGastric acid is stimulated by 3 factors:\n• Acetylcholine: From parasympathetic neurones of the vagus nerve that innervate parietal cells directly\n• Gastrin: Produced by pyloric G-cells\n• Histamine: Produced by mast cells\nHistamine stimulates the parietal cells directly and also potentiates parietal cell stimulation by gastrin and neuronal stimulation. H2 blockers such as ranitidine are therefore an effective way of reducing acid secretion.\nGastric acid is inhibited by 3 factors:\n• Somatostatin\n• Secretin\n• CCK",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When acid's a problem, histamine's the key player!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B because histamine is a critical stimulator of gastric acid secretion, acting directly on parietal cells and significantly potentiating the effects of other secretagogues like gastrin and acetylcholine. This central role makes it a key target for acid-reducing medications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastric acid secretion is tightly regulated by a complex interplay of neural, hormonal, and paracrine factors. Histamine, released from enterochromaffin-like (ECL) cells, binds to H2 receptors on parietal cells, directly stimulating proton pump activity. Crucially, histamine also acts synergistically, amplifying the acid-secretory response to both gastrin and acetylcholine. This potentiation effect means that even low levels of histamine can significantly enhance acid production, establishing it as a final common pathway for gastric acid secretion and explaining the efficacy of H2 receptor antagonists in acid suppression.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Gastrin is a powerful stimulator of gastric acid secretion, not an inhibitor. It directly stimulates parietal cells and promotes histamine release.\nOption C (Incorrect): Gastric acid secretion begins during the cephalic phase, which is triggered by the sight, smell, or thought of food, well before food enters the stomach.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gastric acid secretion is primarily stimulated by the vagus nerve (part of the parasympathetic nervous system), which releases acetylcholine, not the glossopharyngeal nerve.\nOption E (Incorrect): Somatostatin is a potent inhibitor of gastric acid secretion, acting to suppress gastrin release and directly inhibit parietal cell function.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Factor | Effect on Gastric Acid Secretion | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Stimulators** | | |\n| Acetylcholine | Stimulates | Direct action on parietal cells via vagus nerve |\n| Gastrin | Stimulates | Direct action on parietal cells; stimulates histamine release |\n| Histamine | Stimulates & Potentiates | Direct action on parietal cells; potentiates gastrin & ACh effects |\n| **Inhibitors** | | |\n| Somatostatin | Inhibits | Suppresses gastrin release; direct inhibition of parietal cells |\n| Secretin | Inhibits | Reduces gastrin release; inhibits parietal cell acid secretion |\n| CCK | Inhibits | Modulates gastric emptying; can inhibit acid secretion at high doses |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Histamine is the ultimate potentiator of gastric acid, making H2 blockers effective.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nEndoscopy often reveals gastric or duodenal ulcers, or signs of reflux esophagitis, conditions frequently exacerbated by dysregulated gastric acid secretion. Historically, vagotomy was an intraoperative procedure to reduce acid production in severe ulcer disease.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Management of Peptic Ulcer Disease (2017) recommends H2 receptor antagonists as a treatment option for acid-related disorders.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is inhibited by gastrin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is potentiated by histamine | ✅ Correct |\n| C | It commences only when food enters the stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It is stimulated by the glossopharyngeal nerve | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It is stimulated by somatostatin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) There are 3 classic phases of gastric acid secretion:\nCephalic (preparatory) phase [significant]: Th** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
