  "question": "With regard to the adrenal gland (suprarenal gland):\nA The suprarenal vein on each side drains into the corresponding renal vein\nB The adrenal gland is situated within the same fascial compart-ment as the kidney\nC The zona glomerulosa forms the innermost layer of the adrenal cortex\nD The anterior surface of the right adrenal gland is overlapped by the inferior vena cava\nE The adrenal medulla is derived from embryonic mesoderm",
  "options": {
    "A": "The suprarenal vein on each side drains into the corresponding renal vein",
    "B": "The adrenal gland is situated within the same fascial compart-ment as the kidney",
    "C": "The zona glomerulosa forms the innermost layer of the adrenal cortex",
    "D": "The anterior surface of the right adrenal gland is overlapped by the inferior vena cava",
    "E": "The adrenal medulla is derived from embryonic mesoderm"
  },
  "answer": "D) The adrenal glands lie anterosuperior to the upper part of each kidney. They weigh approximately 5 g each and measure 50 mm vertically, 30 mm across, and 10 mm thick. They are somewhat asymmetrical, with the right adrenal being pyramidal in shape and left adrenal being crescentic, and lie within their own compartment of (Gerota’s) renal fascia. A fascial septum separates the adrenal gland from the kidney, which explains why in nephrectomy (removal of the kidney) the latter gland is not usually displaced (or even seen).\nEach gland, although only weighing a few grams, has three arteries supplying it: a direct branch from the aorta, a branch from the renal artery, and a branch from the inferior phrenic artery. This reflects the high metabolic demands of the tissue. The single main suprarenal vein drains into the nearest available vessel: on the right it drains into the inferior vena cava and on the left directly into the renal vein. The right adrenal gland is tucked medially behind the inferior vena cava. In addition, the right suprarenal vein is particularly short and stubby. Both these features make the inferior vena cava vulnerable to damage in a right adrenalectomy.\nThe adrenal gland comprises an outer cortex and an inner medulla, which represent two developmentally and functionally independent endocrine glands within the same anatomical structure. The medulla is derived from the neural crest (ectoderm). It receives preganglionic sympathetic fibres from the greater splanchnic nerve and secretes adrenaline (70 per cent) and noradrenaline (30 per cent). The cortex is derived from mesoderm and consists of three layers, or zones. The layers from the surface inwards may be remembered by the mnemonic GFR (which also stands for glomerular filtra-tion rate):\nG = zona Glomerulosa (secretes aldosterone)\nF = zona Fasciculata (secretes cortisol and sex steroids)\nR = zona Reticularis (secretes cortisol and sex steroids)",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Right adrenal, right IVC; left adrenal, left renal vein.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is correct because the right adrenal gland is anatomically positioned medial and posterior to the inferior vena cava, with its anterior surface often overlapped by this major vessel. This close relationship is a critical anatomical consideration for adrenal surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe right adrenal gland, being pyramidal, is tucked medially behind the inferior vena cava, making its anterior surface intimately associated with the IVC. This anatomical proximity, coupled with the particularly short and stubby right suprarenal vein draining directly into the IVC, makes the IVC vulnerable to injury during a right adrenalectomy. Understanding this relationship is crucial for safe surgical dissection.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The right suprarenal vein drains directly into the inferior vena cava, not the renal vein. Only the left suprarenal vein drains into the left renal vein.\nOption B (Incorrect): The adrenal gland is situated within its own compartment of Gerota's renal fascia, separated from the kidney by a fascial septum.\nOption C (Incorrect): The zona glomerulosa forms the outermost layer of the adrenal cortex, not the innermost. The layers are GFR (Glomerulosa, Fasciculata, Reticularis) from superficial to deep.\nOption E (Incorrect): The adrenal medulla is derived from embryonic neural crest (ectoderm), while the adrenal cortex is derived from mesoderm.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Adrenal Cortex | Adrenal Medulla | Right Suprarenal Vein | Left Suprarenal Vein |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Embryonic Origin | Mesoderm | Neural Crest (Ectoderm) | IVC | Left Renal Vein |\n| Layers/Zones | Glomerulosa, Fasciculata, Reticularis | None (chromaffin cells) | Short, stubby | Longer |\n| Primary Secretions | Steroid hormones (aldosterone, cortisol, androgens) | Catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine) | | |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Right adrenal gland hugs the IVC; left adrenal vein hugs the renal vein.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn cross-sectional imaging (CT/MRI), the right adrenal gland is typically seen superior and medial to the right kidney, often appearing triangular or pyramidal, nestled posteromedial to the IVC. Intraoperatively during a right adrenalectomy, careful dissection is required to mobilize the gland from the IVC, especially when ligating the short right suprarenal vein to prevent IVC injury.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Adrenal Tumors (2019). These guidelines provide recommendations for the evaluation and surgical management of various adrenal pathologies, including approaches to adrenalectomy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The suprarenal vein on each side drains into the corresponding renal vein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The adrenal gland is situated within the same fascial compart-ment as the k | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The zona glomerulosa forms the innermost layer of the adrenal cortex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The anterior surface of the right adrenal gland is overlapped by the inferi | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The adrenal medulla is derived from embryonic mesoderm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) The adrenal glands lie anterosuperior to the upper part of each kidney. They weigh approximately 5 g** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
