  "answer": "C) Gastrin is secreted by gastrin-secreting cells (G-cells) found in two locations: the pyloric region of the stomach and the upper half of the small intestine. Gastrin is released by:\n• Vagal stimulation\n• Distension of the pyloric antrum\n• Proteins (especially partially digested proteins) in the food\nGastrin is inhibited by:\n• A low pH in the lumen of the pyloric antrum (negative feedback loop)\n• Somatostatin\nGastrin has 3 main actions:\n• It stimulates gastric acid secretion\n• It stimulates gastric motility\n• It stimulates exocrine pancreatic secretions\nOverproduction of gastrin leads to excessive gastric acid secretion and the formation of multiple peptic ulcers. This is known as the Zollinger–Ellison syndrome and is often due to a gastrin-secreting tumour (gastrinoma).",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Gastrin: The stomach's acid-producing cheerleader, not its chill pill.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question correctly identifies a fundamental aspect of gastric physiology. Gastrin is a key hormone responsible for initiating and maintaining the acidic environment necessary for digestion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nGastrin is secreted by G-cells, predominantly found in the pyloric antrum of the stomach and the upper small intestine. Its release is stimulated by vagal input, distension of the pyloric antrum, and the presence of proteins in the stomach. The most critical action of gastrin is its potent stimulation of gastric acid secretion from parietal cells, which is vital for protein digestion and antimicrobial defense. Additionally, gastrin stimulates gastric motility and exocrine pancreatic secretions, coordinating the digestive process.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Gastrin is primarily secreted by G-cells located in the pyloric region of the stomach and the upper small intestine, not the body of the stomach.\nOption B (Incorrect): Gastrin secretion is inhibited by low pH in the pyloric antrum, forming a negative feedback loop to prevent excessive acid production, rather than being stimulated by it.\nOption D (Incorrect): Gastrin stimulates gastric motility, promoting the mixing and emptying of stomach contents, contrary to inhibiting it.\nOption E (Incorrect): Zollinger–Ellison syndrome (ZES) is caused by *increased* secretion of gastrin, typically from a gastrinoma, leading to severe hyperacidity and multiple peptic ulcers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature         | Gastrin                                                                                              |\n| :-------------- | :--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |\n| Secretion Site  | G-cells in pyloric antrum, upper small intestine                                                     |\n| Stimulated By   | Vagal stimulation, antral distension, proteins                                                       |\n| Inhibited By    | Low pH in antrum, somatostatin                                                                       |\n| Main Action     | Stimulates gastric acid secretion, stimulates gastric motility, stimulates exocrine pancreatic secretions |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Gastrin: G-cells, Gastric acid, Gut motility.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn endoscopy, multiple, refractory peptic ulcers, especially in atypical locations (e.g., post-bulbar duodenum, jejunum), are highly suggestive of Zollinger-Ellison syndrome. Intraoperatively, a gastrinoma may be found within the 'gastrinoma triangle' (defined by the cystic duct, common bile duct, and the second and third portions of the duodenum).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNorth American Neuroendocrine Tumor Society (NANETS) Guidelines for Gastrinomas (e.g., 2017). These guidelines recommend localization studies and surgical resection for resectable gastrinomas.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is secreted in the body of the stomach | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is stimulated by low pH | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It stimulates gastric acid production | ✅ Correct |\n| D | It inhibits gastric motility | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Decreased secretion results in the Zollinger–Ellison syndrome | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Gastrin is secreted by gastrin-secreting cells (G-cells) found in two locations: the pyloric region ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
