  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CD4 cells are HIV's target; their loss is AIDS's tragic hallmark.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer, E, accurately identifies a hallmark feature of the virus responsible for AIDS: its destruction of CD4 T-lymphocytes. This cellular depletion is the direct cause of the profound immunodeficiency seen in AIDS.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHIV, a retrovirus, specifically targets CD4 T-lymphocytes, which are critical orchestrators of the adaptive immune response. The virus binds to the CD4 receptor and a co-receptor (CCR5 or CXCR4) on these cells, enters, and integrates its viral DNA into the host genome. Viral replication within these cells ultimately leads to their lysis and death, resulting in progressive depletion of CD4 T-cells. This severe lymphopenia cripples the immune system, leaving the host susceptible to opportunistic infections and certain malignancies, defining the clinical syndrome of AIDS.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): HIV has a single-stranded RNA genome, not a double-stranded genome. Its genetic material is reverse transcribed into DNA upon infection.\nOption B (Incorrect): HIV is an enveloped virus, meaning it acquires a lipid bilayer from the host cell membrane upon budding.\nOption C (Incorrect): HIV possesses reverse transcriptase, an enzyme essential for converting its RNA genome into DNA, a defining characteristic of retroviruses.\nOption D (Incorrect): HIV is a retrovirus, belonging to the Lentivirus genus, and is distinct from the adenovirus group.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | HIV (Retrovirus) | Adenovirus | Herpes Simplex Virus (HSV) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Genome Type | ssRNA (diploid) | dsDNA | dsDNA |\n| Envelope | Yes | No | Yes |\n| Reverse Transcriptase | Yes | No | No |\n| Primary Target | CD4 T-cells | Epithelial cells | Epithelial cells, neurons |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: HIV targets CD4 T-cells, leading to immunodeficiency.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nImaging in AIDS patients often reveals opportunistic infections like Pneumocystis pneumonia (diffuse ground-glass opacities on CT), Kaposi's sarcoma (nodular lesions on skin/endoscopy), or CNS toxoplasmosis (ring-enhancing lesions on brain MRI).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNIH Guidelines for the Use of Antiretroviral Agents in Adults and Adolescents with HIV (2023). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the initiation, monitoring, and management of antiretroviral therapy (ART) to suppress viral replication and preserve immune function.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | A double-stranded genome | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Lacks a viral envelope | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lacks reverse transcriptase | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Is a member of the adenovirus group | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Destroys CD4 T-lymphocytes | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) HIV is the virus responsible for causing AIDS. It multiplies in CD4 lymphocytes and this multiplicat** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
