  "answer": "B) B: Peripheral neurons\nPeripheral nerve cells, unlike nerve cells of the central nervous system, do regen-erate following injury. It is a slow process that occurs at about 1 mm/day and may be followed with nerve conduction studies. Schwann cells are responsible\nfor myelination of nerve fibres, which increases the axonal speed of conduction. Following injury (Wallerian degeneration), they are able to regenerate. Mucosal cells are epithelial cells, which behave like stem cells and can therefore continu-ously renew themselves. Liver cells (hepatocytes) under certain circumstances can be stimulated to divide. Renal tubular cells lack the ability to regenerate the following injury. This is why renal blood flow is so carefully autoregulated. It is also why acute tubular necrosis is taken so seriously, because damage to renal tubular cells is irreversible and will lead to end-stage renal failure, requiring renal replacement therapy in the form of dialysis or transplantation.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Peripheral nerves: slow and steady wins the regeneration race!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Peripheral neurones. Unlike central nervous system components, peripheral nerves possess a remarkable capacity for regeneration following injury, a process crucial for potential functional recovery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPeripheral nerve regeneration is a well-orchestrated biological event. Following injury, the distal axon undergoes Wallerian degeneration, clearing debris. Crucially, Schwann cells, which myelinate peripheral nerves, dedifferentiate, proliferate, and form Büngner bands, creating a supportive scaffold and secreting neurotrophic factors. This environment guides the regenerating axonal sprouts from the proximal stump, allowing for regrowth at approximately 1 mm/day. This mechanism is absent in the central nervous system, where inhibitory factors and glial scarring impede regeneration.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cerebral cortex, part of the central nervous system, lacks significant regenerative capacity. Damage leads to neuronal loss and glial scar formation, not functional regeneration.\nOption C (Incorrect): Skeletal muscle has limited regenerative capacity via satellite cells, but severe damage often results in fibrosis rather than complete restoration.\nOption D (Incorrect): Cardiac muscle has virtually no regenerative capacity. Injury, such as a myocardial infarction, results in irreversible cell death and replacement by non-contractile scar tissue.\nOption E (Incorrect): Spinal cord, also part of the central nervous system, does not regenerate significantly after injury. Glial scarring and inhibitory molecules prevent axonal regrowth, leading to permanent neurological deficits.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Tissue Type | Regenerative Capacity | Key Cells/Mechanism |\n| :---------- | :-------------------- | :------------------ |\n| Peripheral Nerves | High | Schwann cells, Wallerian degeneration |\n| CNS (Brain/Spinal Cord) | Very Low/None | Glial scarring, inhibitory factors |\n| Cardiac Muscle | None | Fibrosis, scar formation |\n| Skeletal Muscle | Limited | Satellite cells |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Peripheral nerves regenerate; CNS does not. Think Schwann cells vs. glial scar.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn nerve conduction studies, regenerating peripheral nerves show progressive improvement in amplitude and conduction velocity. Intraoperatively, nerve repair involves meticulous microsurgical coaptation of nerve stumps to guide axonal regrowth.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society for Surgery of the Hand (ASSH) Clinical Practice Guidelines (e.g., 2017) on Peripheral Nerve Injury. These guidelines recommend early diagnosis, appropriate surgical repair (e.g., primary repair, nerve grafting), and post-operative rehabilitation to optimize functional recovery.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cerebral cortex | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Peripheral neurones | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Skeletal muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cardiac muscle | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Spinal cord | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) B: Peripheral neurons\nPeripheral nerve cells, unlike nerve cells of the central nervous system, do r** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
