  "question": "With regard to the blood supply of the stomach:",
  "options": {
    "A": "The right half of the lesser curvature is supplied by the right gastoepiploic artery",
    "B": "The left half of the greater curvature is supplied by the left gastric artery",
    "C": "The fundus of the stomach is supplied by the left gastric artery",
    "D": "The gastroduodenal artery is a branch of the common hepatic artery",
    "E": "The right gastric artery is most commonly implicated in a bleeding duodenal ulcer"
  },
  "answer": "D) D: The gastroduodenal artery is a branch of the common hepatic artery\nThe blood supply of the stomach is initially quite confusing, easily forgotten, and commonly asked about, but a few key rules make this a simple area of anatomy that will never be forgotten.\nRule 1\nThe coeliac trunk divides into 3 main branches, which can be easily remem-bered by the mnemonic Left-Hand Side (LHS):\n• Left gastric artery (L)\n• Common hepatic artery (H)\n• Splenic artery (S)\nRule 2\nFor the purposes of remembering the blood supply to the stomach, the stomach can be divided into 3 main areas:\n• Lesser curvature\n• Greater curvature\n• Fundus\nRule 3\nThe lesser curvature is supplied by the left and right gastric arteries. The left gastric, as already mentioned, comes directly off the coeliac trunk. The right gastric is a branch of the common hepatic artery.\nRule 4\nThe greater curvature is supplied by the right and left gastroepiploic arteries. The right gastroepiploic artery comes off the gastroduodenal artery. The left gastroepiploic artery comes off the splenic artery.\nRule 5\nThe fundus is supplied by the 6, or so, short gastric arteries which arise from the splenic artery.\nRule 6\nThe gastroduodenal artery is an important artery to remember for clinical pur-poses. It arises from the common hepatic artery and lies posterior to the first part of\nthe duodenum. A posteriorly situated duodenal ulcer may erode through the duode-nal wall into the blood vessel causing catastrophic, life-threatening haemorrhage. Urgent endoscopy or laparotomy may be required to stop the bleeding.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 The GDA: posterior, perilous, and paramount for duodenal ulcer bleeding!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption D is correct because the gastroduodenal artery (GDA) is a consistent and critical branch arising from the common hepatic artery, which itself is a major division of the celiac trunk. This anatomical relationship is fundamental to understanding upper gastrointestinal blood supply and pathology.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe celiac trunk is the primary arterial supply to the foregut, branching into the left gastric, common hepatic, and splenic arteries. The common hepatic artery then gives rise to the gastroduodenal artery, which descends posterior to the first part of the duodenum. This posterior location makes the GDA particularly vulnerable to erosion from a penetrating duodenal ulcer, leading to potentially life-threatening hemorrhage, a key clinical implication for surgeons.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The right half of the lesser curvature is supplied by the right gastric artery, not the right gastroepiploic artery, which supplies the greater curvature.\nOption B (Incorrect): The left half of the greater curvature is supplied by the left gastroepiploic artery (from the splenic artery), not the left gastric artery, which supplies the lesser curvature and fundus.\nOption C (Incorrect): The fundus of the stomach is primarily supplied by the short gastric arteries, which arise from the splenic artery, not the left gastric artery.\nOption E (Incorrect): The gastroduodenal artery, due to its posterior relation to the duodenum, is the vessel most commonly implicated in severe bleeding from a duodenal ulcer, not the right gastric artery.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Stomach Region/Clinical Point | Primary Arterial Supply | Origin |\n|---|---|---|\n| Lesser Curvature | Left & Right Gastric Arteries | Celiac Trunk (Left), Common Hepatic (Right) |\n| Greater Curvature | Left & Right Gastroepiploic Arteries | Splenic (Left), Gastroduodenal (Right) |\n| Fundus | Short Gastric Arteries | Splenic Artery |\n| Bleeding Duodenal Ulcer | Gastroduodenal Artery | Common Hepatic Artery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the celiac trunk's LHS branches: Left gastric, Hepatic, Splenic. GDA comes from Common Hepatic.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn angiography, a bleeding duodenal ulcer often shows extravasation from the gastroduodenal artery or one of its branches. Intraoperatively, a posterior duodenal ulcer may require a duodenotomy to identify and ligate the bleeding GDA.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Gastroenterology (ACG) Clinical Guideline: Upper Gastrointestinal and Ulcer Bleeding (2021) recommends early endoscopy for diagnosis and management of upper GI bleeding, often identifying the source as a duodenal ulcer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | The right half of the lesser curvature is supplied by the right gastoepiplo | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | The left half of the greater curvature is supplied by the left gastric arte | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | The fundus of the stomach is supplied by the left gastric artery | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | The gastroduodenal artery is a branch of the common hepatic artery | ✅ Correct |\n| E | The right gastric artery is most commonly implicated in a bleeding duodenal | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D: The gastroduodenal artery is a branch of the common hepatic artery\nThe blood supply of the stomac** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
