  "question": "Which one of these statements regarding insulin is true?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Insulin receptors use cAMP as their signal transducer",
    "B": "It is secreted by alpha-cells of the pancreas",
    "C": "Secretion is stimulated by somatostatin",
    "D": "It is an anabolic hormone",
    "E": "Release is inhibited by the ingestion of amino acids"
  },
  "answer": "D) D: It is an anabolic hormone\nInsulin acts via cell membrane spanning receptors which have intrinsic receptor tyrosine kinase activity. When insulin binds to the receptor, the tyrosine kinase is phosphorylated, resulting in a cascade of intracellular signalling mecha-nisms which results in glucose uptake into the cell. It is secreted by beta cells\nof the pancreas. Somatostatin is secreted by delta cells. Secretion is inhibited by somatostatin, which is always considered an inhibitory hormone. Insulin is considered an anabolic hormone; that is, it takes up glucose into the cell and converts it to larger ‘building blocks’ such as proteins and fats. Release of\ninsulin is stimulated not only by the ingestion of glucose but also amino acids which it will convert into larger proteins.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Insulin: The body's master builder and energy storer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, stating that insulin is an anabolic hormone. This is accurate because insulin's primary role is to promote the storage of energy and the synthesis of complex molecules from simpler ones, which is the definition of anabolism.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nInsulin is the quintessential anabolic hormone, orchestrating the body's energy storage. Upon binding to its receptor, which possesses intrinsic tyrosine kinase activity, it initiates a cascade leading to glucose uptake into cells, glycogen synthesis in the liver and muscle, and conversion of excess glucose into triglycerides for fat storage. Furthermore, insulin promotes amino acid uptake and protein synthesis, making it crucial for growth and tissue repair. Its anabolic actions ensure that absorbed nutrients are efficiently utilized and stored for future energy demands.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Insulin receptors utilize intrinsic receptor tyrosine kinase activity for signal transduction, not cAMP. cAMP is typically associated with G-protein coupled receptors.\nOption B (Incorrect): Insulin is secreted by the beta-cells of the pancreatic islets, while alpha-cells secrete glucagon.\nOption C (Incorrect): Somatostatin, secreted by delta-cells, is an inhibitory hormone that suppresses the secretion of both insulin and glucagon.\nOption E (Incorrect): The release of insulin is stimulated by the ingestion of amino acids, as insulin promotes protein synthesis and helps clear amino acids from the bloodstream.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Cell of Origin | Primary Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| Insulin | Beta-cells | Anabolic: Glucose uptake, glycogen/protein/fat synthesis |\n| Glucagon | Alpha-cells | Catabolic: Glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis |\n| Somatostatin | Delta-cells | Inhibits insulin and glucagon secretion |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Insulin builds and stores; glucagon breaks down and releases.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, an insulinoma (a rare pancreatic neuroendocrine tumor) would appear as a small, often solitary, well-circumscribed lesion within the pancreas, typically causing symptoms of hypoglycemia due to excessive insulin secretion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Diabetes Association (ADA) Standards of Care in Diabetes (2024) recommends insulin as a cornerstone therapy for managing hyperglycemia, particularly in Type 1 Diabetes and advanced Type 2 Diabetes, leveraging its anabolic effects.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Insulin receptors use cAMP as their signal transducer | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It is secreted by alpha-cells of the pancreas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Secretion is stimulated by somatostatin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It is an anabolic hormone | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Release is inhibited by the ingestion of amino acids | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D: It is an anabolic hormone\nInsulin acts via cell membrane spanning receptors which have intrinsic ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
