  "id": 140530,
  "question": "A woman has episodic abdominal pain which is worse after fatty meals. Which hormone is responsible for her post-prandial worsening of symptoms?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Somatostatin",
    "B": "Secretin",
    "C": "Pepsin",
    "D": "Cholecystokinin",
    "E": "Gastrin"
  },
  "answer": "D) D: Cholecystokinin\nCholecystokinin (CCK) is responsible for stimulation of gallbladder contraction. The release of CCK is stimulated by dietary fat. It is produced in the I-cells of the duodenum and jejunum. Moreover, CCK also stimulates the release of pancreatic enzyme secretion and decreases the rate of gastric emptying.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When fat hits the gut, CCK makes the gallbladder strut!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Cholecystokinin (CCK). This hormone is directly responsible for gallbladder contraction, which is stimulated by the presence of fat in the duodenum, leading to the classic post-prandial pain associated with biliary issues.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCholecystokinin (CCK) is a peptide hormone produced by I-cells in the duodenum and jejunum in response to dietary fat and protein. Its primary role in this scenario is to stimulate the contraction of the gallbladder, releasing bile into the small intestine to aid in fat digestion. This contraction, especially in the presence of gallstones, can cause significant pain, explaining the patient's symptoms after fatty meals. CCK also promotes pancreatic enzyme secretion and slows gastric emptying.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Somatostatin is an inhibitory hormone that suppresses the release of many GI hormones, including CCK, and reduces gallbladder contraction. It would not worsen symptoms.\nOption B (Incorrect): Secretin is released in response to acid in the duodenum and primarily stimulates bicarbonate secretion from the pancreas and bile ducts, not gallbladder contraction.\nOption C (Incorrect): Pepsin is a proteolytic enzyme secreted by the stomach, not a hormone, and is involved in protein digestion, not gallbladder contraction or fat-induced pain.\nOption E (Incorrect): Gastrin is released in response to protein and distension in the stomach, stimulating gastric acid secretion and mucosal growth, not directly causing gallbladder contraction or post-fatty meal pain.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Primary Stimulus | Primary Action | Site of Production |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cholecystokinin (CCK) | Fat, Protein | Gallbladder contraction, Pancreatic enzyme release | Duodenum, Jejunum (I-cells) |\n| Secretin | Acid in duodenum | Pancreatic bicarbonate release, Bile duct bicarbonate release | Duodenum (S-cells) |\n| Gastrin | Protein, Distension | Gastric acid secretion, Mucosal growth | Stomach (G-cells) |\n| Somatostatin | Acid, Low pH | Inhibits GI hormone release, Reduces gastric emptying | Pancreas, GI tract |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Fatty meals + abdominal pain = think CCK and gallbladder.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, one would look for gallstones within the gallbladder lumen, gallbladder wall thickening, pericholecystic fluid, or a positive sonographic Murphy's sign, indicative of cholecystitis. Intraoperatively, an inflamed, distended gallbladder with stones would be observed.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Gastroenterological Association (AGA) Institute Guidelines (e.g., 2016) on the management of gallstones and cholecystitis recommend ultrasound as the initial diagnostic imaging for suspected biliary colic or cholecystitis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Somatostatin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Secretin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Pepsin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Cholecystokinin | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Gastrin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D: Cholecystokinin\nCholecystokinin (CCK) is responsible for stimulation of gallbladder contraction. ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
