  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Cortisol: Your body's morning alarm clock, not a sugar-lowering snooze button.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption E is correct because cortisol exhibits a distinct diurnal rhythm, with its highest levels occurring in the early morning upon waking. This circadian pattern is a fundamental aspect of its physiological regulation and is crucial for maintaining homeostasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCortisol, a glucocorticoid hormone synthesized in the adrenal cortex, is under the control of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis. Its secretion follows a circadian rhythm, peaking between 6-9 AM and gradually declining throughout the day, reaching its nadir around midnight. This morning surge helps prepare the body for daily activities by mobilizing energy stores, modulating immune responses, and influencing mood and cognition.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cortisol is a steroid hormone, derived from cholesterol, not a protein. \nOption B (Incorrect): Cortisol is a glucocorticoid that *raises* blood glucose by promoting gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis, and decreasing glucose utilization. \nOption C (Incorrect): Cortisol is primarily a *catabolic* hormone, breaking down proteins and fats to provide substrates for glucose production. \nOption D (Incorrect): Cortisol secretion is stimulated by ACTH from the anterior pituitary, not by renin. Renin is involved in the regulation of aldosterone.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Hormone | Type | Primary Stimulus | Key Effect |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cortisol | Steroid | ACTH (HPA axis) | Increases blood glucose, anti-inflammatory |\n| Aldosterone | Steroid | Angiotensin II, K+ | Na+ reabsorption, K+ excretion |\n| Adrenaline | Catecholamine | Sympathetic nervous system | \"Fight or flight\" response, increases HR/BP/glucose |\n| Insulin | Peptide | High blood glucose | Lowers blood glucose, anabolic |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember the 'cortisol curve' – high in the AM, low at night.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nFor conditions of cortisol excess (Cushing's syndrome), imaging (CT/MRI) of the adrenal glands may reveal an adenoma, or pituitary imaging may show an ACTH-producing adenoma. Intraoperatively, an adrenalectomy for a cortisol-producing tumor involves careful identification and excision of the affected adrenal gland, often laparoscopically.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nEndocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis of Cushing's Syndrome (2008, updated 2015) - Recommends midnight salivary cortisol or 24-hour urine free cortisol as initial screening tests.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | It is a protein | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | It lowers blood glucose | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | It is an anabolic hormone | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | It is stimulated by renin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | It has a peak hormonal concentration in the morning | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) E: It has a peak hormonal concentration in the morning\nCortisol is a steroid hormone that is release** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
