  "question": "A woman sprains her ankle while running down a flight of stairs. Which ligament did she most likely injure?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Deltoid",
    "B": "Anterior talo-tibial",
    "C": "Medial collateral",
    "D": "Calcaneo-fibular",
    "E": "Calcaneo-tibial"
  },
  "answer": "D) D: Calcaneo-fibular ligament\nThe most common ankle sprain is lateral which occurs as a result of exces-sive inversion of the foot and dorsiflexion of the ankle. The deltoid ligament, also known as the medial ligament of the ankle, is very strong and located at the medial malleolus. Excessive eversion would be the most likely mechanism of injury.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Inversion's the villain, CFL's the victim.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D, the calcaneo-fibular ligament. This ligament is part of the lateral ankle complex, which is most commonly injured during an inversion sprain, the typical mechanism when \"running down a flight of stairs\" leads to an ankle sprain.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAnkle sprains are overwhelmingly inversion injuries, affecting the lateral ligament complex. This complex consists of the anterior talofibular ligament (ATFL), calcaneo-fibular ligament (CFL), and posterior talofibular ligament (PTFL). The ATFL is the most commonly injured, often followed by the CFL, frequently in combination. The calcaneo-fibular ligament resists inversion and adduction of the talus, making it highly susceptible to injury during the excessive inversion described.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Deltoid): Incorrect. The deltoid ligament is the strong medial ankle ligament, injured by eversion forces, which are far less common.\nOption B (Anterior talo-tibial): Incorrect. This is a component of the medial (deltoid) ligament, not a lateral ligament. While the anterior talofibular ligament (ATFL) is a lateral ligament and commonly injured, the question asks for the most likely, and CFL is a strong contender often injured with ATFL.\nOption C (Medial collateral): Incorrect. The medial collateral ligament is a major ligament of the knee, not the ankle.\nOption E (Calcaneo-tibial): Incorrect. This is not a recognized primary ankle ligament. The tibiocalcaneal part is a component of the deltoid ligament, but \"calcaneo-tibial\" as a standalone ligament is not standard terminology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Ligament Complex | Components | Location | Injury Mechanism | Commonality |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Lateral Ankle | Anterior Talofibular (ATFL), Calcaneo-fibular (CFL), Posterior Talofibular (PTFL) | Lateral malleolus to talus/calcaneus | Inversion | Most common (85-90%) |\n| Medial Ankle (Deltoid) | Tibionavicular, Tibiocalcaneal, Anterior/Posterior Tibiotalar | Medial malleolus to navicular/calcaneus/talus | Eversion | Less common (5-10%) |\n| Syndesmotic | Anterior/Posterior Inferior Tibiofibular, Interosseous membrane | Between tibia and fibula | Dorsiflexion + external rotation | Least common (1-10%) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Inversion sprains injure lateral ankle ligaments; eversion sprains injure the medial deltoid ligament.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, a torn calcaneo-fibular ligament appears as discontinuity, edema, or hemorrhage within its substance, often with surrounding soft tissue swelling. X-rays are primarily to rule out fractures (e.g., avulsion fracture of the fibula or talus).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Diagnosis and Treatment of Ankle Sprains (2019). It recommends early functional rehabilitation for acute ankle sprains and emphasizes ruling out fractures with Ottawa Ankle Rules.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Deltoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Anterior talo-tibial | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Medial collateral | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Calcaneo-fibular | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Calcaneo-tibial | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D: Calcaneo-fibular ligament\nThe most common ankle sprain is lateral which occurs as a result of exc** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
