  "question": "With regard to adrenal gland disorders:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Adrenal insufficiency results in hypokalaemia and hypernatraemia",
    "B": "Conn’s syndrome results in hyperkalaemia",
    "C": "Cushing’s disease is due to a cortisol-producing tumour of the adrenal cortex",
    "D": "Pheochromocytoma is due to oversecretion of cortisol by a tumour of the adrenal medulla",
    "E": "Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (adrenogenital syndrome) results in virilization and salt wasting"
  },
  "answer": "E) E: Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (adrenogenital syndrome) results in viril-ization and salt wasting\nDisorders of the adrenal gland may relate to the adrenal cortex, medulla, or both. There is only one disorder worth mentioning that selectively affects the adrenal medulla. That is a phaeochromocytoma – a tumour of the adrenal medulla that results in the overproduction of catecholamines (such as adrena-line and noradrenaline). This leads to hypertension, headaches, palpitations, and sweating (all known effects of adrenaline).\nConditions of the adrenal cortex may result from an overproduction or an underproduction of hormones. An overproduction of cortisol is known as Cushing’s syndrome. There are several causes of Cushing’s syndrome, the most common being iatrogenic (the use of exogenous steroids). However, the term Cushing’s disease is strictly used to describe Cushing’s syndrome as a result of an ACTH-producing pituitary tumour, or adenoma.\nAn overproduction of aldosterone from the zona glomerulosa of the adrenal cortex, as a result of a functioning adenoma, is known as Conn’s syndrome. The overproduction of aldosterone leads to increased excretion of potassium and hydrogen ions from the distal convoluted tubule and collecting ducts of the kidney, resulting in a hypokalaemic metabolic alkalosis.\nAdrenal insufficiency (also known as Addison’s disease) results in decreased pro-duction of glucocorticoids and mineralocorticoids from the adrenal cortex. It is most commonly a result of destruction of the adrenal cortex by autoimmune adre-nalitis. Decreased mineralocorticoid activity results in sodium loss and decreased\npotassium excretion, with consequent hyperkalaemia, hyponatraemia, volume depletion, and hypotension. Hypoglycaemia may occasionally occur as a result of glucocorticoid deficiency and impaired gluconeogenesis. Stresses such as infec-tions, trauma, or surgery may precipitate a life-threatening adrenal crisis, which may prove fatal unless corticosteroid therapy is begun immediately.\nCongenital adrenal hyperplasia (or adrenogenital syndrome) represents a group of autosomal recessive, inherited metabolic disorders characterized by a deficiency in a particular enzyme involved in the biosynthesis of cortical steroids, particularly cortisol and aldosterone. 21-hydroxylase deficiency accounts for 90 per cent of cases. Steroidogenesis is then channelled into other pathways leading to increased production of androgens, leading to virilization in females and genital enlargement and/or precocious puberty in males. Simultaneously, the deficiency of cortisol results in increased secretion of ACTH, resulting in adrenal hyperplasia. Impaired aldosterone secretion leads to salt wasting. Patients are treated with exogenous ste-roids which, in addition to providing adequate levels of glucocorticoids, suppress ACTH levels and thus decrease the synthesis of the steroid hormones responsible for many of the clinical abnormalities.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Hard",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 CAH: When your adrenals can't make salt, they make sex instead!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is E. Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (CAH), also known as adrenogenital syndrome, is characterized by enzyme deficiencies leading to virilization due to excess androgen production and salt wasting from impaired aldosterone synthesis. This option accurately describes the key clinical features of CAH.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nCAH is an autosomal recessive disorder, most commonly due to 21-hydroxylase deficiency, which impairs the synthesis of cortisol and aldosterone. The lack of cortisol leads to increased ACTH secretion, causing adrenal hyperplasia and shunting of steroid precursors towards androgen production, resulting in virilization. Simultaneously, impaired aldosterone synthesis leads to renal salt wasting, manifesting as hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypovolemia. This complex interplay of hormonal imbalances defines the syndrome.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Adrenal insufficiency (Addison's disease) results in decreased mineralocorticoids, leading to sodium loss and decreased potassium excretion, causing hyponatremia and hyperkalemia, not hypokalemia and hypernatremia.\nOption B (Incorrect): Conn's syndrome (primary hyperaldosteronism) involves excessive aldosterone, which promotes potassium excretion, leading to hypokalemia, not hyperkalemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cushing's disease is specifically caused by an ACTH-producing pituitary tumor. A cortisol-producing tumor of the adrenal cortex causes Cushing's syndrome, not Cushing's disease.\nOption D (Incorrect): Pheochromocytoma is a tumor of the adrenal medulla that oversecretes catecholamines (adrenaline, noradrenaline), not cortisol.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Adrenal Disorder | Primary Hormone Imbalance | Key Clinical/Electrolyte Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Addison's Disease** | Decreased Cortisol & Aldosterone | Hyponatremia, Hyperkalemia, Hypotension, Hypoglycemia |\n| **Conn's Syndrome** | Increased Aldosterone | Hypokalemia, Hypertension, Metabolic Alkalosis |\n| **Cushing's Disease** | Increased ACTH -> Increased Cortisol | Hyperglycemia, Central Obesity, Hypertension, Hypokalemia |\n| **Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia (CAH)** | Decreased Cortisol & Aldosterone, Increased Androgens | Virilization, Salt Wasting (Hyponatremia, Hyperkalemia), Hypotension |\n| **Pheochromocytoma** | Increased Catecholamines | Paroxysmal Hypertension, Tachycardia, Headaches, Sweating |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Adrenal cortex makes sugar, salt, sex; medulla makes stress hormones.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, congenital adrenal hyperplasia often presents with bilateral adrenal enlargement or hyperplasia. Intraoperatively, the adrenal glands may appear diffusely hyperplastic rather than having a discrete tumor.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia (2018) recommends lifelong glucocorticoid replacement and monitoring for virilization and salt-wasting crises.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Adrenal insufficiency results in hypokalaemia and hypernatraemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Conn’s syndrome results in hyperkalaemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Cushing’s disease is due to a cortisol-producing tumour of the adrenal cort | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Pheochromocytoma is due to oversecretion of cortisol by a tumour of the adr | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (adrenogenital syndrome) results in viriliza | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) E: Congenital adrenal hyperplasia (adrenogenital syndrome) results in viril-ization and salt wasting** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
  "verified_answer": "E"
