  "question": "Which of the following regarding local anaesthetics is true?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Cocaine is an amide",
    "B": "Addition of adrenaline increases systemic absorption of the local anaesthetic",
    "C": "One of the first signs of toxicity is perioral paraesthesia",
    "D": "They work by blocking potassium channels in the nerve endings",
    "E": "They inhibit the propagation of impulses in Aß fibres first"
  },
  "answer": "C) C: One of the first signs of toxicity is perioral paraesthesia\nTwo separate classes of local anaesthetics exist: amides and esters. Amides account for the majority of local anaesthetics in clinical use, although cocaine is an ester. Local anaesthetics work by blocking sodium channels. This prevents depolarization and thereby propagation of pain impulses along the nerve.\nLocal anaesthetics tend to block the smaller fibres before the larger ones; that is the smaller pain fibres are blocked first (Ad and C fibres) with sparing of the larger neurones such as the motor fibres.\nThe addition of adrenaline to local anaesthetic has three effects. First, it prevents bleeding by a direct effect of adrenaline on the local vasculature causing vaso-constriction. Second, by way of vasoconstriction it prevents systemic absorption of the local anaesthetic thereby preventing toxicity/side effects and increasing the local duration of action. Third, by preventing systemic absorption it allows larger doses to be used than would otherwise be allowed in the absence of adren-aline. However, because of this ‘vasoconstrictive effect’, adrenaline must never be used on pedicles that contain an end artery (e.g., digits, nose tips, earlobe, penis) where ischaemic necrosis may result.\nIt is important that the maximum dose of local anaesthetic not be exceeded, otherwise the consequences may be lethal. This is because local anaesthetics are cardiotoxic by way of blocking sodium channels and interfering with cardiac conduction. One of the earliest and reliable signs of systemic toxicity is perioral tingling. This may be followed by cardiovascular collapse and death.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 LA toxicity: Tingling lips, then trouble trips!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nOption C is correct because perioral paraesthesia is a classic and early indicator of local anaesthetic systemic toxicity. This symptom arises from the local anaesthetic's effect on sodium channels in the central nervous system, signaling impending cardiotoxicity.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nLocal anaesthetics exert their effect by reversibly blocking voltage-gated sodium channels, thereby preventing the influx of sodium ions required for nerve impulse propagation. When systemic absorption exceeds safe limits, these agents can affect the central nervous system and cardiovascular system. Early CNS signs, such as perioral paraesthesia or tingling, are crucial warning signs because the brain is highly sensitive to these effects. Recognizing these initial symptoms allows for timely intervention before more severe and potentially lethal cardiovascular collapse occurs, which is a direct consequence of sodium channel blockade in cardiac tissue.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cocaine is an ester local anaesthetic, not an amide. Amides and esters are the two main chemical classes of local anaesthetics, differing in their metabolism and allergic potential.\nOption B (Incorrect): Adrenaline causes vasoconstriction, which significantly *decreases* the systemic absorption of local anaesthetics, thereby prolonging their local effect and reducing systemic toxicity.\nOption D (Incorrect): Local anaesthetics work by blocking *sodium* channels, not potassium channels, to prevent nerve depolarization and impulse propagation.\nOption E (Incorrect): Local anaesthetics preferentially block smaller, unmyelinated or lightly myelinated nerve fibres first, such as Aδ and C fibres (pain and temperature), before affecting larger Aβ (touch, pressure) or motor fibres.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Amide Local Anaesthetics | Ester Local Anaesthetics |\n|---|---|---|\n| Chemical Structure | Amide linkage | Ester linkage |\n| Metabolism | Hepatic (CYP450) | Plasma pseudocholinesterase |\n| Allergic Potential | Low (rare) | Higher (due to PABA metabolite) |\n| Examples | Lidocaine, Bupivacaine, Ropivacaine | Procaine, Tetracaine, Cocaine |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Perioral tingling after LA? Think toxicity, act fast!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, observe for patient agitation, perioral tingling, or metallic taste after local anaesthetic injection, as these are early signs of systemic toxicity requiring immediate attention.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Regional Anesthesia and Pain Medicine (ASRA) Guidelines for Local Anesthetic Systemic Toxicity (LAST) (2020) recommend immediate administration of lipid emulsion therapy for severe LAST.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cocaine is an amide | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Addition of adrenaline increases systemic absorption of the local anaesthet | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | One of the first signs of toxicity is perioral paraesthesia | ✅ Correct |\n| D | They work by blocking potassium channels in the nerve endings | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | They inhibit the propagation of impulses in Aß fibres first | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) C: One of the first signs of toxicity is perioral paraesthesia\nTwo separate classes of local anaesth** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
