  "question": "A surgeon’s finger is placed in the epiploic foramen of Winslow. The superior margin is:",
  "options": {
    "A": "Common bile duct",
    "B": "First part of the duodenum",
    "C": "Head of pancreas",
    "D": "Hepatic veins",
    "E": "Caudate lobe of the liver"
  },
  "answer": "E) E: Caudate lobe of the liver\nThe greater sac communicates with the lesser sac through the epiploic foramen of Winslow. The superior boundary is the caudate lobe of the liver. The common bile duct lies in the free edge of the lesser omentum, that forms the anterior boundary. The first part of the duodenum is the inferior boundary. The posterior boundary is the inferior vena cava.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Easy",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Know your foramen boundaries, or you'll be lost in the lesser sac!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the caudate lobe of the liver as the superior boundary of the epiploic foramen of Winslow. This anatomical landmark is crucial for understanding access to the lesser sac and its surrounding structures.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe epiploic foramen (of Winslow) is a critical communication pathway between the greater and lesser sacs of the peritoneum. Its precise boundaries are essential for surgeons, particularly during procedures involving the liver, gallbladder, or pancreas. The caudate lobe of the liver, specifically its inferior aspect, forms the superior margin of this foramen. Understanding these boundaries allows for safe surgical access, for example, to drain a pancreatic pseudocyst or explore the lesser sac for pathology, while avoiding injury to vital structures like the portal triad anteriorly or the IVC posteriorly.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): The common bile duct is part of the portal triad, which lies within the free edge of the lesser omentum, forming the anterior boundary of the epiploic foramen, not the superior.\nOption B (Incorrect): The first part of the duodenum forms the inferior boundary of the epiploic foramen, not the superior.\nOption C (Incorrect): The head of the pancreas is located posterior to the lesser sac and inferior to the epiploic foramen, but does not directly form one of its boundaries.\nOption D (Incorrect): Hepatic veins drain into the inferior vena cava superiorly, but do not directly form a boundary of the epiploic foramen.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Boundary | Structure |\n| :------- | :-------- |\n| Anterior | Free edge of lesser omentum (containing portal triad: common bile duct, hepatic artery, portal vein) |\n| Posterior | Inferior vena cava (covered by parietal peritoneum) |\n| Superior | Caudate lobe of the liver |\n| Inferior | First part of the duodenum |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Epiploic foramen boundaries: Caudate superior, Duodenum inferior, Portal triad anterior, IVC posterior.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a surgeon can palpate the epiploic foramen by inserting a finger posterior to the free edge of the lesser omentum (containing the portal triad) and anterior to the inferior vena cava. On cross-sectional imaging (CT), the foramen appears as a narrow communication between the greater and lesser sacs, identifiable by these surrounding structures.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThis is fundamental surgical anatomy, not typically addressed by specific society guidelines. However, mastery of such anatomical landmarks is implicitly recommended by all major surgical bodies (e.g., American College of Surgeons, Royal College of Surgeons) as foundational for safe and effective surgical practice.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Common bile duct | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | First part of the duodenum | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Head of pancreas | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hepatic veins | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Caudate lobe of the liver | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: E) E: Caudate lobe of the liver\nThe greater sac communicates with the lesser sac through the epiploic f** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
