  "question": "Which femoral fracture is at risk of developing avascular necrosis?",
  "options": {
    "A": "Subcapital neck fracture",
    "B": "Intertrochanteric fracture",
    "C": "Subtrochanteric fracture",
    "D": "Spiral shaft fracture",
    "E": "Medial condylar fracture"
  },
  "answer": "A) A: Subcapital neck fracture\nIntracapsular femoral neck fractures are at risk of avascular necrosis if left untreated due to interruption of the blood supply that runs from a distal to proximal direction.",
  "chapter": "General Surgery",
  "specialty": "General Surgery",
  "difficulty": "Medium",
  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Subcapital: Severed supply, dead head. Act fast!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A: Subcapital neck fracture. This fracture type is uniquely susceptible to avascular necrosis (AVN) due to its intracapsular location, which directly compromises the primary blood supply to the femoral head.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe femoral head receives its blood supply predominantly from the medial and lateral circumflex femoral arteries, which give rise to ascending cervical (retinacular) vessels. These vessels run along the femoral neck within the joint capsule. A subcapital fracture, occurring just below the femoral head, often severs these critical retinacular vessels, particularly the superior and inferior groups, leading to ischemia of the femoral head. The intracapsular hematoma also contributes to increased intra-articular pressure, further impeding blood flow.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Intertrochanteric fractures are extracapsular and occur distal to the retinacular vessels, thus preserving the blood supply to the femoral head and carrying a very low risk of AVN.\nOption C (Incorrect): Subtrochanteric fractures are also extracapsular and occur well below the femoral neck, posing no significant risk to the femoral head's blood supply.\nOption D (Incorrect): Spiral shaft fractures involve the diaphysis of the femur and do not compromise the blood supply to the femoral head, which is supplied by the circumflex arteries.\nOption E (Incorrect): Medial condylar fractures are located in the distal femur and have no bearing on the blood supply to the proximal femoral head.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Fracture Type | Location | AVN Risk | Management Consideration |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Subcapital Neck | Intracapsular | High | Urgent reduction/fixation or arthroplasty |\n| Intertrochanteric | Extracapsular | Low | Internal fixation (e.g., IMN, DHS) |\n| Subtrochanteric | Extracapsular | Low | Internal fixation (e.g., IMN) |\n| Femoral Shaft | Diaphyseal | Very Low | Internal fixation (e.g., IMN) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Intracapsular femoral neck fractures = high AVN risk. Extracapsular = low AVN risk.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn X-ray, a subcapital fracture shows a break just below the femoral head. Intraoperatively, a non-bleeding femoral head fragment after reduction and drilling indicates compromised vascularity, often necessitating arthroplasty.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Hip Fractures in Adults (2020) recommends urgent surgical treatment for femoral neck fractures to reduce the risk of AVN and nonunion.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Subcapital neck fracture | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Intertrochanteric fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Subtrochanteric fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Spiral shaft fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Medial condylar fracture | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A: Subcapital neck fracture\nIntracapsular femoral neck fractures are at risk of avascular necrosis i** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
