  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 SITS muscles keep your shoulder in its place!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is D: Infraspinatus. This muscle is one of the four muscles that comprise the rotator cuff, essential for shoulder stability and a wide range of motion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe rotator cuff is a critical group of four muscles and their tendons (Supraspinatus, Infraspinatus, Teres Minor, Subscapularis – often remembered by the acronym SITS) that surround the glenohumeral joint. These muscles originate from the scapula and insert onto the humerus, forming a 'cuff' that provides dynamic stability to the shoulder joint. Their coordinated action is crucial for abduction, internal rotation, and external rotation of the arm, allowing for complex movements and preventing dislocation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Latissimus dorsi is a large back muscle involved in adduction, extension, and internal rotation of the arm, but it is not part of the rotator cuff.\nOption B (Incorrect): Rhomboid major retracts and rotates the scapula, and is not directly involved in glenohumeral joint rotation as a rotator cuff muscle.\nOption C (Incorrect): Serratus anterior protracts and rotates the scapula, often called the 'boxer's muscle,' but it is not a rotator cuff muscle.\nOption E (Incorrect): Deltoid is the primary abductor of the arm and a powerful shoulder muscle, but it is superficial to the rotator cuff and not considered part of it.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Muscle | Rotator Cuff? | Primary Action | Innervation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Supraspinatus | Yes | Abduction (first 15-30 deg) | Suprascapular nerve |\n| Infraspinatus | Yes | External Rotation | Suprascapular nerve |\n| Subscapularis | Yes | Internal Rotation | Upper and Lower Subscapular nerves |\n| Teres Minor | Yes | External Rotation | Axillary nerve |\n| Deltoid | No | Abduction, Flexion, Extension | Axillary nerve |\n| Latissimus Dorsi | No | Adduction, Extension, Internal Rotation | Thoracodorsal nerve |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Remember SITS: Supraspinatus, Infraspinatus, Teres Minor, Subscapularis are the rotator cuff.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn MRI, rotator cuff tears appear as high signal intensity within the tendon on T2-weighted images, indicating fluid or discontinuity. Intraoperatively, tears are visualized as defects in the tendon, often requiring repair with sutures and anchors.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Academy of Orthopaedic Surgeons (AAOS) Clinical Practice Guideline for the Treatment of Rotator Cuff Tears (2019). Recommends non-operative management as initial treatment for most partial-thickness tears and some full-thickness tears, with surgery reserved for failed conservative treatment or acute, traumatic full-thickness tears.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Latissimus dorsi | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Rhomboid major | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Serratus anterior | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Infraspinatus | ✅ Correct |\n| E | Deltoid | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) D: Infraspinatus\nThe rotator cuff muscles/tendons are: supraspinatus, infraspinatus, subscapularis, ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
