  "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Bony bumps on fingers? Think OA, not RA!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Osteoarthritis. Heberden's and Bouchard's nodes are pathognomonic clinical signs of osteoarthritis, representing osteophyte formation at specific interphalangeal joints.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHeberden's nodes are bony enlargements at the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joints, while Bouchard's nodes are similar enlargements at the proximal interphalangeal (PIP) joints. These nodes are formed by the proliferation of new bone (osteophytes) at the joint margins, a hallmark of degenerative joint disease. This contrasts sharply with inflammatory arthritides, which typically cause erosions and synovitis rather than osteophyte formation.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Rheumatoid arthritis primarily affects the metacarpophalangeal (MCP) and PIP joints symmetrically, causing synovitis, erosions, and ulnar deviation, but not Heberden's or Bouchard's nodes.\nOption C (Incorrect): Psoriatic arthritis can affect DIP joints and cause dactylitis and nail changes, but its pathology involves inflammation and erosion, not the classic osteophytic nodes of OA.\nOption D (Incorrect): Crystal arthritis, such as gout, involves acute inflammatory attacks due to crystal deposition, often leading to tophi and erosions, but not Heberden's or Bouchard's nodes.\nOption E (Incorrect): Septic arthritis is an acute bacterial infection of a joint, characterized by severe pain, swelling, and fever, and does not involve chronic osteophyte formation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Osteoarthritis | Rheumatoid Arthritis | Psoriatic Arthritis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Joint Involvement | DIP, PIP, CMC of thumb, knee, hip, spine | MCP, PIP, wrist, MTP, symmetric | DIP, PIP, spine, sacroiliac, asymmetric |\n| Nodes/Erosions | Heberden's (DIP), Bouchard's (PIP) nodes (osteophytes) | Erosions, synovitis, ulnar deviation | Erosions, dactylitis, nail changes |\n| Systemic Features | None | Fatigue, fever, rheumatoid nodules | Psoriasis, enthesitis, uveitis |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Heberden's (DIP) and Bouchard's (PIP) nodes = Osteoarthritis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn plain radiographs, Heberden's and Bouchard's nodes appear as marginal osteophytes at the DIP and PIP joints, respectively, often accompanied by joint space narrowing and subchondral sclerosis.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Rheumatology (ACR) 2019 Guideline for the Management of Osteoarthritis of the Hand, Hip, and Knee. It recommends non-pharmacologic and pharmacologic interventions for symptom management.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Osteoarthritis | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Rheumatoid arthritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Psoriatic arthritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Crystal arthritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| E | Septic arthritis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) A: Osteoarthritis\nHeberden and Bouchard’s nodes form secondary to marginal osteophytes at the distal** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: SBAs for the MRCS Part A**\n",
